<FIRST>u w AM-Sandinista-ContraTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0791-a0722 11-16
0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sandinista-Contra Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0791-a0722,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads with parties saying talks still deadlocked, editing changes
thruout. Stands for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Nicaraguan government and
the Contra rebels met for four hours Thursday night and were unable
to narrow their differences on terms for restoring a cease fire.
   Spokesmen for both sides said the principal sticking point was
the refusal by the Contras to agree to a Sandinista demand for the
withdrawal of rebel forces inside Nicaragua to base camps in
Honduras.
   The Sandinistas are linking their consent to a cease fire to a
rebel withdrawal while the Contras are insisting on maintaining
their present positions once a truce goes into effect.
   One positive sign after the talks recessed was the absence of
kind of strident criticism of each other's position that
characterized their public comments 24 hours earlier.
   The talks began on Nov. 9 and will resume Friday morning.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, an official ``witness'' to the
discussions, left the talks Wednesday night to keep an appointment
elsewhere. He said he rejoined the negotiations Thursday night on
orders from the Holy See. After his departure Wednesday, the
atmosphere for the discusssions deteriorated markedly.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros told reporters he had noted a
``hardening'' of the government's position on the cease-fire.
   The chief rebel negotiator, Col. Enrique Bermudez, said the
Sandinistas showed no interest in agreeing to a cease-fire as a
first step in a confidence building process.
   His Sandinista counterpart, Vice-Foreign Minister Victor Hugo
Tinoco, said that for a ``real and effective cease-fire to take
place, the Contras should go back to their camps in Honduras.''
   There are an estimated 5,000 rebels inside Nicaraguan territory.
   Earlier, Bermudez said that once a cease-fire was agreed to,
details of the duties and makeup of a verification commission to
monitor compliance could be worked out.
   The talks are being mediated by officials from the United
Nations and the Organization of American States, one of whom said
after the 10 p.m. recess that the negotiations were ``inching
along.''
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega suspended the cease-fire 17
days ago, citing what he said were repeated terrorist activities by
the Contra forces.
   Reviving the truce is considered an important goal because
national elections are set for Nicaragua on Feb. 25.
   The Contra delegation stunned the Sandinistas Wednesday night
when Bermudez called for a weeklong recess in the talks just when
government negotiators said an agreement appeared to be within
reach.
   Tinoco told a news conference Thursday that the rebel action
``shows clearly the Contras have no interest in peace, no interest
in a cease-fire, no interest in demobilization.''
   But Matamoros denied that significant progress had been made
Wednesday, asserting that statements to the contrary ``were not
accurate'' and that the Sandinista negotiators showed a lack of
``flexibility'' in the discussions.
   The Contras proposed on Wednesday that the talks be reconvened
in a week, possibly in Guatemala, but Bermudez seemed to back away
from that stand Thursday by calling for a resumption of the talks
in early evening.
</TEXT>
