<FIRST>u w AM-CivilRightsCommission     11-16 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights Commission,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Extension For civil Rights Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate late Thursday approved a 22-month
extension of the U.S. Civil Rights Commission that would head off
the panel's automatic demise at the end of this month.
   The measure now goes back to the House, which had passed a
six-month extension a day earlier and was ready to accept the
longer-term bill, said a spokesman for Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who
worked out the compromise.
   The spokesman, David Carle, said the 22-month extension was a
middle ground between Democrats who wanted only a short-term
measure while they waited to see whom President Bush appoints to
the panel in the coming weeks and the White House's desire for a
six-year bill.
   The commission won praise in the 1960s for holding hearings
across the South and recommending bold civil rights legislation.
But during the Reagan administration its effectiveness has eroded
and the panel has been consumed by internal bickering. Congress has
slashed funding for the commission.
</TEXT>
