<FIRST>r w PM-RuralVeterans     11-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Veterans,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Derwinski Pledges to Keep VA Hospitals Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans Secretary Edward J. Derwinski is
pledging to keep rural VA hospitals open, a promise lawmakers say
they welcome but contend doesn't address all the health-care
problems for veterans who live in sparsely populated areas.
   ``I have no intention of closing and no intention of making
changes that in any way would diminish hospital care in rural
areas,'' Derwinski told the Senate Veterans Affairs Committee.
``These kinds of locations must stay.''
   Derwinski referred specifically to hospitals in Fargo, N.D., Hot
Springs, S.D., Martinsburg, W.Va., Miles City, Mont., Prescott,
Ariz., and Walla Walla, Wash.
   Sen. Max Baucus, a Montana Democrat, complained at Wednesday's
hearing that most Washington policy-makers lacked a sensitivity to
the vast distances that people in the West must travel for health
care.
   Sen. Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., complained that many rural
veterans were being denied the health care to which they are
accustomed. VA facilities, he said, have limited their treatment in
the last five years to only the poorest veterans and those with
service-connected disabilities.
   ``We made a decision retroactively affecting these veterans that
is just a disaster for these veterans,'' said Daschle, adding that
most are too old to enter private insurance programs.
   ``There are veterans who are being turned away and they are
getting sicker or dying as a result,'' he said.
   Dr. Daniel Winship of the VA's medical division said there was
no policy decision to cut the so-called Category B and C patients.
He said that the demand for care by Category A patients has
``virtually consumed'' the VA's resources.
   Health care for rural veterans, like rural health care in
general, suffers from a shortage of doctors and nurses, difficult
access to facilities and a lack of resources because most rural
hospitals are not affiliated with medical schools.
   The American Legion says that 95 percent of all veterans live
within a 100-mile radius of the nearest VA facility, but 83 percent
of the veterans served by the Miles City, Mont., hospital live more
than 100 miles from it.
   Baucus noted that Los Angeles has nine centers compared with two
in Montana, and Derwinski said in his native Chicago three
hospitals were within six miles of one another.
</TEXT>
