<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Elderly     11-16 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Elderly,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Are Silent Casualties in Drug War, Panel Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-year-old Evelyn Blackwell is one of
few elderly residents in her neighborhood who dares to stand up to
the drug dealers.
   ``We've got senior citizens who are afraid in their own homes
and afraid to come out,'' the longtime Washington resident said
Wednesday.
   Miami's Rosemary Dalton, 65, said seniors in her public housing
project are ``afraid and sick and tired'' of the dope dealers.
   ``You can smell the ether and they make so much noise you can't
sleep,'' Dalton said.
   Elsie Taylor-Jordan of Alexandria, Va., at 63 is raising her
1{-year-old great-granddaughter, Ashley, abandoned by the baby's
drug-addicted mother.
   ``Being able to use drugs whenever she wanted was more important
than caring for her child,'' Taylor-Jordan said.
   America's elderly are silent casualties in the nation's drug
war, isolated in crack-infested neighborhoods, abused by violent
addicts and left to rear babies abandoned by drug-abusing parents,
a Senate committee was told.
   Instead of finding refuge in their families, many seniors suffer
drug-related violence at home at the hands of addicted relatives
and neighbors, Brooklyn District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman told
the Special Committee on Aging.
   ``No bond of love can stand in the way of crack,'' Holtzman
testified. ``Hundreds, even thousands of older New Yorkers are now
vulnerable to murder, to assault by their children, grandchildren
or great-grandchildren desperate for their next fix of crack.''
   Holtzman told of one case in which a Brooklyn woman suffocated
after her son tied her to a bed and set the room on fire because
she refused to give him money for crack.
   Sgt. Robert Crawford of the Oakland Police Department in
California said some elderly residents lose control of their homes
when adult children or grandchildren turn the property into a haven
for crack users.
   ``Many times the elderly person will ignore the activity and
simply hide in a back bedroom,'' Crawford said. ``When the police
raids come he or she is left behind until the arrestee returns
after posting bail or being released because of overcrowded jails.
The process then repeats itself.''
   Committee Chairman David Pryor, D-Ark., said the extent to which
the elderly are being victimized by the drug crisis is difficult to
measure because many keep silent due to a ``sense of fear and
shame.''
   ``In preparing for this hearing, we heard plenty of stories
about abuse of the elderly as a result of drugs _ yet it was
virtually impossible to find someone willing to make their story
public,'' Pryor said.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., said his staff had a similar experience
trying to find public witnesses from among elderly residents of a
Pennsylvania housing project where drug problems made life ``hell
in a high-rise.''
   ``They were afraid of reprisals, they were afraid of telling the
truth, they didn't want the drug dealers to know,'' Heinz said.
   Heinz urged swift approval of legislation he has proposed to
expedite the eviction of drug dealers from public housing projects.
Pryor said that as Congress puts more money into fighting drugs,
``we must ensure that the often hidden victims of drug abuse are
not forgotten.''
   Holtzman said the popularity of crack has been a major reason
for an upturn in violence against the elderly. She said her office
handled 400 percent more elderly abuse cases in 1988 than in 1986,
the year that crack use took off.
   Many more cases go unreported because parents and grandparents
often are ``deeply ashamed about the violence visited upon them by
their offspring'' or afraid of retaliation if they turn someone in,
Holtzman said.
   States need massive new resources for local law enforcement,
drug treatment, education and prevention, and services for drug
abusers and victims, Holtzman said.
   ``Although both the president and Congress have been aware of
the enormity of America's drug crisis and proclaimed a war, they
have not funded one,'' she said.
</TEXT>
