<FIRST>r w PM-Education-RedTape     11-16 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education-Red Tape,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Hearing Focuses on School Flexibility</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Hearing scheduled 9:30 a.m. EST; will be led</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill that would allow schools more
flexibility in the use of federal education dollars in exchange for
improving student performance gets a hearing today, but one critic
is calling the legislation ``nonsense.''
   ``I don't like it,'' Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the
House Education and Labor Committee, told reporters at the National
Press Club this week.
   ``I think it's nonsense. ... It's part of deregulation. But Mr.
Smith is very sincere about it. I see nothing wrong with having the
hearing.''
   The bill, introduced by Rep. Peter Smith, R-Vt., would create a
voluntary program allowing local schools more flexibility in the
use of federal education dollars in exchange for improving student
performance. Participation in the program would be canceled if
student achievements worsen within two years.
   Among the scheduled witnesses are New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean;
Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers;
and Stephanie Robinson of the National Urban League.
   Hawkins contends that a bill signed into law last year addresses
many of the concerns raised in Smith's bill.
   ``Trying new ideas when we already have success seems to be a
foolish waste of money,'' he said.
   Hawkins also complained that President Bush and the nation's
governors failed to specify at a September education summit the
federal regulations that are the most frustrating for educators.
   ``To some extent I'm for simplification of regulations,'' he
said. ``I would hope that this hearing will help ... find out what
they're talking about. The president made a commitment to the
governors that he would sponsor deregulation. Well, obviously they
want to get money with no strings attached. But that doesn't mean
it's good for children.''
   Smith, an educator and former Vermont lieutenant governor,
introduced the bill days before the historic education summit that
concluded with an agreement that national performance goals would
be developed and federal regulations tied to key education programs
would be loosened.
   In a joint statement, Bush and the governors said, ``we want to
swap red tape for results.''
   Smith said the summit gave his bill the impetus it needed.
   ``It's a difference between night and day,'' Smith said in an
interview Wednesday. ``The idea of restructuring is something that
a number of us has been working on for five to six years. It's
bipartisan, but mostly at the gubernatorial and state commission
level. (The summit) propelled the idea onto the national agenda.''
   The bill specifies that the civil rights of students cannot be
infringed in exercising local flexibility with federal dollars _ a
provision Smith said ensures that programs for disadvantaged
students won't be shortchanged.
   Smith said he had gotten positive reaction from many members of
Congress, although the National Education Association is ``more
guarded'' and the National Urban League insists it ``doesn't go far
enough.''
   ``It's a big change,'' he said. ``We're talking about a major
concept on how we relate to schools. It ought to be controversial.
People ought to care deeply about it and ask tough questions about
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
