<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast     11-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Calls on Arabs to Respond to Proposal for Mideast Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir nears
the end of a fast-paced visit, the Bush administration is looking
for a go-ahead on Mideast talks from Egypt and the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``There is a need for us to get a positive response from the
Egyptians for the process to move forward,'' a senior U.S. official
said Wednesday after Shamir concluded back-to-back talks with
President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Before flying to Cincinnati for a reunion with former President
Reagan tonight, Shamir was meeting today with members of the House
Foreign Affairs and the Senate Foreign Relations Committees.
   The 74-year-old prime minister seemed tired and yet upbeat in
summing up his sessions with Bush and Baker at a news conference
late Tuesday.
   ``In principle, I cannot see any deep differences between our
positions and American positions,'' he said. ``It's only a matter
of details.''
   Shamir, whose proposal for talks with Palestinian Arabs had U.S.
support, is seeking assurances the PLO would not get a foot in the
door of the negotiations.
   He said he came away from his talks with Bush and Baker
convinced that ``they will not do anything to force us to sit
together and negotiate with them (the PLO) if we do not want to.''
   Shamir wants to restrict the talks with Palestinians to setting
up an election on the West Bank and Gaza. The winners would
negotiate with Israel a form of limited self-rule for the
Palestinians.
   But, Shamir said, Egypt in behalf of the PLO has tried to
broaden the agenda for the talks to other issues. Referring to the
Egyptian president, he said ``(Hosni) Mubarak now understands it
was a blunder.''
   Earlier, Shamir said ``there are some obstacles that we have to
remove and work out. It will be a long process. It will take time.
It's not easy.''
   The PLO, dealing with the administration through Egypt, has not
given a green light for Palestinians on the West Bank and in Gaza
to meet with Israel to arrange the election.
   Baker said a response from Egypt was essential for the talks to
move ahead.
   Referring to Israel's conditional acceptance of his plan for the
talks, Baker said, ``I hope we will soon be receiving a similar
response from Egypt.''
   Baker and Shamir said they made progress toward negotiations,
but a senior U.S. official who requested anonymity said, ``I can't
tell you that we have sorted out specific details.''
   Before Shamir called on Bush, there were reports of U.S.
impatience with Israel for seeking various assurances on the
discussions.
   After the session, Shamir and U.S. officials struck a friendly
stance.
   ``There is no more tension,'' Shamir said. He also told
reporters, ``I think we made some progress.''
   Marlin Fitzwater, the presidential spokesman, said Bush was not
frustrated with Shamir over the delay in getting to the table.
   ``It's important not to become impatient when you're dealing
with the Middle East,'' Fitzwater said. ``Two thousand years is the
normal wait for things to happen.''
   Bush also took up two other touchy issues with Shamir _ Israel's
military cooperation with South Africa and an expansion of Jewish
settlements on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Last week, a U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said there
was ``very great concern'' that Israel may have provided U.S.
technology to South Africa for a missile test last summer.
   And on Tuesday, Margaret D. Tutwiler, the State Department
spokeswoman, denounced as an obstacle to peace a planned Israeli
settlement in northern Gaza.
   Shamir has insisted on the right of Jews to live anywhere.
   Asked about Israel's South African connection, he said military
contracts had been ``reduced to the greatest extent'' in the past
2{ years.
   ``There is no question about it,'' Shamir said. ``We are not
busy with any nuclear arms.''
</TEXT>
