<FIRST>r w PM-US-EasternEurope     11-16 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Eastern Europe,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: No One Should Stand in Way of Change in East Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says no government should stand
in the way of changes sweeping Eastern Europe, but promises that
next month's summit with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will
not be used ``to negotiate the future of Europe.''
   Bush made his statement Wednesday after Gorbachev reaffirmed his
firm opposition to German reunification despite the opening of the
Berlin Wall.
   Gorbachev said in Moscow the existence of two Germanys ``has
been recognized by the world community'' since the end of World War
II and that even talk about reunification constitutes interference
in the affairs of the two countries.
   Bush, in a speech to a convention of the AFL-CIO, reiterated his
call for a Europe ``whole and free'' but did not directly call for
a reunified Germany, which U.S. policy envisions.
   Before an audience that included Solidarity leader Lech Walesa,
Bush said he watched in awe last week as Berliners danced atop the
Berlin Wall.
   He said he had expected to see the wall opened during his
lifetime and hoped it would happen during his presidency.
   ``Change has a way of sweeping through like a fast-moving
train,'' Bush said. ``And no one and no government should stand in
its way.''
   While praising the easing of travel restrictions in
Czechoslovakia, Bush said ``freedom of travel is not enough. Only
free and unfettered elections can satisfy the yearnings of a free
people.''
   Bush and Gorbachev will meet Dec. 2 and 3 on ships in the
Mediterranean off the coast of Malta. The president then may go on
to Brussels to report to NATO allies on the trip.
   The president said he and Gorbachev ``are not meeting to
negotiate the future of Europe.
   ``The peoples of Eastern Europe are speaking their own minds
about that future and they are calling for democracy, freedom of
the press and of conscience, the right of the governed to choose
their leaders,'' Bush said.
   The agenda of the next month's summit and expectations of any
accomplishments appear to be shifting as the meeting approaches.
   Bush originally said the meeting would not be an arms-control
summit, but the White House said Wednesday that arms negotiations
will be discussed.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush and
Gorbachev likely would reach ``a consensus in their thinking'' for
progress to reduce strategic nuclear forces and conventional arms
in Europe. However, he said it was ``quite doubtful'' that any
papers would be signed.
   The press spokesman acknowledged that Washington and Moscow were
sparring over the summit's outcome.
   He said the Soviets have a tendency ``to build expectations
before a summit, and we have a tendency to play them down.
   ``I suspect the reality is somewhere in the middle,'' he said.
``But I would urge you to discount theirs a little bit on the top
side.''
</TEXT>
