<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CivilRights     11-16 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extension of Embattled Civil Rights Panel OK'd by House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to extend the life of the embattled U.S.
Civil Rights Commission for six months are on their way to the
Senate after winning approval from the House.
   The bill approved Wednesday was designed to keep the commission
from automatically going out of business at the end of the month
but keep it on the front burner in view of its recent problems. The
vote was 278-135.
   Approval of the stopgap measure by the full House came a day
after it emerged from the Judiciary Committee amid concerns that
action was necessary to reconstitute the commission and end its
internal strife.
   An alternative GOP plan would have deliberately put the
commission out of business _ for one day only _ to give President
Bush a chance to dump the current members. It then would have been
reconstituted for six years.
   Democrats said it would be unwise to go ahead with a six-year
bill with lawmakers about to wrap up their business and go home
until after the holidays.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., said he initially had favored a
one-year measure but bowed to the belief of Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., that six months was time enough to resolve the issue.
   In the 1960s, civil rights forces hailed the commission's
hearings across the South, its ringing reports on racial injustice
and bold legislative proposals. Since 1983, however, the atmosphere
has soured and both parties in Congress have combined to slash the
panel's funding.
   Controversy has focused on former Chairman William B. Allen, who
remains a member of the commission. He recently came under fire
after delivering to a conservative group a speech titled: ``Blacks?
Animals? Homosexuals? What is a Minority?''
   The commission, in a 6-1 vote, called the speech ``thoughtless,
disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory.'' Allen, who is black,
calls himself the only conservative on the panel and says he does
``not believe in coddling people.''
   Lawmakers say he's not alone in fanning the controversy and that
at least one other member of the commission has made ``bizarre''
remarks.
</TEXT>
