<FIRST>u a AM-Noriega-Covert     11-16 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noriega-Covert,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Reportedly OKs Covert Overthrow of Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has launched a covert
effort to overthrow Panama's Gen. Manuel A. Noriega, with the
acquiescence of the Senate and House intelligence committees, a
newspaper reported Thursday.
   The CIA has been authorized to spend $3 million initially to
sponsor a coup by recruiting Panamanian military officers or other
dissidents, the Los Angeles Times reported.
   The covert operation has no restrictions beyond an order
prohibiting Noriega's assassination, and the use of U.S. troops
along with other ``high risk'' options are under consideration, the
newspaper said.
   The Times quoted an unidentified source as calling the operation
``an unimpeded effort to try to topple Noriega.''
   ``We're going into it with the understanding that there may be
loss of life, though the effort will be not to kill anyone,'' the
source told the Times.
   A White House press spokesman was not immediately available for
comment on the report.
   The United States has been trying to force Noriega from power
since he was indicted on drug-trafficking charges in February 1988
by federal grand juries in Miami and Tampa, Fla.
   After a coup by members of the Panama Defense Forces on Oct. 3
failed, congressional critics assailed the Bush Administration for
its restrained response to that attempt.
   Bush administration officials outlined the current operation
three weeks ago before the Senate and House intelligence
committees, the Times said. The officials made it clear that the
administration is no longer willing to negotiate an alternative
that would allow Noriega to avoid criminal prosecution in the
United States.
</TEXT>
