<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StelloNomination     11-16 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stello Nomination,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate For Weapons Post Says He's Victim of `Bum Rap'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Hearing scheduled to resume at 2 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's nominee to head the
nation's nuclear arms production says he unavoidably made enemies
during 23 years as a regulator of atomic power, but that charges of
professional misconduct are unfounded.
   ``It's a bum rap,'' Victor Stello Jr. said at his confirmation
hearing Wednesday, acknowledging that his personality played a part
in having gained many enemies.
   ``I say what I think ... I'm aggressive, I'm not a diplomat ...
I can be abrasive,'' he said, adding that he was fully committed to
ensuring safe nuclear operations.
   Stello rebutted several charges raised by Democratic members of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, including that he was too cozy
with the utilities he was responsible for regulating while chief of
staff of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   The committee scheduled a further hearing for this afternoon to
take testimony from individuals who asked to speak either in favor
or against the Stello nomination.
   The committee chairman, Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said a third session
was likely Friday, and that Stello might be asked to return for
additional testimony. That appeared to mean the administration
stood little chance of gaining full Senate confirmation of Stello
before Congress recesses for the year, probably next week.
   Democratic Sens. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and Timothy
Wirth of Colorado told Stello they would vote against his
nomination as assistant energy secretary for defense programs. Sen.
John Glenn of Ohio strongly hinted he would, too.
   Kennedy accused Stello of ``corruption of the processes and
procedures'' of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and said he
``bears a major share of the responsibility'' for an erosion of
public confidence in the regulation of nuclear power.
   ``Few nominees have arrived before this committee with a longer
train of excess baggage than Victor Stello Jr.,'' Kennedy said. ``I
intend to oppose this nomination.''
   Stello has been the NRC's chief of staff, ranking below only the
five commissioners, since 1986. He was nominated for the Energy
Department job July 24.
   If confirmed, Stello would be responsible for nuclear weapons
production, the main activity of the Energy Department. Key
facilities in the weapons complex, which comprises 17 major plants
in 12 states, have been shut down in recent months because of
severe safety, management and environmental problems.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins made an unusual personal plea
on behalf of the nominee, telling the committee he had no
reservations about Stello's fitness to serve.
   ``I am more convinced today than ever before that he is the
right man for the job,'' Watkins said.
   The charges against Stello include allegations that he
improperly advised the Tennessee Valley Authority in 1986 on how to
respond to an NRC investigation of TVA's nuclear program, and that
he authorized cash payments for information from a former utility
worker in 1988 in an effort to undermine an NRC investigator.
   Stello said he could assure the committee that those and other
allegations were groundless.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the ranking Republican on the
committee, said he saw no reason for Congress to question Bush's
judgment in choosing Stello, but several Democrats said many doubts
about Stello's fitness had not been dispelled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
