<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseBudget     11-16 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Budget,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Star Wars Supporters Doubt Its Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional approval of a $305 billion
defense bill that slashes President Bush's request for the
Strategic Defense Initiative has left even the strongest backers of
Star Wars doubting its future.
   ``Why waste money for SDI if it's not the president's intention,
or the Congress' intention, to deploy,'' Sen. Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo., asked Wednesday, shortly before the Senate overwhelmingly
agreed to the fiscal 1990 military bill.
   The legislation, approved 91-8, cuts $1.1 billion from the
president's proposal of $4.9 billion for SDI, about $279 million
less than the fiscal 1989 amount and the first budget reduction in
the program in six years.
   Bush is expected to sign the bill, which trimmed his request for
other major strategic programs such as the MX and Midgetman nuclear
missiles and the B-2 stealth bomber.
   The House, meanwhile, approved by voice vote a companion
military spending bill that provides the money to implement the
policies in the defense legislation.
   The $286 billion spending bill, which goes to the Senate for its
consideration, largely mirrors the defense legislation on funds for
SDI, land-based nuclear missiles and the B-2 bomber.
   The House eliminated a handful of contentious issues, including
an amendment providing House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., with
an Air Force C-20 aircraft at Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland,
ready at his request.
   The substitute amendment allows Foley the use of an Air Force
aircraft when he needs it, consistent with current practice.
   Among the other prickly issues dropped from the bill was an
amendment providing a classified amount of money for the SR-71 spy
plane, a program the administration decided to cancel.
   However, lawmakers may have created more problems when they
eliminated about $90 million earmarked for university projects in
the home districts of House and Senate members.
   The spending bill cuts $400 million from the administration's
request for $1.8 billion for procurement of the Trident 2 missile
and $11 million from the administration's $216 million request for
testing the troubled missile.
   That bill also prohibits spending more than $250 million on the
program until three successful flight tests have occurred. In
August, the weapon suffered its second successive failure in
undersea test firings, exploding seconds after being launched.
   In the Senate, the chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
Democrat Sam Nunn of Georgia, said the defense bill ``continues
strategic modernization at a somewhat slower rate than the
administration sought.''
   But Wallop bemoaned the fate of SDI particularly in light of the
Republican administration's inaction.
   ``I must fault the administration for failing to fight harder
for SDI funding and not sticking to their own pronouncements on the
importance of the program,'' said Wallop, who voted against the
bill.
   Overall, the bills provide $4.3 billion for the B-2, $430
million less than the administration requested for the fiscal year
that began Oct. 1.
   Money is included for two bombers in fiscal 1990, one less than
the administration sought, but adopts Bush's proposal for
components for five bombers in fiscal 1991.
   Approximately $1.1 billion is included for two land-based
nuclear missiles: the multiple-warhead, rail-based MX and the
single-warhead, truck-based Midgetman. The bills trim about $150
million from the administration's request for the two weapons and
includes House language imposing a 50-missile cap on the MX.
   The legislation provides for the Navy's F-14D Tomcat jet fighter
and the AHIP helicopter _ for one more year _ and postpones a
decision on the Marine Corps' V-22 Osprey and the Phoenix missile.
   The bills accept the administration's plan to kill six other
programs, including the SSN-688 submarine, the F-15 aircraft and
the M-88 tank recovery vehicle.
</TEXT>
