<FIRST>r w PM-ForeignAid     11-16 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Aid,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Aid Bill Sidetracked</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just hours after Polish labor leader Lech
Walesa made a passionate plea for U.S. funds, a foreign aid bill
offering the first installment of that help was sidetracked by an
unrelated abortion dispute in the Senate.
   The domestic politics of one of America's most volatile issues
intervened late Wednesday to send the $14.6 billion foreign aid
measure back to the House for further action as Walesa dined with
lawmakers in the Capitol just a few yards from the Senate floor.
   While the bill, which provides military and economic aid in the
coming year to U.S. friends and allies around the globe, still was
expected to pass, further delays could throw prospects for $533
million in aid to Poland and Hungary into doubt for this year.
   Earlier in the day, Walesa appealed in strong terms for U.S.
financial support and investment to keep Poland's dramatic changes
alive. Some lawmakers in the audience sported lapel buttons that
read, ``Make the check to Lech.''
   The issue that delayed the bill was a Senate provision to send
$15 million to the United Nations Population Fund, a family
planning agency that has been barred from receiving U.S. funds for
five years because it operates in China, which has repressive
population control policies.
   Anti-abortion forces object to the money because of China's
one-child-per-family policy, which they say has led to forced
abortions and sterilizations.
   The House had effectively deleted the money a day earlier, but
the Senate voted 52-44 to insist it remain in the bill. Proponents
pointed out that the bill would bar any of the U.S. contribution
from being used in China.
   Another provision added in the Senate on Wednesday also could
cause problems for the bill, a ban on counting illegal aliens in
the upcoming national Census. The measure was pushed by Sen.
Richard Shelby, D-Ala., and approved on a 50-48 vote.
   Throughout the day Wednesday, House and Senate negotiators also
talked informally in an effort to come to agreement on separate
legislation setting the shape and size of an overall three-year aid
package for Poland and Hungary. The Senate had passed a version
totaling $738 million, the House an $838 million bill.
   Both Poland and Hungary have led the way in the political and
economic reform movement sweeping Eastern Europe, and Congress has
sought to encourage the changes with U.S. aid.
   The money bill also remained subject to a veto threat because of
a provision stemming from the Iran-Contra scandal that would bar
use of foreign aid to entice other countries to carry out policies
contrary to U.S. law. The administration believed the language
would tie its hands in dealings with allies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
