<DOCNO> AP891116-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Walesa-Color     11-16 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa-Color,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weary Walesa Leaves Dinner Early</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Walesa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's tiring being the toast of Washington, so
Lech Walesa called it a day early and missed some of the accolades
being heaped upon him.
   Walesa, exhausted after a day in which he made a triumphant
appearance before Congress, abruptly left a dinner in his honor at
the Capitol on Wednesday night, saying he was too tired to continue.
   ``The day has taken some toll and he is tired and he regrets
having to depart,'' said House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash.
   A glittering assembly had gathered in Statuary Hall to hail the
leader of Poland's Solidarity labor union as the hero of the day.
   However, the dinner continued after Walesa left and Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., his voice quavering and his eyes brimming
with tears, expressed the pride he said all Polish-Americans feel
at Walesa's achievements.
   ``Lech Walesa today made a speech that was so simple, so direct,
so honest,'' Rostenkowski said. ``He is a man who says, I know what
freedom is because I haven't had it.''
   Walesa, at a luncheon after his address before Congress,
described his speech simply:
   ``It was too long. I am not a good speaker.''
   Not too long by Senate standards, said Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell of Maine. ``By those standards it was a very short
speech.''
   ``In addition, he had something to say,'' said Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
   Dole said that as Walesa walked into the House chamber he turned
to him and said:
   ``If the lights go out, I can fix them before I give the speech.
I would like you to understand, I really am an electrician; I never
wanted to be a diplomat.''
   He had never understood, he said, ``how much responsibility''
one takes on when one assumes the role of a leader.
   Now, he said, ``I must be what you want me to be.''
   Walesa, who spoke through an interpreter, said he could not
pronounce the names of his hosts.
   But in many cases he was wrong.
   Seated near him were Zbigniew Brzezinski, national security
adviser in the Carter administration; Sen. Frank Murkowski,
R-Alaska; Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., and many other
Polish-Americans of achievement and rank.
   Rostenkowski led a standing ovation on the House floor when
Walesa described Solidarity's long battle for survival and its
eventual triumph and said:
   ``We did not smash a single window pane. But we were stubborn,
very stubborn, ready to suffer. We knew what we wanted. And our
power prevailed in the end.''
   Walesa's speech had personal meaning for many.
   Ms. Mikulski wore her great-grandmother's scarf, hand
embroidered with the arms of Poland, and handed down in her family,
daughter to daughter.
   ``His triumph is the fulfillment of a dream that my family have
had for more than 100 years _ that Poland is free and on the way to
democracy,'' the senator said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
