<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-16 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Closes at Another High, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at
yet another high Thursday, while the dollar edged up against the
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 24.11 points, or 0.07
percent, to close at 35,876.34, the fourth straight record high
since Monday. The index had gained 83.59 points for the previous
record, closing at 35,852.23 Wednesday.
   The dollar ended at 143.85 yen, up 0.48 yen from the previous
day's 143.37-yen finish. The currency started at 143.83 yen in
Tokyo and ranged between 143.75 yen and 144.00 yen.
   The Nikkei's rise followed an overnight gain in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues in New York.
   The index erased some of its gains as the yen's weakness against
the dollar discouraged market players, said Kazuyuki Suzuki, a
dealer with Daiwa Securities Co.
   Other dealers said sales for profit taking by some investors
also helped narrow the index's gains.
   ``Although the index's gain is not that big, trading was pretty
active,'' Suzuki said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar was slowly getting stronger
against the yen as many investors expected the U.S. trade deficit
in September to shrink from the previous month, dealers said.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is to announce its monthly trade
statistics in Washington later Thursday. The figures are seen as a
major economic indicator of the U.S. economy.
   A Bank of Tokyo trader anonymously said market players were
reluctant to make major moves and currency rates moved narrowly
prior to the trade figure announcement.
</TEXT>
