<FIRST>r w PM-Contra-SandinistaTalks 650   11-16 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra-Sandinista Talks, 650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Talks in Disarray; Sandinistas Blame Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of cease-fire talks between
Nicaragua's rival factions is in question today after Sandinista
delegates said the Contra rebels had second thoughts just when an
agreement seemed within reach.
   The key element of an eight-point draft proposal, a copy of
which was obtained by The Associated Press, called for the
withdrawal of 2,000 Contra forces from Nicaragua to rebel camps in
Honduras as part of a cease-fire agreement.
   The proposal was the principal working document of the two sides
as they met Wednesday for the fifth time in seven days in an
attempt to restore the truce President Daniel Ortega suspended Nov.
1.
   After about three hours of discussions, the Contra delegation
stunned the Sandinistas in early evening by asking for a week-long
suspension of the talks.
   ``We had made a lot of progress today,'' said the chief
Sandinista negotiator, Victor Hugo Tinoco. ``It was a total
surprise that they decided to break off the talks.''
   But Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros denied that significant
progress had been made, asserting that statements to the contrary
``were not accurate'' and that the Sandinista negotiators showed a
lack of flexibility in the discussions.
   He defended the call for a recess by saying that after many
hours of talks dating back to last Thursday, a time for
``reflection'' was appropriate.
   After rethinking their earlier proposal for a seven-day recess,
the Contras announced after 11 p.m. that they would return this
morning to discuss next steps with the Sandinistas and with
Organization of American States and United Nations mediators.
   The scene of the talks was an eight-story OAS office building
three blocks from the White House.
   There was a bizarre twist when, according to Tinoco, the Contra
delegation asked for a 30-minute recess to talk things over among
themselves only to disappear for two hours.
   ``We don't know where they are,'' Tinoco told reporters shortly
after 10 p.m. ``They are somewhere in this building.'' He and
fellow delegates then left for their hotel.
   The Contra decision to ask for a week's recess just when the
talks seemed on the verge of success, prompted Sandinista
speculation that a hidden State Department hand had nipped the
proposal in the bud.
   Sandinista partisans prowled stairwells throughout the building
searching for U.S. diplomats but came up empty-handed. The official
U.S. policy is that the State Department gives advice to the
Contras but is not directly involved in the discussions.
   Restoring the cease fire is considered an important goal because
national elections are set for Nicaragua on Feb. 25.
   An American negotiator for the Sandinistas, Paul Reichler,
sounded incredulous when he talked to reporters about the perceived
change of Contra attitudes.
   ``On the verge of reaching an agreement, they're breaking off
the talks,'' he said. ``It does not make sense unless the Contras
do not want an agreement of any kind.''
   He wondered whether the sudden appearance at the talks of Contra
chief of staff Israel Galeano, otherwise known as Comandante
Franklin, was related to the rebel retreat.
   Other key points in the draft proposal included:
   _Verification of the cease fire by a United Nations force
scheduled to take up peacekeeping duties in Central America shortly.
   _A pledge by the Contras not to dispatch any forces into
Nicaragua from base camps in Honduras, in addition to withdrawing
2,000 of their estimated 5,000 troops based in Nicaragua.
   _A request to Central American presidents to extend from Dec. 5
the deadline set Aug. 7 for concluding the demobilization of the
Contras.
   _A Contra delegation would travel to Nicaragua in the last week
of November to determine if political conditions will permit the
safe return to Nicaragua of rebel combatants.
</TEXT>
