<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Civilians     11-16 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Civilians,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civilians Take Brunt Of Brutal Strife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Salvador, Bjt ^By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria Zubarria of apartment 43
in Zacamil's housing block 111A is swollen like a bullfrog's throat
because her cancer treatment is three days overdue.
   Juan Alberto Ponce has carried a white flag up and down
Conacaste's alleys No. 3 and 4 dozens of times searching in vain
for a way through fierce combat to alley 8, where his family has
been holed up for four days.
   Dr. Ricardo Mendez of Soyapango's Psychiatric Hospital has
worked since Sunday without sleep and for two days without food
because the hospital is in the middle of an urban battlefield and
relief for him and his staff has not arrived.
   Though hundreds of leftist guerrillas and soldiers of the
rightist government have been killed and wounded in this week's
battle for San Salvador, it is the capital's civilian population
that is taking the brunt of the suddenly and drastically escalated
civil war.
   More than 100 non-combatants have been killed, and civilians
make up about half the 1,600 total wounded, according to
still-sketchy casualty figures on fighting that began Saturday
night.
   President Alfredo Cristiani has accused insurgents of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front of entrenching themselves
in densely populated working-class neighborhoods so they are
shielded by non-combatants.
   The presence of thousands of civilians around dug-in rebels has
not prevented the government from sending rocket-firing helicopters
and warplanes with heavy-caliber machine guns against guerrilla
strongholds.
   Thousands of homes have been damaged or wrecked in nearly
continuous strafing of the outlying neighborhoods where the
insurgents are making a stand.
   A reporter races across the clearing separating Zacamil's
six-story apartment complexes from the barricaded streets, assault
rifle fire ringing through the passages between the buildings and
smacking into their facades.
   Guerrillas keep watch at both ends of each floor, sighting down
their Soviet-desgined AK-47s toward soldiers up the road and
occassionally squeezing off short bursts.
   Eduardo Rodriguez, who lives in apartment 42, next to the
cancer-stricken Mrs. Zubarria, crouches behind the low wall of the
fourth floor hallway.
   ``We want to get out of here,'' he says, under his breath so the
guerrillas a few yards away don't hear, to the just-arrived
reporter.
   Later, inside his small apartment with his wife, Adriana, and
their children, he tells how they have almost run out of water and
are low on tortillas, the only food they have left.
   ``They won't let us leave,'' says Mrs. Rodriguez softly, with a
gesture with her chin toward the external hallway where the rebels
crouch. ``We're their protection.''
   Alberto Davila finally decided to take up what he and his wife,
Angela, could carry from their home in Conacaste early Wednesday
and flee along with thousands of others who streamed out of the
neighborhood beneath white flags.
   Mrs. Davila, tears streaming down her face, clutched her
6-year-old daughter's hand as they paused in their flight.
   ``It's terrible, it's terrible,'' she sobbed as several
residents hurried by with an improvised stretcher carrying a
middle-aged woman, her jaw blown off by a bullet or shrapnel. Deep
in shock, she sat straight-backed on the rig and stared straight
ahead with glazed eyes.
   ``We stayed this long because we didn't want to leave the house
abandoned,'' said Davila.
   Mrs. Rodriguez of Zacamil echoed that sentiment.
   She and her family have hung on in Zacamil despite the combat
``because once we leave, we must be resigned to losing everything.
They'll just take it all. But now, we're willing to go with just
the clothes we have on.''
   Perhaps the only civilians in Soyapango not distraught by the
death and destruction surrounding them this week are the catatonics
or severely psychotics among the 360 patients at Dr. Mendez's
hospital.
   But oblivion or delusion cannot keep them entirely immune from
the war and its consequences.
   They have not eaten in more than 48 hours either.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
