<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-16 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Sets Another Record, Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed at a
fourth straight record high today, while the dollar rose against
the yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 24.11 points, or 0.07
percent, ending the day at 35,876.34. On Wednesday, the index
gained 83.59 points.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.85 yen, up 0.48 yen from its
143.37-yen finish on Wednesday. The U.S. currency opened at 143.83
yen and ranged between 143.75 and 144.00 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate moved inside a very tight range,'' said
Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   The dollar opened higher in Tokyo following its overnight rise
in New York, and then rose further because the Tokyo market
expected a decrease in the U.S. trade deficit for September, other
dealers said.
   The U.S. Commerce Department was to announce its monthly trade
statistics in Washington later today.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly sold the dollar to slow its rise
shortly after the currency touched the 144.00-yen mark at late
morning. The central bank does not usually comment on its monetary
actions.
   Ms. Takeuchi said current economic factors were negative for
dollar buying. But she said investors probably would not abandon
the U.S. currency, mainly because of expectations of further
U.S-Soviet arms reductions, which are seen as a remedy for the U.S.
trade deficit.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei index first rose in early
trading following overnight gains in the Dow Jones average of 30
major industrial issues in New York, but then lost more than half
its initial gains.
   ``The index stopped rising as the yen touched 144 yen and
discouraged market players,'' said Masaya Hashizume, a dealer with
Nikko Securities.
   He said a lack of direction in trading also contributed to the
small gains. ``Participants kept changing their buying targets,''
he said.
   ``Investors were trying to sell for profit-taking whenever they
could,'' Hashizume said. He said participants also were concerned
about the forthcoming U.S. trade figures.
   An estimated 1.1 billion shares changed hands on the market's
first section, down from Wednesday's 1.2 billion. Among the winners
were real estate and railways issues.
</TEXT>
