<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Hospital     11-16 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Hospital,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloodbath Drains Hospital Resources</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wounded come in waves. They
have been coming for days and Hospital Rosales is stretched past
the limit.
   ``We need anesthestics. We need antibiotics. We need bandages,''
Dr. Melvin Guardado, the head of emergency services said. ``And
blood? There isn't any blood. On blood, we're done for.''
   Guardado moves aside as yet another stretcher bearing yet
another wounded civilian comes through the open door.
   People huddle outside in groups. A woman cries. The day is
steamy. A thin film of sweat coats the doctor's face.
   ``There are people are coming in from Mejicanos, from
Soyapango,'' he says.
   ``The fighting is heavy there. We understand there are a lot
more waiting to be evacuated but the ambulances can't get in.''
   Guerrillas from the Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National
Liberation have been entrenched in heavily populated northern
neighborhoods like Soyapango and Mejicanos since Saturday.
   The air force has been using warplanes armed with .50-caliber
Gatling guns and helicopter gunships with .30-caliber machines guns
on the areas.
   Guardado takes a drag on his cigarette, watching attendants
wrestle yet another stretcher off the back of a pickup. Soldiers
and police posted in the emergency room watch too.
   Some patients are questioned as well as treated. The army says
wounded guerrillas are being evacuated from battle zones as
civilians.
   ``The surveillance is intense,'' the doctor murmurs as a police
officer moves in on a stretcher bearing a young man shot in the leg.
   Guardado has been a surgeon in San Salvador for 23 years. He's
lived through a decade of war. He manned the emergency room in the
devastating 1986 earthquake. He thought he'd seen it all.
   Until Saturday night, that is, when leftist rebels brought their
war against the U.S.-backed government to the capital.
   ``It wasn't this bad in the earthquake,'' Guardado says. ``I've
never seen anything like it.''
   Rosales, the main civilian hospital in San Salvador, has treated
more than 400 civilian casualties since the offensive began.
   ``Gunshot wounds,'' Guardado says. ``Almost all of them are
gunshot wounds.''
   The 400-bed public hospital, which has eight operating rooms,
can muster about 25 residents, interns and medical students at any
one time. In between the waves of wounded, they try to get some
rest.
   ``Some of the staff is living here at the hospital,'' Guardado
says. ``We have others who can't get to the hospital because of the
fighting. We have a lot of tired people.''
   In a corner of the teeming emergency room, Jose Antonio Canas
watches attendants hovering over his wife, Lidia. She has been shot
in the stomach.
   ``She went to the door to see what was going on,'' he says. ``We
don't know where the bullet came from.''
   The couple and their three teen-age children live in Mejicanos,
the scene of some of the heaviest and most sustained combat.
   Why didn't they leave?
   ``Where were we going to go?'' Canas asks. ``There is fighting
everywhere.''
   He looks at his wife. She is 45. They have been married since
they were teen-agers.
   ``There is no point to this. For anyone,'' he says. ``It has to
stop.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
