<FIRST>r a PM-SmokeoutRdp     11-16 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smokeout Rdp,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Across America, Refrain to Smokers: Kick the Habit Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Smokeout, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Claus lost his pipe, celebrities told tales of going cold
turkey and cigar-smoker Sen. Edward Kennedy proposed funds for an
anti-smoking campaign as millions of American smokers today felt
the heat not to light up.
   On street corners and in offices and hospitals, the country's
non-smoking majority encouraged smokers to snub out their
cigarettes today for the 13th annual Great American Smokeout.
   The American Cancer Society, the Smokeout sponsor, hoped that 10
million of the country's 50 million smokers would give up their
smokes for at least 24 hours.
   The organization estimates that 29 percent of the population
smoke. Four decades ago, 41 percent did.
   ``The people that are smoking now are ... pretty hard core,''
said Mike Madden, a spokesman for the Minnesota Lung Association.
   He and other activists said smokers may need an excuse such as
today's events to break their nicotine addiction.
   But inside Maine's 43 hospitals there'll be no excuse. The
nation's strictest anti-smoking law went into effect today, banning
smoking at hospitals. The only exceptions were for patients with
written permission from a doctor, and then only in designated areas.
   Hospital officials were armed with carrot sticks, popcorn,
crossword puzzles and advice on giving up smoking. Smokers were
being shown the door.
   But physicians who treat people for drug or alcohol dependency
say they are not sure how they will cope with the law.
   ``It's a real moral dilemma,'' said Dr. George Dreher of St.
Mary's Hospital in Lewiston. ``I've had patients walk out of detox
when they found out they couldn't smoke. So what's my priority?''
   In the Philadelphia area, hospitals were setting up clinics
offering advice on how to stop smoking. Many restaurants banned
smoking, Temple University traded pencils for cigarettes and U.S.
Healthcare gave out apples.
   Former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop today was to hand
out ``I'm a Born Non-Smoker'' T-shirts for newborns at a Washington
area hospital.
   He joined Kennedy, the Massachusetts Democrat, at a news
conference Wednesday to announce legislation that would call for
$185 million in federal spending next year on an anti-smoking
advertising campaign; grants to states, schools and businesses that
promote anti-smoking programs; and money to establish a new Center
for Tobacco Products.
   The center would for the first time give the government
regulatory control over the contents of cigarettes.
   ``It's about time that the federal government stood up to be
counted on a product that kills 390,000 people every year,'' Koop
said.
   Kennedy called cigarettes ``a form of death.'' Then he said he
would try to kick his cigar habit.
   Smoking causes lung cancer, heart disease and respiratory
disease. The surgeon general has warned of the potentially fatal
risks of smoking and the addictive nature of nicotine, the active
drug in cigarettes.
   The Tobacco Institute of Washington, the industry's lobbying
arm, generally does not offer a rebuttal to the Smokeout.
   In Illinois, smokers and non-smokers at Loyola University
Medical Center in Maywood today can test carbon monoxide levels in
their lungs.
   Santa's lungs got a break on Wednesday.
   In Southern California, a group of elementary school pupils
yanked the pipe from the mouth of a 8-foot-tall cutout Santa Claus
at a Pasadena shopping center.
   The mall's management decided to make Santa a non-smoker after
the cancer society passed on a complaint from a caller unhappy to
see him puffing.
   Celebrity former smokers at a New York City news conference told
tales of woe for the anti-smoking cause.
   Screen actress Sylvia Miles said she gave up cigarettes out of
embarrassment.
   ``Every year I used to say I wouldn't smoke, and then this year
I decided I was so ashamed to come here and lie, that I really
stopped,'' she said.
   ``I did it in a sneaky way,'' said actor Eli Wallach, who
stopped 25 years ago. ``I switched to little baby cigars and
inhaled those and got sicker and sicker.''
   Non-smoker Eileen Fulton of television's ``As the World Turns''
said she almost started smoking as a young actress with a chance
for a cigarette commercial.
   ``I sat down and took a big drag, right down to my heels,'' she
said. ``They said, `Oh, that's wonderful, Eileen.' Then I turned
around and passed out right on the floor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
