<FIRST>r i PM-Beaujolais     11-16 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beaujolais,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wine-Lovers Turn Out for Promising Beaujolais</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK McDOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beaujolais nouveau fresh from the cask vied with
coffee and croissants in cafes this morning as bon vivants raced to
get their first taste of what forecasters hope will be the best
year for French wine in decades.
   ``Don't drink too much of that stuff or we won't see you for
lunch,'' a waiter joked with an early morning tippler at the Val
d'Or wine bar near the Champs Elysee. ``It's a lot more alcoholic
this year.''
   Proprietor Marcelle Rongier said the Val d'Or sold its first
bottle of the newly arrived Beaujolais nouveau to a regular
customer just after opening at 7 a.m.
   ``He's taking it to work,'' Mrs. Rongier said. ``And he said
he'd come back for lunch and then back again after he gets off.''
   A consumption embargo on the young wine, the first to be
consumed en masse since the autumn grape harvest, was lifted at
midnight Wednesday. Promoters called the 1989 stock the best in 25
years.
   ``This is an exceptional year for Beaujolais and all the
vintages in France,'' said Michel Deflache of the Beaujolais
winegrowers association. ``It's more of a complete wine this year.''
   Wine lovers await the arrival of the fruity beverage each
November at bars and parties from Paris to Australia. Planes,
trains, trucks and ships transported cases all over the world this
week so imbibers could enjoy their first glass today.
   The export success is largely due to Deflache's organization,
the Union Interprofessionnelle des Vins du Beaujolais. Critics and
admirers have debated the wine's other merits for years.
   ``It's extraordinary marketing, but not extraordinary wine,''
declared Jacques Constant, 49, who chose coffee instead of
Beaujolais for breakfast at the Bar St. Philippe in the fashionable
Faubourg St. Honore shopping district.
   ``Twenty years ago, this wine was nothing and it's still
nothing,'' Constant pronounced. ``The real French wines are the
Bordeaux and Bourgogne.''
   Bar owner Rene Bourel launched a spirited response: ``I prefer
the Beaujolais to the Bordeaux. Why? It's like a blond woman or a
brunette, a matter of taste. But I find Bordeaux disgusting.''
   Outdoor parties in the crisp November air were planned all over
the French capital this afternoon, with the largest expected to be
on the Ile de la Cite featuring a New Orleans jazz band and a
banquet of cheeses.
   Prognosticators look to this year's Beaujolais as a bellwether
for the much-hyped 1989 vintages.
   A long dry summer and early, rain-free harvest have led to
expectations that this year's French wines could rank among the
best this century, made of balanced grapes with minimal acidity.
   That gives the Beaujolais nouveau, normally considered an
inexpensive lightweight by connoisseurs, a greater role this year.
And wholesale price increases of 30 percent over last year point
the overall trend in the French wine market thanks to the vaunted
harvest, Deflache says.
   About half of this year's production of 4.4 million cases of
Beaujolais nouveau went to foreign markets, principally West
Germany, Britain, Belgium, the United States and Japan.
   The Japanese market remains the fastest-growing, Deflache said,
with demand jumping from 300,000 cases in 1988 to 440,000 cases
this year.
   The U.S. market represents an equivalent number of sales and
celebrations were planned today in New York, Los Angeles,
Pittsburgh, Atlanta, San Francisco, Houston and Dallas.
</TEXT>
