<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-16 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruby the elephant can paint, but can she
differentiate between colors?
   The Phoenix Zoo, with help from researchers at several
universities, have started testing Ruby to find out.
   The 16-year-old pachyderm received her first paintbrush two
years ago when her keepers noticed she spent a lot of time using
rocks and sticks to doodle in the sand. Before long, painting had
become a favored reward for successfully completing her regular
obedience training.
   ``All we have to do is say the word `paint,' and she squeals,''
said keeper Tawny Carlson.
   Zoo officials noticed Ruby seems to choose the color of her
paint based on colors worn by her visitors. On days guests wear
red, the officials said, she tends to paint red; yellow came into
vogue when large earthmoving equipment worked on a nearby
construction project.
   ``Color vision has only been documented in primates. If we can
document this, it will be something new for elephants,'' said zoo
keeper Anita Schanberger.
   ``It's not a trivial question to answer,'' said Chris Murphy, a
veterinary ophthalmologist with the medical school at the
University of California, Davis. ``It sounds trivial, but you can't
just hold out red and blue plastic blocks and then say that proves
it.''
   Murphy and colleagues at California-Davis, along with experts at
Cornell University, Arizona State University and the University of
Arizona, have coached zoo personnel on how to conduct the color
testing, zoo spokesman Dick George said Wednesday.
   Zookeepers have developed a plywood testing device that will
eventually be used to test for color discrimination, but first Ruby
must master the mechanics of the machine, which involves pulling a
lever for a food reward. George said the testing could take several
years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reno's most prominent painted lady, an 18-foot
showgirl statue, has been ordered down from her perch after
welcoming visitors with open arms and a champagne toast since the
1950s.
   Depicted for years on postcards of the gambling city's downtown,
the scantily clad Primadonna Lady is the only survivor among nine
long-legged statue showgirls that for three decades towered above
the old Primadonna hotel-casino.
   In 1984, the Primadonna Lady _ paint chipping on her red
strapless costume, her tired eyes and her hairdo below her
feathered hat _ was moved from downtown to the roof of a proposed
burlesque dance club.
   But the club never opened. And now city officials want the
statue removed. They cite city ordinances barring closed businesses
from retaining signs advertising the enterprise.
   Mike Mitchell, a supervisor in the city's building department,
said Wednesday he was responding to a complaint in ordering the
building's owners to take the statue down within 10 days.
   ``I guess this is a personal thing for a lot of people,''
Mitchell said. ``She's been around a long time. I do have empathy
for her. But that doesn't have any bearing on why she has to come
down.''
   Mark De La Fuente, a member of the board of Would Corp., which
owns the would-be burlesque and an adult bookstore next door, said
city officials are harassing his company.
   ``It's funny in a state like this, but they don't seem to like
our kind of business much,'' he said. Licensed brothels are legal
in most Nevada counties.
</TEXT>
