<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast of Frigid Air Moves into Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A blast of frigid air continued to move through the nation's
midsection today, as thunderstorms were pushing out the warm
weather that the East has had since the weekend.
   Tornadoes in Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, the Carolinas and
Kentucky caused hundreds of injuries and many deaths Wednesday.
   Wintery weather swept into Michigan, bringing snow that put a
chill on the opening day of deer season and was a factor in an auto
accident in which four teen-agers were killed.
   Temperatures early this morning fell to freezing in Chicago and
Peoria, 30 in Rockford and 33 in Decatur as a light snow dusted
central Illinois.
   On Wednesday, temperatures dipped into the teens and single
digits from eastern Montana through the Dakotas to northwestern
Minnesota by early evening. Winds gusting to 40 mph produced wind
chill readings colder than 25 degrees below zero.
   There were dozens of reports of large hail and damaging winds in
Kentucky, Alabama and Mississippi on Wednesday, while thunderstorms
produced heavy rain across parts of the Ohio Valley, Tennessee and
the central Gulf Coast states.
   In Ohio, thunderstorms produced an inch of rain in half an hour
in Fairfield, 1.75 inches of rain in 20 minutes at Wayne, and 1.7
inches of rain in 20 minutes at Trenton.
   Snow fell across the upper Mississippi Valley and western
sections of the Great Lakes region Wednesday night, with heavy snow
today along the southern shore of Lake Superior and Lake Michigan.
   Up to a foot of snow was expected to fall today in upper
Michigan and storm warnings and watches were in effect for lower
Michigan and northern Indiana. Gale warnings were in effect for
Lake Superior and Lake Michigan.
   The nation's high Wednesday was 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   Other reports at a.m. EST:
   _East: Atlanta 48 windy; Boston 64 showery; Buffalo 57;
Charleston, S.C. 71 thunderstorms; Chattanooga 43 partly cloudy;
Cincinnati 37 rain; Cleveland 41 rain; Detroit 33 snow; Hatteras 73
windy; Jacksonville 73 cloudy; Key West 78 fair; Knoxville 43
showery; Macon 63 cloudy; Miami 75 fair; New York 61 windy;
Philadelphia 64 cloudy; Pittsburgh 54 showery; Portland, Maine 56
foggy; Richmond 68 windy; Tampa 76 cloudy; Washington, D.C. 65
cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 2 fair; Chicago 33 cloudy; Denver 15 fair;
Des Moines 19 snow; Indianapolis 34 snow; Kansas City 23 windy;
Little Rock 45 fair; Louisville 39 rain; Memphis 43 fair; Nashville
42 cloudy; New Orleans 55 windy; North Platte 10 fair; Oklahoma
City 33 fair; Omaha 16 windy; Rapid City 5 fair; St. Louis 35 snow;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 15 windy; Sault Ste. Marie 25 snow; San
Antonio 44 partly cloudy.
   _West: Anchorage 16 cloudy; Boise 31 cloudy; Casper 22 partly
cloudy; Fairbanks 2 cloudy; Great Falls 32 fair; Honolulu 69 partly
cloudy; Las Vegas 52 cloudy; Los Angeles 65 partly cloudy; Medford
37 fair; Pendleton 37 partly cloudy; Phoenix 58 partly cloudy;
Portland, Ore. 42 fair; Reno 30 fair; Salt Lake City 29 cloudy; San
Diego 58 partly cloudy; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle 44 cloudy;
Spokane 30 cloudy.
   _International: Montreal 61 partly cloudy; Ottawa 45 foggy;
Regina 7 fair; Toronto 54 foggy; Winnipeg 5 fair.
