<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchCouncil     11-16 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Council,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Council of Churches Seek Catholics, Evangelicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Council of Churches is making a
push to strengthen ties with Roman Catholics and conservative
evangelicals, traditionally on the sidelines of America's largest
ecumenical body.
   It is one of the more pressing matters facing the council in the
1990s, according to members of the council's governing board, who
are gathered in Pittsburgh this week for their twice-yearly meeting.
   ``If the wall can come down in Germany, anything can happen. But
my assumption would be that we would form a new council'' if Roman
Catholics and evangelicals assumed a more active role, said the
Rev. Patricia McClurg, outgoing council president.
   ``The Roman Catholic Church in membership is larger than all the
rest of us here put together,'' she said. ``And so in fairness to
the way they would approach such a council, the gifts they would
bring, I believe we would have to draw a new blueprint.''
   Ms. McClurg, associate executive of the Presbytery mission in
Elizabeth, N.J., told the governing board Wednesday a committee has
been appointed to increase council input from Roman Catholics and
evangelicals. Although the two groups currently are represented on
some council projects, neither is a full-fledged member.
   The Rev. Eileen W. Lindner, a Presbyterian minister from
Tenafly, N.J., and an associate general secretary for the council,
said the seven-member committee will ``explore the ways in which
we're already witnessing Christian unity'' with Roman Catholics and
evangelicals.
   Thirty-two Protestant, Orthodox and Anglican denominations
constitute the council, with a combined membership of 42 million
Christians.
   Some conservative evangelicals have criticized the council in
the past for its involvement in so many social issues, according to
the Very Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky, an archpriest of the Orthodox
Church in America who will be installed tonight as the council's
new president.
   ``Some evangelical people would feel that more prayer is
needed,'' Kishkovsky said.
   Many of the resolutions being considered by the 273-member
governing board during its three-day meeting in Pittsburgh, which
ends Friday, involve domestic issues. One measure calls for a
congressional hearing to discuss the harassment of black elected
officials, while another urges legislation banning the sale of
handguns and assault weapons to the public.
   Other resolutions being voted on by the board today call for
continued support of affirmative action and equal pay for work of
equal value.
   On international issues, the council's division of overseas
ministries is urging the U.S. government to prevent the return to
power in Cambodia of Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge. The governing board
also will consider resolutions involving the political situations
in El Salvador and Angola, and the 75th anniversary of the Armenian
genocide.
   Kishkovsky and the Rev. Syngman Rhee, the president-elect
nominee, said they want to focus more on matters closer to home
during the next few years in hopes of helping the faithful through
today's trying times.
   ``The churches need to take concern and care for what is
happening in the United States'' like divorce and drug abuse, said
Rhee, a mission executive with the Presbyterian Church (USA) in
Louisville, Ky.
   ``Global issues have occupied our attention and our energy quite
a bit. We need to come back to the basic patterns of ministries of
the church to the people,'' he said.
   Council leaders hope the shift will have a financial effect as
well. The council is in the midst of a restructuring prompted, in
part, by stagnant contributions from the 32 denominations.
   Council officials on Wednesday presented a proposed budget of
$45.4 million for 1990, nearly $1 million more than 1989's spending
plan. About 70 percent of the money will go to Church World
Service, the council's relief and refugee resettlement agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
