<FIRST>r a PM-ReluctantRescuee     11-16 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reluctant Rescuee,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Victim Greets Rescuer With Fists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 82-year-old woman came out swinging when
a firefighter tried to rescue her from her burning home,
authorities said
   The volunteer firefighter who found Evelyn Foreman of Bedford on
the floor of her smoke-filled bedroom Tuesday said he expected to
find her unconscious or dead.
   Instead, she started throwing punches, said the 28-year-old
firefighter, Daniel Datesman.
   Mrs. Foreman remained hospitalized in stable condition early
today.
   ``She wanted to know who the hell I was and what I was doing in
her bedroom,'' Datesman said Wednesday. ``She wouldn't leave her
home.''
   Mrs. Foreman slugged her rescuer three times before collapsing.
Datesman said he didn't understand how she was able to do that in
heavy smoke.
   Other volunteers helped Datesman carry Mrs. Foreman out of the
house when he became disoriented in the smoke.
   ``She beat the heck out of him,'' Assistant Fire Chief Steve
Wineland said. ``She was definitely feisty.''
   The cause of the fire, which caused $15,000 in damages, has not
been determined, Wineland said.
   The flames were confined to the kitchen. The rest of the
2{-story brick home received water and smoke damage.
   Mrs. Foreman, a retired nurse, came to once firefighters got her
outside and initially refused to go to Memorial Hospital of Bedford
County. Neighbors and friends finally persuaded her to go as a
precaution.
   Datesman said he planned to visit Mrs. Foreman ``to give her a
big bouquet of flowers and a big hug. She's a remarkable woman.''
</TEXT>
