<FIRST>r a PM-RockHall     11-16 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rock Hall,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleveland Meets Fund-raising Deadline; Rock Hall Ready to Roll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a rocky fund-raising effort, backers say
they have the money to break ground next year for a national rock
'n' roll hall of fame and museum in downtown Cleveland.
   ``We are off the rocks and on a roll,'' Cleveland Mayor George
Voinovich said at a news conference announcing the city had met the
Wednesday deadline to raise $40 million for the glass-and-steel
pyramid structure with 18-story tower.
   The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation in New York, a group
of recording industry executives and artists' promoters and
managers which each year since 1986 has inducted music figures into
the hall, had set the deadline.
   The rock mecca is expected to cost $48 million overall. The city
still must find the other $8 million; no deadline for that amount
has been announced.
   The hall would be a centerpiece for a new hotel-retail complex,
called Tower City, which is under construction.
   Larry Thompson, the hall's director, said $40.2 million was
raised by Tuesday night. Contributions and pledges came from
corporations, foundations, government and others.
   Of the $40 million, $5 million comes from a state appropriation,
$5 million from county bonds and $18 million from city property
taxes on Tower City that would be used toward the rock hall's
construction.
   The rest came in commitments by Cleveland corporations and
foundations as well as in personal gifts, said Thompson.
   Last month, a $6.9 million federal Urban Development Action
Grant, considered a key piece in the project's funding, fell
through.
   Local promoters predicted about 600,000 people would visit the
hall and museum each year and spend about $85 million at area
hotels, restaurants and shops.
   Cleveland, where disc jockey Alan Freed is said to have coined
the term ``rock 'n' roll,'' and seven other cities vied to be home
of the hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a UnexplainedOzoneLossesFoundNearAntarctica     11-16 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>Unexplained Ozone Losses Found Near Antarctica</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers said today they have found evidence
of mysterious ozone destruction near Antarctica that cannot be
explained by the well-known ``ozone hole'' there.
   The finding suggests that scientists have more to learn about
the important problem of what destroys ozone in the atmosphere,
said researcher M.H. Proffitt.
   Reporting in the British journal Nature, the scientists said
they had detected ozone losses outside the ozone hole, which is an
area of annual and temporary ozone destruction over Antarctica.
They also found evidence that ozone losses begin before the hole
forms each year.
   Other scientists urged caution in interpreting the research but
said it is potentially significant.
   Ozone is a form of oxygen. It is a pollutant at ground level but
beneficial high in the atmosphere, where it shields out ultraviolet
rays that can promote skin cancer.
   Protection of the globe's ozone shield has become a focus of
international concern, focusing on the use of compounds called
chlorofluorocarbons. Chlorine from those compounds is implicated in
the ozone hole.
   The new study's co-authors include Proffitt of the Cooperative
Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, a joint venture
of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the
University of Colorado. The other co-authors are with NOAA.
   The scientists found evidence of ozone destruction at altitudes
of about 11 miles to 12 miles by analyzing readings taken during
airplane flights during 1987.
   In an unusual approach to measuring ozone losses, the
researchers first determined an apparently normal minimum ratio of
ozone levels to amounts of nitrogen compounds. When a given sample
of air showed a lower ratio, it was considered to have lost some
ozone.
   Using this method, the researchers found evidence of ozone loss
averaging at least 15 percent to 30 percent at the 11-mile altitude
outside the ozone hole, the limits of which roughly correspond to
the outline of Antarctica.
   The newly found area of depletion extended about 342 miles
outside the boundary of the ozone hole and perhaps twice that far,
Proffitt said in a telephone interview.
   In addition, losses inside and outside the area covered by the
ozone hole were observed in mid-August, which was before the
formation of the hole in September.
   The researchers concluded that losses outside the ozone hole
were caused by some sort of chemical reaction that occurred outside
the hole. Perhaps they resulted from temporary conditions that
allowed chlorine to destroy ozone for limited periods, Proffitt
said.
   Robert de Zafra of the State University of New York at Stony
Brook, who has studied the chemistry of the ozone hole, said
Wednesday he found the paper's evidence ``interesting but not
compelling.''
   He cautioned that the researchers used only an indirect means of
detecting ozone loss. An aberration similar to what they called
evidence of ozone loss near the ozone hole also appears in their
data from the Northern Hemisphere, but they do not claim ozone loss
there, he said.
   Still, if their analysis near the ozone hole ``holds up and is
verified by other, more direct measurements, then this is a fairly
major and significant finding that will send people scurrying to
try to determine the cause of it,'' he said.
   Guy Brasseur, acting director of the atmospheric chemistry
division at the National Center for Atmospheric Research in
Boulder, Colo., also cautioned the paper's conclusions should be
considered only tentative.
   The paper gives good evidence for ozone destruction, but not
absolute proof, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-16 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Generally Higher Ahead of U.S. Trade Figures, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was generally higher in lively late
morning trading in Europe today, buoyed by investor demand ahead of
the release of eagerly awaited U.S. trade figures.
   Gold prices fell below the important $390.00 an ounce level in
quiet trading.
   The market was expecting the U.S. trade deficit to have narrowed
to around $8.9 billion in September, from $10.77 billion in August,
dealers said.
   Traders said it will take a trade deficit of between $8.3
billion and $8.5 billion for the dollar to be pushed up. A deficit
wider than $9 billion will send the dollar lower, they said.
   ``Recent economic indicators have shown the U.S. economy is
slowing, but the underlying, long-term prospects for the U.S.
economy are still good,'' said one trader in Milan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.48 yen to a closing 143.85 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 144.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.84355 West German marks, up from 1.8382
   _1.6320 Swiss francs, up from 1.6220
   _6.2710 French francs, up from 6.2420
   _2.07835 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0790
   _1,354.50 Italian lire, up from 1,348.25
   _1.1712 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1726
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5755 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5810 late Wednesday.
   An overnight rise in gold prices was wiped out by European
selling pressure this morning. Dealers said they expect profit
taking and consolidation in light of gold's recent upward climb.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $390.30 a troy ounce,
down from late Wednesday's $391.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of $389.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $388.75, down from $391.00 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.32 to close at a bid $389.62.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.49 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $5.46.
</TEXT>
