<FIRST>r a PM-JudgeTrial     11-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge Trial,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Was Undressed, Former Secretary Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EBENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former court secretary says she felt
insulted after she saw a judge wearing nothing but his undershorts
when he called her into in his office six years ago.
   Betty Krisko, 58, told a jury Wednesday she yelled an epithet at
suspended Judge Joseph F. O'Kicki before stalking out of his office
that day.
   O'Kicki, 59, who sat on the bench for 17 years before being
suspended last year, is on trial on 11 charges spanning more than a
decade. He has denied the charges, which include bribery,
extortion, open lewdness and coercion.
   ``He was standing sideways, 10 to 12 feet away, dictating into
the Dictaphone,'' Betty Krisko said, testifying on the April 1983
episode. ``He had nothing on but a pair of bikini briefs,'' she
said.
   ``I was disgusted and embarrassed.''
   O'Kicki appeared to be naked when he called the former secretary
into his office on another occasion in July 1983, said Ms. Krisco,
who worked for the judge for 12 years before leaving in February
1985.
   Under cross-examination by defense attorney Richard Galloway,
Ms. Krisko said she could see only O'Kicki's chest area and could
not tell whether he was wearing pants.
   She also testified that although her relationship with the judge
was good at one point, in later years O'Kicki often harassed her
and appeared to be trying to ``get rid'' of her.
   ``He gave me so many problems at work,'' she said. ``He ...
locked me out of the office and ... threw files off my desk.''
   Earlier Wednesday, defense attorneys questioned the credibility
of a former tipstaff who said he often drove O'Kicki's daughters to
college or performed chores around the judge's house on county time.
   George Koban, a former Philadelphia police officer who left the
force in 1972 because of a disability, said he paid O'Kicki $500
for a better-paying job but never received it.
   A tipstaff takes care of the jury and keeps the courtroom in
order.
   Defense attorneys Wednesday presented Koban's bank records from
that time, saying they did not reflect a $500 withdrawal.
   O'Kicki's trial began Nov. 7 and is expected to last at least
three weeks. He faces a second trial on 16 other counts at a still
unscheduled date.
</TEXT>
