<DOCNO> AP891116-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IBMProbe     11-16 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Probe,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Says Used Equipment Sold to Government as New</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
acknowledged that it sold the federal government used equipment it
had claimed was new, a published report said today.
   IBM spokesman Mark Holcomb told The Washington Times that the
company also falsely certified that equipment sold to the
government was made of domestic parts in accordance with the Buy
American Act.
   Holcomb said IBM has been trying to negotiate a settlement with
the General Services Administration, the government agency that has
been investigating IBM computer contracts.
   ``Eighteen months ago, IBM discovered through its own internal
audit procedure and disclosed to the government contract compliance
related to the Buy American Act and the new-versus-used issue,''
Holcomb told the newspaper.
   He said the false certifications may have begun as early as 1982
but that the GSA was investigating IBM shipments from 1986 to 1988.
   A finding that IBM gave false information could lead the federal
government to suspend one of its biggest computer contractors from
doing business with the government.
   IBM provides computer mainframes and support services to the
federal government. The GSA told the Times that IBM received 84
percent of Navy contracts for IBM or IBM-compatible mainframes.
   A Justice Department spokesman, Dan Eramian, declined to say
whether the department is investigating IBM, the Times said.
   Holcomb said IBM has acted to correct the problems and said the
false certifications were not made intentionally.
   ``It's a matter of not knowing as the result of an
administration problem, not knowing the content. IBM has corrected
the problem. It no longer exists,'' he said.
</TEXT>
