<DOCNO> AP891116-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorDisclosure     11-16 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Disclosure,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Urges More Disclosure of Medical Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors shouldn't send patients to a clinic for
expensive tests if they own a stake in the clinic _ unless they
advise the patient to get a second opinion first, a law professor
argues in a medical journal article.
   The attorney, Marc A. Rodwin of Tufts University, said it is not
enough for doctors simply to tell patients about the conflict of
interest, because patients may not understand why it matters.
   Many doctors now own shares in X-ray centers and other
facilities where they frequently send patients for tests or other
services.
   ``Patients need to know that virtually every major study
indicates that physicians who make referrals to medical facilities
they own recommend more (or more expensive) medical tests and
procedures than physicians without ownership interests,'' Rodwin
wrote.
   Rodwin outlined his case in a report published today in the New
England Journal of Medicine.
   Conflict of interest can affect a doctor's views about whether a
medical service is needed _ not just who should provide it, Rodwin
said.
   Rather than simply telling patients about their conflict or
giving them a list of alternative clinics, ``physicians who
recommend expensive tests or procedures in facilities in which they
have a financial interest should probably advise their patients to
seek a second opinion from a physician without a conflict of
interest.''
</TEXT>
