<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Soldier'sHeart     11-16 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Soldier's Heart,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain Soldier's Heart Implanted in Palestinian Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors today transplanted the heart of an
Israeli soldier who was killed in an Arab guerrilla attack into a
Palestinian patient, Israeli officials said.
   Hanna Khader, 54, a former hotel manager from east Jerusalem,
was recovering and in stable condition in the intensive care ward
at Hadassah Medical Center in Jerusalem after the four-hour
operation, the family said.
   Thirteen family members gathered in the hospital lobby
afterward, crying and hugging each other.
   ``I can't tell you how happy I am,'' said Mary, his 51-year-old
wife. He's a human being, and there is no difference between a
Palestinian and an Israeli in such cases.''
   Jamilla, Khader's 29-year-old daughter, said the family was not
told by the hospital who donated the heart but learned of it from
the media.
   She indicated family members had some concern that they could be
targeted by radical Palestinians or fundamentalists for accepting
an Israeli heart but said: ``In such cases we cannot mix politics
with medicine.
   ``If we refused to take the heart it would be like killing him
with our own hands,'' she said, adding that she would do the same
if one of her family had an organ needed by an Israeli.
   The Israeli-born soldier, reservist Sgt. Zeev Traum, 40, who
grew up in New York and lived on an Israeli collective farm, died
Wednesday night of a head wound suffered in an ambush Monday.
   Traum was the second trooper to die in the attack claimed by the
Palestinian Moslem fundamentalist Hamas group. He was the 42nd
Israeli victim of a 23-month-old Palestinian uprising in which 615
Arabs also have died.
   Spokesmen at Hadassah could not be reached, but an Israeli
official who spoke on condition of anonymity confirmed that the
soldier's family had donated the heart to the Arab patient.
   The family ``agreed immediately to make the donation simply out
of pure generosity, but they are in mourning and don't want to talk
about it,'' the official said.
   Traum's heart was brought to Jerusalem in a special ice chest by
helicopter from Soroka Hospital in the southern Israeli town of
Beersheba shortly before midnight.
   The surgery conducted by Dr. Dov Simon was the ninth heart
transplant done in Israel.
   It was the first known case since the uprising began of an
Israeli victim donating an organ to a Palestinian.
   In December, the family of a Palestinian shot to death by
Israeli soldiers in the West Bank town of Nablus refused a request
to donate their son's heart to a dying Israeli civilian.
   The Palestinian, Nasr Hawwash, 20, was declared brain dead after
sustaining a serious head wound Dec. 16 during a demonstration.
   The Israeli accountant Yehiel Israeli, 46, had been hooked to a
respirator on Dec. 18 after unsuccessful surgery on a heart valve.
He died three days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
