<FIRST>r w PM-Speaker'sPlane     11-16 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speaker's Plane,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0551 to clear garble</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Refuses To Set Air Force Plane Aside for Speaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley can make use of
an Air Force plane on a case-by-case basis when he needs to travel
on official government business, but no ``Air Force Three'' will be
set aside for him.
   That is the result of action taken by the House Wednesday, a day
after reports that an amendment in a defense appropriations bill
would have given Foley the same reserved-plane privilege now
enjoyed only by the president and vice president.
   In adopting a $286 billion military spending bill, House members
agreed to a substitute provision that would make an Air Force
aircraft available to Foley if he requested it. But no specific
C-20 plane would be kept ready for his call at Andrews Air Force
Base in nearby Maryland.
   Under what has been described as a gentleman's agreement, the
Defense Department has traditionally furnished the speaker with a
plane on request. Foley is next in line of presidential succession
after Vice President Dan Quayle.
   When reporters asked presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
Wednesday about an earlier proposal to set aside an aircraft for
Foley, he said, ``I doubt that the proposal will fly once it is
exposed to the American people's scrutiny.''
   ``We worked it out with the Air Force,'' Rep. John Murtha,
D-Pa., said after the House agreement to keep the old arrangement.
Murtha is chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
defense who, according to congressional sources, had inserted the
change into the bill.
   Murtha said the committee had felt strongly that ``because of
the speaker's high responsibility'' and incidents of terrorism a
plane should be designated for his use. But, he said, ``we had
trouble with the technical language.''
   The Defense Department already provides a jet for the president,
known as Air Force One; and for the vice president, dubbed Air
Force Two.
   It remained unclear whether Foley had requested a change, but
his staff seemed surprised when told it was part of the bill.
   Questioned at midday about the possibility of having a $20
million aircraft at his disposal, Foley said there has never been a
case where the speaker has been denied use of an aircraft for
official purposes.
   ``I am sure that will continue. Nor would I ever suppose that
any aircraft would be assigned exclusively to me and not be
available for other use under appropriate circumstances for
official purposes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
