<FIRST>r a PM-TennesseanChanges     11-16 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tennessean Changes,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leadership Changes Announced at Nashville Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Seigenthaler is assuming
responsibility for the business side of The Tennessean and
relinguishing his title of editor as part of a realignment of
duties at the Gannett Co. Inc.-owned newspaper.
   Seigenthaler was named chairman, publisher and chief executive
officer of The Tennessean. He is also editorial director of
Gannett's USA Today.
   Under a joint operating agreement with the Nashville Banner, The
Tennessean handles all advertising, circulation, production and
distribution functions for the two newspapers. The news departments
remain separate. The Nashville Banner is owned by The Nashville
Banner Publishing Co.
   Seigenthaler gave up the title of editor to E. Frank Sutherland
Jr., who returns to The Tennessean. Sutherland was editor of The
Times in Shreveport, La.
   C.W. Johnson, now deputy managing editor, will be promoted to
managing editor to replace Wayne Whitt, who is retiring. Metro
Editor Teresa Wasson moves to deputy managing editor.
   Joseph P. Pepe of the Gannett corporate staff was named
president and chief operating officer of The Tennessean. Pepe has
been coordinating Gannett's customer service program since July. He
had been executive vice president for operations at the El Paso
(Texas) Times since 1987.
   ``I'm honored by the confidence and challenge by Gannett,'' said
Seigenthaler. ``I'm elated by the appointment of Joe Pepe and
personally gratified to see Frank Sutherland come back to where he
started.''
   Harry Browning, who had been president and general manager of
The Tennessean, was named a general executive of Gannett.
   The changes were announced Wednesday by Brian Donnelly,
president of Gannett's Metro Newspaper Division.
</TEXT>
