<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 3rdLd-Writethru   11-16 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0544,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa to Repeal Major Segregation Law, Open All Beaches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 4th, `In many ...,' to UPDATE with reax
from far-right party. Pickup 5th pvs: De Klerk, addressing.. .</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SAHM VENTER</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has declared all
whites-only beaches open to blacks and will repeal the law that
allows local officials to segregate public facilities, President
F.W. de Klerk announced today.
   ``The time has arrived to repeal this act,'' he said, referring
the Separate Amenities Act that his National Party put into law in
1953.
   Since then, the act has been used by white local governments
across the country to bar blacks from parks, libraries, swimming
pools, civic centers, buses and a range of other amenities.
   In many communities, most or all of these amenities are now
opened to all races. But whites-only facilities persist in the
capital, Pretoria, in many rural towns, and in several small
industrial cities where the far-right Conservative Party took power
in municipal elections last year and re-introduced segregation laws.
   The proposed repeal ``is the beginning of the end of a separate
white community life,'' said Koos van der Merwe, chief spokesman
for the Conservatives, who urged whites to oust de Klerk.
   ``The steps which now will inevitably follow will be the
scrapping of separate residential areas, separate schools and
separate voters' rolls,'' he said. ``Mr. de Klerk is placing South
Africa on the road of a totally racially mixed South Africa, which
will inevitably be governed by a black majority.''
   De Klerk, addressing a high-level advisory group called the
President's Council, said the Separate Amenities Act would be
repealed ``as soon as possible'' after Parliament reconvenes on
Feb. 2.
   The repeal would leave three major categories of segregation in
South Africa _ residential neighborhoods, public hospitals and
public schools.
   The government is in the process of designating certain
neighborhoods as multiracial, although it says whites will retain
the option of living in segregated areas. De Klerk has given no
signal that public schools and hospitals will be integrated.
   Anti-apartheid leaders had anticipated either repeal or revision
of the Separate Amenities Act, and said any change, while welcome,
would not affect the political domination of the 5 million whites
over the 32 million blacks, Asians and people of mixed-race.
   Activists have demanded the repeal of the two remaining
legislative cornerstones of apartheid _ the Group Areas Act, which
segregates residential areas, and the Population Registration Act,
which officially classifies all South Africans by race.
   De Klerk said repeal of the Separate Amenities Act would be
undertaken ``with careful consideration of the implications of such
a step.'' He said ``fitting measures'' would be taken to ensure
that the opening of segregated facilities did not lead to
overcrowding, an increase in crime or environmental problems.
   Steps to integrate whites-only beaches ``should be taken and
implemented without any delay,'' he said.
   Many beaches have been opened to all races in recent years, but
segregated beachfronts remain the country's main resort city,
Durban, and several smaller resort communities. Durban's city
council recently voted down a beach integration proposal.
   ``It has been decided that all beaches will henceforth be
accessible to all members of the public,'' de Klerk said. ``Insofar
as ordinances or bylaws may exist in conflict with this, the local
authorities are requested to act within the spirit of this
decision.''
   De Klerk, who took office in August, said his announcements were
``in line with our stated goal to eliminate discrimination.''
   His announcements were the latest in a series of moves aimed at
enhancing the prospects for black-white negotiations on a new
constitution that would extend political rights to blacks while
protecting white interests.
   Among these moves:
   _Eight prominent political prisoners, including seven leaders of
the outlawed African National Congress, were freed unconditionally
on Oct. 15.
   _For the first time in years, the government has allowed mass
demonstrations and marches by anti-apartheid activists.
   _De Klerk and other officials have sharply increased government
contacts with opposition leaders, holding meetings with nationally
known and local activists.
   ``There is no alternative for South Africa but the road of
reconciliation,'' de Klerk said today. ``The government is not
playing games ... We are in deadly earnest with regard to the road
on which we have embarked.''
   He said the government had spent the equivalent of $70 million
since 1983 upgrading beaches and would continue this program with
the aim of minimizing overcrowding and possible racial friction. He
said local authorities would retain powers to control potential
crowding problems.
   De Klerk said the the government would support
``non-discriminatory methods to ensure acceptable behavior,
civilized standards and compliance with the law.''
</TEXT>
