<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 11-16 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0550,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Westerners Turn Up, Say They Weren't Kidnapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with West German ambassador disputing
report of robbery, other details. Pickup 8th pvs: A Beirut...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American woman and two West Germans
turned up in good health in Lebanon today, and relatives and West
German authorities said the three claimed they had not been
kidnapped.
   A previously unknown group said Wednesday it had abducted the
three.
   Relatives and West German Ambassador Wolfgang Gottelmann said
Deborah Fahrend, 54, and naturalized West Germans Mounir Shamseddin
Sami, 39, who was born in Lebanon and his son, Danjel, 7, born in
Berlin would leave for Cyprus later in the day by ferry.
   ``They are free. They presented themselves this morning at the
consular section of the embassy after they had read the reports (of
their kidnapping). There was no kidnapping,'' Gottelmann told The
Associated Press by telephone.
   He disputed a family member's comment that the three had been
robbery victims rather than hostages.
   ``They had not been robbed. They were already back in east
Beirut ready to return to Cyprus when the claim was issued. They
had come to Lebanon to see the man's family,'' he added.
   He said: ``The American lady was a friend of the family. They
cannot explain how this happened. I doubted this thing from the
beginning.''
   A relative said the three ``called from the West German Embassy
in Christian east Beirut to report that they were O.K.''
   The relative, who refused to be further identified, said Mounir
Shamseddin Sami told relatives by telephone that the three were
``robbed by gunmen.''
   ``He didn't say where they were robbed,'' the relative added.
   Ms. Fahrend, 54, of San Francisco, was ``with Sami and the boy.
They are all O.K.,'' the relative added.
   The discrepancies between the various accounts of what happened
could not immediately be reconciled.
   ``It seems those who robbed them also took their passports,
photocopied them and issued the claim hoping to make some money,''
the relative said.
   A Beirut police spokesman, who cannot be name in line with
standing regulations, said: ``It's a strange story. I don't believe
that they were held against their will.''
   In Bonn, a West German government spokesman said the three
insisted they were not abducted. ``They showed up at the (West
German Embassy in Beirut) saying they could not explain why it was
reported they were kidnapped,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Rainer Mueller. He said the three went to the embassy this morning
and were all in good health.
   ``They told the embassy they went there because they were upset
about news reports of their kidnapping,'' said Mueller.
   The kidnapping claim was made in a typewritten statement, in
Arabic, by a group calling itself The Organization of Just Revenge.
The statement was delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut with
photocopies of the passports and visas of the three people.
   ``The Organization of Just Revenge announces its responsibility
for kidnapping the West German Mounir Sami (born in Lebanon) and
his son Danjel Sami and American publisher-journalist Deborah
Fahrend in Beirut for their activities in Lebanon,'' it said.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater announced to
reporters flying with President Bush to Houston today that the
three had turned up.
   ``The West German government has informed us that the three
people kidnapped in Beirut yesterday _ two Germans and one U.S.
citizen _ are in the West German Embassy in Beirut. All three are
reported in good health. That's all we have. The cable just came to
the president,'' Fitzwater said.
   Ms. Fahrend, 54, is a nurse and sometime poet who had described
herself as a ``publisher-journalist.'' She reportedly had gone to
war-torn Lebanon in hopes of writing a book on what she called her
``chance in a lifetime.''
   It could not be immediately determined whether the three knew
each other.
   Eighteen foreigners are held in Lebanon, including eight
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Most of the hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian factions.
</TEXT>
