<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bolivia     11-16 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bolivia,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>24-Hour Strike Shuts Down Mines, Factories in Bolivia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour general strike called to
protest a government crackdown on labor unrest idled mines and some
factories in Bolivia today, but businesses and transportation
appeared to be operating normally.
   On Wednesday, the 3-month-old government of President Jaime Paz
Zamora declared a state of siege and rounded up hundreds of
teachers and labor leaders after negotiations with striking
teachers broke down.
   The three-month state of siege expands police powers and allows
state governments to limit public meetings. The center-left
government said it acted to guarantee peaceful local elections next
month.
   ``We are calling for the strike to demand the freedom of all the
leaders, students and workers detained by the repressive
government,'' said Filemon Escobar, leader of the Bolivian Workers
Central, the main union federation.
   At least half of the 858 teachers and labor leaders arrested
Wednesday were later released, said the Interior Ministry. The
state of siege authorized police to detain people without charges
for 48 hours.
   Today's strike closed the 14 government-owned mines and some
factories, but in La Paz and other cities businesses were operating
normally.
   Teachers refused to hold final exams scheduled today and said
they will not hand out report cards unless they receive the
one-time $103 bonus they are demanding to make up for inflation.
   ``In declaring the state of siege the government revealed its
real undemocratic face in violating the constitution and the law,''
said a statement by the Workers Central calling for the 24-hour
general strike today.
   The Workers Central, which is made up of the country's principal
unions, also demanded new talks between the government and teachers.
   ``After three months in power President Jaime Paz Zamora shows
he cannot resolve the basic problems of the Bolivian people,'' said
the statement.
   The government has said it cannot afford to pay the bonus and
will not negotiate under pressure.
   Three of the leaders of the teachers union were taken to a
private clinic in critical condition after being on a hunger strike
for 24 days.
   ``Our hands will not tremble to impose order and the law,'' said
congressman Luis Vazques, a member of the governing Movement of the
Revolutionary Left. ``This government respects the constitution but
demands that democracy be respected. We wish to defend the values
of democracy.''
   The state of siege was also enacted to guarantee the municipal
elections scheduled for Dec. 3. It imposes a 1:00-to-5:00 a.m.
curfew. There are no restrictions, however, on political
advertisement or intercity or foreign travel, says the prefect of
La Paz, Fernando Cajias.
   Bolivian cities were calm Wednesday after the state of siege was
declared. In recent days there have been widespread confrontations
between rock-throwing protesters and police who used tear gas to
break up marches and road blocks.
   Bolivia, South America's poorest country, has a minimum monthly
wage of $25. Teachers earn an average of $75 a month, and education
makes up 18 percent of the federal budget.
</TEXT>
