<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-GoingBack 1stLd-Writethru   11-16 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Going Back, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0467,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disappointed East Germans Trickle Back Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT spelling of Wietsche in 3rd
graf: Wietsche was ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diethard Wietsche has gone back to East
Germany, where he says he spent 10 years in prison for trying to
escape, because he's disappointed with life in the capitalist West.
   He says he now has hope for promised changes in his Communist
homeland.
   Wietsche was one of about 60 East Germans who had arrived by
Wednesday at the East Berlin center where the government welcomes
back prodigal sons and daughters.
   ``Every day about 30 people knock on the door here and ask to
re-enter the German Democratic Republic,'' said Peter Heyn, deputy
chief of the center in Berlin's northeastern Buch district. ``The
climate in the Federal Republic (West Germany) has gotten colder.''
   He predicted the center soon would reach its capacity of 150
people.
   It is not clear how many of the East Germans who fled to West
Germany this year might return home now that Communist leaders in
East Berlin have opened of the borders to free travel and promised
a more open society.
   About 200,000 East Germans, most of them young and skilled, had
emigrated to their rich western neighbor this year before the
authorities buckled under the pressure of a peaceful popular revolt
and threw open their borders.
   West Germany's ZDF television network said Wednesday about 7,000
disillusioned East Germans were expected to turn their backs on
their rich neighbor, but officials on both sides of the border said
there were no signs of a major organized return for the time being.
ZDF gave no source for its report.
   An air of old-style secrecy surrounds the East Berlin government
returnee center, East Germany's only one until the national Red
Cross started setting up several of its own this week.
   Gray corrugated-metal fences keep outsiders from peering in.
Patrolling soldiers demand identification from anyone wanting to
enter the eight-story building.
   But Heyn said ``we are trying everything'' to simplify
procedures for regaining East German citizenship.
   Wietsche, 33, a native East German who said he was jailed for 10
years for trying to flee to the West, said West German society
wasn't for him.
   ``But what made the biggest difference was the fall of Erich
Honecker,'' Wietsche said. The hard-line East German leader who
oversaw the construction of the Berlin Wall was ousted Oct. 18.
   A car mechanic, Wietsche said he moved legally to the Bavarian
city of Regensburg two years ago after he was released from jail.
He said he expects reforms to begin soon under Egon Krenz, who
replaced Honecker.
   A 48-year-old warehouse worker who would not give his name said
he left West Germany a few days ago after four years, feeling
``totally disappointed.''
   ``I was allegedly too old for a job,'' he said. ``It wasn't for
me. I wanted to come back mainly because of the security, which I
missed quite a bit in the Federal Republic.''
   The East German Red Cross, which said it was preparing for a
wave of up to 10,000 people returning, opened four reception
centers along the border with West Germany. Authorities in cities
such as Magdeburg and Erfurt readied emergency shelters in military
barracks, schools and dormitories.
   West German Red Cross officials in Bonn said buses were on
standby but no organized return was planned.
   Dispatches by East Germany's state-run news agency ADN Wednesday
suggested only a trickle of returnees had arrived at the official
centers.
   Officials said the flow back to East Germany would be difficult
to document since many people would simply return to their homes.
   East German officials say the government will loan each person
who returns 150 marks, or $82, in immediate aid and 15 marks, or
$8, for each day of unemployment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
