<FIRST>u a PM-Hostages-Fahrend 1stLd-Writethru a0486 11-16 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Fahrend, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Woman Reported Abducted Had Sought ``Chance in a Lifetime''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with West German authorities and
family source saying three were not abducted but robbed. Picks up 8th graf,
`A previously...'. SUBS 12th graf, `Eighteen other...', to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American woman who was reported abducted
in Lebanon with a West German friend and his son had described her
visit to the war-torn country as a ``chance in a lifetime.''
   Deborah Fahrend and the two others went to the West German
Embassy in Beirut today and insisted they had not been kidnapped. A
family source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the three
were robbed of their passports.
   Fahrend, 54, formerly of San Francisco, told her family she had
planned to write a book about Lebanon and that she had a publisher
lined up.
   ``It seems to me to be a chance in a lifetime,'' Fahrend wrote
in a recent letter to her 89-year-old mother, Margaret Brooks.
   Fahrend had written books of poetry that she had printed herself
and distributed to her friends and relatives, said Brooks.
   ``She's creative and wants to do something, and she's still
searching for her fulfillment, and that's why she's doing the
writing,'' Fahrend's sister, Emily Rowe, said in a telephone
interview from the family home in Davis, 70 miles northeast of San
Francisco.
   Fahrend chose her last name three years ago. It means
``traveling'' in German. Her last name had been Corra, from her
ex-husband, whom she divorced about 20 years ago. Fahrend had been
living in West Berlin for the last four years.
   A previously unknown group said in Beirut on Wednesday it had
kidnapped an American woman and two naturalized West Germans _ a
man born in Lebanon and his 7-year-old son.
   The claim was made in a typewritten statement in Arabic for a
group calling itself The Organization of Just Revenge. The
statement was delivered to a Western news agency with photocopies
of the passports and visas of the three people.
   It described the woman as Fahrend, calling her a
publisher-journalist. The others were identified as Mounir
Shamseddin Sami, 39, born in Lebanon, and his son, Danjel, born in
Berlin.
   Brooks briefly had discussed the trip to Lebanon on the
telephone with her daughter but didn't discuss the possible
dangers. The State Department warns Americans not to travel to
Lebanon.
   Eighteen foreigners are in captivity there, including eight
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   In a letter to her mother last week, Fahrend wrote she was going
to Beirut with ``Munir'': ``I'm going to use Munir's connections to
the hilt,'' she said, referring to diplomatic friends he had in
Lebanon who could put her in contact with Druze and Sunni
officials, according to her sister.
   The mother said Deborah referred to Munir as her ``therapist and
really good friend'' when they visited the United States this
spring.
   The Munir in the message apparently was the ``Mounir'' mentioned
in the statement from the terrorists.
   Rowe added that just before moving to West Berlin, Fahrend
finished a master's degree in creative writing at San Francisco
State. She earlier earned undergraduate degrees in international
administration and registered nursing.
   Jane McCullough, a friend who lived in San Geronimo, 20 miles
north of San Francisco, said she received a card from Fahrend last
week that had been mailed from Cyprus on Nov. 1.
   The card read: ``I'm sending this Christmas greeting early this
year as I know I'll be swamped when I return. I'm on my way to
Beirut to visit Munir's family. While there I'll be doing some
interviewing so I can write about it from more than just my
perspective.''
</TEXT>
