<HEAD>Gunman Kills Three at Tupelo Intersection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man out on bond on assault charges
brought by his former girlfriend shot and killed her and two blind
co-workers as she drove them home from work, authorities said.
   Joe L. Westbrooks was charged with three counts of murder in the
Wednesday afternoon shotgun slayings of Paula Pearson, 32; and the
two blind people, Willis Thrasher, 34; and Carolyn Sullivan, 45,
authorities said.
   Westbrooks, 30, apparently followed Pearson from work to the
intersection where the shooting took place, Police Chief Ed Crider
said. Witnesses said the man pulled up beside Pearson's car, jumped
out and fired several times into the car.
   Westbrooks was arrested moments after the shooting, and a
12-gauge shotgun was confiscated, Crider said.
   Detective Wayne Tutor said Westbrooks, 30, had been charged
earlier with burglary and assault in connection with attacks on
Pearson.
   Rob Russell, her employer at BHR Co., a publishing company, said
Westbrooks called Pearson twice Wednesday and threatened to kill
her.
   ``A girlfriend of hers tried to get her to call the police, but
she didn't want to get him in any more trouble than he was in,''
Russell said.
   Pearson, a mother of three children, ``carried these two people
home from work every night and would go get them in the morning,''
said Russell.
   Russell said Westbrooks had harassed the eight-week employee of
his company since the couple's breakup a month ago.
