<FIRST>r a PM-BondRating     11-16 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bond Rating,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Bond Rating Lowered, Tied with Louisiana As Nation's
Lowest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts has tied Louisiana with the lowest
long-term bond rating of any state in the nation.
   ``We are at the bottom of the barrel,'' State Treasurer Robert
Q. Crane said Wednesday after Moody's Investors Service downgraded
the state's $8.5 billion in long-term debt from ``A'' to ``Baa 1.''
   Moody's cited a $721 million budget deficit, which has stopped
Gov. Michael Dukakis from talking about the ``Massachusetts
Miracle,'' his term for the state's rebounding economy in the mid
1980s.
   The move came the day before the state went to market with $140
million in short-term notes to pay off overdue bills in the
Medicaid program, which pays medical bills for the poor.
   ``The magnitude of the projected deficit is made all the more
onerous by the apparent lack of consensus on how to deal with it,''
Moody's said.
   Standard and Poor's Corp., the other major Wall Street
credit-rating service, let the state keep its ``A'' rating, but
placed it on CreditWatch and said it would lower the rating if
Massachusetts didn't resolve its difficulties by next month.
   Lower credit ratings mean a borrower has a greater risk of
default and must pay higher interest rates on new debt to
compensate lenders for the additional risk.
   The lowering does not directly affect short-term notes. Their
rating was lowered in June from the highest MIG 1 rating to MIG 2,
according to Moody's Vice President George Leung.
   The state plans to sell $250 million in long-term debt next
month, and Administration and Finance Secretary L. Edward Lashman
said that is when the higher interest rate caused by the lowered
bond rating really will hurt.
   Dukakis said he was not surprised by the lowered credit rating,
and he and Lashman said it was time for the Legislature to raise
taxes to solve the deficit problem.
   ``We've known for months that unless and until we get this
budget into balance our credit rating was in jeopardy,'' Dukakis
said. ``The best and the fastest way to do it is to pass a
responsible revenue package.''
   Moody's strongly criticized the state's inability to deal with
the deficit.
   The ratings service noted that the Legislature soundly rejected
a tax increase earlier this year, ``expressing a preference for
expenditure reductions to achieve budget balance.''
   But Moody's said the deficit-reduction package being debated by
the House would be worth only about $400 million.
   Leung said the House's vote Tuesday to reject a $46 million
revenue-raiser _ confiscating unclaimed beer and soda bottle and
can deposits from wholesalers _ played a role in the lowering of
the rating.
   Lashman called that House move ``the most irresponsible vote I
have ever seen.''
   Leung said the ratings service did not care whether the state
balanced the budget with cuts or taxes, or both. However, he said
it was unlikely the Legislature would be willing to balance the
budget with cuts alone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-NoriegaOuster 2ndLd-Writethru a0492 11-16 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega Ouster, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0492,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0578 to restore copy at end</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Reportedly Launches Covert Bid to Overthrow Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs of Quayle comment after 5th graf, ``If there''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The CIA has launched a $3 million operation,
with the approval of congressional oversight committees, to
overthrow Panamanian Gen. Manuel A. Noriega, a newspaper reported
today.
   The covert operation has ``no restrictions'' other than an order
prohibiting Noriega's assassination and could involve U.S. troops,
the Los Angeles Times reported, citing unidentified sources.
   ``It is an unimpeded effort to try to topple Noriega,'' one
source told the Times. ``We're going into it with the understanding
that there may be loss of life, though the effort will be not to
kill anyone.''
   President Bush said at Andrews Air Force Base, Md., before
leaving for Houston today that he would neither confirm nor deny
the report.
   ``If there was a covert operation, would I discuss it, ever? It
wouldn't be covert if I even referred to it, so there will be no
such discussion of anything, which means I am not confirming nor
denying,'' he told reporters on Air Force One.
   Vice President Dan Quayle also declined to comment directly on
the report today. But when asked if it was proper for the United
States to try to get involved in an effort to oust Noriega, he
replied:
   ``It's certainly proper for the United States to state the
policy very clearly, and that policy is that the sooner Noriega
leaves power, the better off the people of Panama are going to be,
the better off the people of Central America are going to be. ...''
   Asked if the administration and Congress were still coordinated
on the effort to get Noriega out, Quayle said: ``The policy on
Panama and other issues are very closely coordinated with the
Congress. This president insists on consultation and he has gone
out of his way to consult with Congress on this and other matters.''
   The United States has been trying to oust Noriega since he was
indicted on drug-trafficking charges in February 1988 by federal
grand juries in Miami and Tampa, Fla.
   ``What it boils down to is that we want him alive in the United
States or dead,'' one source told the Times.
   Sources told the newspaper the CIA believes disgruntled officers
within the Panama Defense Forces are willing to collaborate in the
overthrow.
   The operation has been dubbed Panama-5 _ a referrence to past
actions against Noriega _ and reflects a renewed commitment by the
Bush administration, which drew criticism following the failed Oct.
3 coup attempt by dissident Panamanian military officers.
   Administration officials presented the plans for the operation
to Senate and House intelligence committees three weeks ago, the
Times said.
   During the failed October coup, the Bush administration said its
hands were tied by a 13-year-old executive order banning U.S.
involvement in the assassination of foreign figures.
   Last month, the Justice Department was assigned to make clear a
series of Ford administration executive orders regarding
clandestine action, the Times reported.
   A clarification memo was written by William P. Barr, assistant
attorney general in charge of legal counsel, sent to CIA Director
William H. Webster and finally delivered to the House and Senate
Intelligence committees, the newspaper said.
   According to the Times, the memo paves the way for more active
U.S. involvement in coup attempts not meant to result in
assassination but that could result in death.
</TEXT>
