<HEAD>Moldavian Leader Removed After Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE that activists petitioned for Grossu's
ouster, Grossu assigned to Moscow job. Pickup 5th graf `The activists...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moldavia's Communist Party chief was replaced
today after activists pushed for his ouster, saying he blocked
reform in the southwestern republic wracked by ethnic unrest.
   The official news agency Tass said Semyon K. Grossu was
``relieved of his duties'' by the republic's policy-making Central
Committee because of a transfer. It did not give his new post, but
the director of the republic's official news agency said he will
work in Moscow in an as-yet-undetermined job.
   His replacement is Pytor Luchinsky, 49, the No. 2 party official
in the republic of Tadzhikistan, Tass reported. The news agency
said he, like Grossu, is an ethnic Moldavian.
   There was no hint in the report that the Moldavian party was
unhappy with Grossu, but activists on Sunday began circulating a
petition demanding removal of conservatives in the top echelons of
the republic's government.
   Grossu and three of his deputies were on the petition because he
was an ``inactive arch-conservative'' blamed for economic,
ecological and political problems, said Konstantin Bogdanash, a
spokesman for the grassroots group People's Front that organized
the petition drive.
   The activists began the petition drive after a Nov. 10 clash
between police and protesters that left almost 200 people injured
in the capital, Kishniev.
   Grossu, 55, headed the Moldavian Communist Party since 1980 and
came under increasing pressure from nationalist activists to
reverse decades of ``Russification'' of the republic that borders
Romania.
   In the past year, Moldavian officials agreed to measures aimed
at preserving the Moldavian language and ethnic rights of the
indigenous population.
   Moldavia is one of the ethnic hotspots in the Soviet Union where
the local population is clamoring for more local control over the
culture, economy and politics.
