<FIRST>u w PM-Archives-Smoking 1stLd-Writethru a0443 11-16 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Archives-Smoking, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Investigating Pact Between Archives, Philip Morris</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New material, editing throughout with today's testimony.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional critic of an agreement between
Philip Morris Cos. and the National Archives to commemorate the
bicentennial of the Bill of Rights today lamented the ``pervasive
presence of tobacco companies on Capitol Hill.''
   The House subcommittee on transportation and hazardous materials
began an investigation of the agreement as the American Cancer
Society launched its 13th annual Great American Smokeout.
   Under the agreement, Philip Morris will donate $600,000 to the
National Archives Trust Fund in exchange for authority to publish
or broadcast announcements and materials promoting the 200th
anniversary of the Bill of Rights. The materials carry the names of
both Philip Morris and the National Archives.
   ``It's not the text of the ad that troubles me, it's the
context,'' said Rep. Chester G. Atkins, D-Mass.
   ``I am embarrassed, too, as a member of Congress by the
pervasive presence of tobacco companies on Capitol Hill ... you
can't have an event without it being cosponsored by the cigarette
industry,'' said Atkins.
   But Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., said, ``We have a long and
time-honored practice in the United States of allowing corporate
America to collaborate with public agencies in order to advertise
public events.''
   ``I would say, let's make one exception. Let's take a
corporation that sells a product that kills the largest number of
Americans ... let's say we'll put them in a little different
category,'' countered Atkins.
   ``Philip Morris has bought the exclusive rights to the
Constitution, which we entrusted to the National Archives, for the
modern equivalent of 30 pieces of silver or $600,000,'' Rep. Thomas
Luken, D-Ohio, chairman of the subcommittee, said in announcing
today's hearing.
   Luken and Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., called Wednesday for
investigations into the two-year agreement between Philip Morris
and the Archives after a consumer health group urged that the
contract be revoked.
   ``It's more than coincidental'' that the bicentennial campaign
began shortly before the society's annual nationwide cigarette-free
day, said Cancer Society spokesman Alan Davis.
   ``Every year just prior to the smokeout one company or another
tries to grab headlines and change the agenda,'' Davis said.
   ``There is no cigarette called Philip Morris,'' said Guy L.
Smith, the company's vice president of corporate affairs. He said
he did not believe the announcements violated the ad ban.
   ``In the same week that the Berlin Wall is being torn down, that
people in this country are being criticized for celebrating the
Bill of Rights is very strange,'' Smith said.
   Congress specifically encourages the Archives to accept
tax-exempt donations ``to enhance its archival and outreach
activities,'' said Archives' spokeswoman Susan Cooper.
   She also said such efforts by the cigarette maker are no
different from the company's past sponsorship of exhibits at the
National Gallery of Art.
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-New Mexico, has written Don Wilson, the
archivist of the United States, questioning how and why the
agreement was made. The Health Research Group, a consumer health
group, last week wrote Bingaman asking Congress to revoke the
August agreement.
   Critics question whether the broadcast announcements violate a
1971 federal ban on cigarette advertisements on television and
radio.
   ``The Philip Morris ads are running on television and do not
contain any health warning and apparently are a flagrant violation
of the law prohibiting such video commercials,'' Luken said.
   ``You have to ask what does advertising mean,'' said John
Banzhaf, chief counsel for Action on Smoking and Health, a consumer
group that led efforts for the federal restrictions. ``It seems to
me this is advertising, since at least one of their purposes,
directly or indirectly, is to encourage the sale of cigarettes,''
he said.
</TEXT>
