<FIRST>r a PM-AgentOrange     11-16 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Speeds Up Payments to Vietnam Vet Victims of Agent Orange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Vietnam veterans injured by the
toxic defoliant Agent Orange will get a big portion of their claim
payments before Christmas under a federal judge's order.
   ``The judge wants to get the payments to the veterans as soon as
possible,'' said Deborah Greenspan, a lawyer administering the
Agent Orange Veteran Payment Program.
   The disbursements, which will total nearly $30 million, won't
significantly change the total award an eligible veteran would
receive, but will provide a large share of it in a lump-sum payment.
   Some 9,300 veterans disabled by Agent Orange during their
Vietnam service will soon receive a single payment of as much as
$8,100, said Ms. Greenspan.
   ``From a veteran's point of view, I think it's significant,''
Ms. Greenspan said of the ruling made Wednesday by U.S. District
Judge Jack B. Weinstein of Brooklyn. ``It will give them a chunk of
money to work with.''
   The veterans getting the lump-sum checks will continue to
receive annual payments until 1994, but the amount of the annual
payments will be reduced to account for the lump-sum payment.
   Disabled veterans admitted into the Agent Orange Veteran Payment
Program by Wednesday are eligible for the payments, Ms. Greenspan
said.
   The changes, Weinstein said, are possible ``because an analysis
of claims processed to date reveals greater than expected funds
available for distribution. Such a `dividend' may not be possible
in future years in view of falling interest rates.''
   Weinstein, who oversees the program, also abolished on Wednesday
a requirement that applications to the program must have been filed
by March 1, 1989, or 120 days after the veteran dies or is found to
be disabled by exposure to the chemical.
   The judge also ruled that survivor payments can be made to a
veteran's parents, adult children and siblings. Under the previous
guidelines, compensation could be paid only to surviving spouses
and dependent children.
   The Agent Orange Settlement Fund was created by Weinstein in
1984 when seven chemical companies _ without admitting guilt _
agreed to pay $180 million to settle a class-action lawsuit brought
by Vietnam veterans and their families who alleged injuries because
of exposure to the chemical during the war.
   Agent Orange, widely used by American forces during the Vietnam
War, contained the highly toxic chemical dioxin. In their lawsuit,
veterans said exposure to the defoliant caused cancer and other
illnesses, as well as birth defects in their children.
</TEXT>
