<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Iowa 2ndLd-Writethru a0589-a059becauseof'specialassignment'feed)
11-16 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Iowa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0589-a0595-a0422,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Defends Probe, But Says Battleship Future May be in Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's top brass today defended the
service's safety record and investigation into the explosion aboard
the USS Iowa, but the Navy's top officer acknowledged that the
future of the Iowa and three other battleships may be ``up for
grabs'' because of budget pressures.
   Rear Adm. Richard Milligan told the Senate Armed Services
Committee that he stood by the initial findings of his
investigation into the gun-turret explosion that claimed the lives
of 47 sailors aboard the Iowa last April 19.
   Milligan said he remains convinced that one of the victims,
Gunner's Mate Clayton Hartwig, appeared to be the most likely
person to have set off the blast.
   He said additional technical tests conducted since he issued his
report on Sept. 7 found ``unique foreign material'' on the
projectile from the exploding gun barrel that would not have been
present during a normal firing of the Iowa's huge 16-inch guns.
   ``Now 3{ months later I know of nothing that would cause me to
change my report,'' Milligan said in a statement submitted to the
committee.
   Milligan's boss, Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, the chief of naval
operations, said under questioning by committee members that there
was ``no basis whatsoever for retiring the battleships as a
consequence'' of the recent spate of accidents that have hit the
Navy.
   However, Trost acknowledged that ``everything is up for grabs
today as we face a smaller out-year budget.''
   He said the four World War II-era battleships brought out of
mothballs several years ago have made a major contribution to the
nation's combat readiness.
   ``That doesn't say they're guaranteed to stay and they'll take
their shot with everybody else'' in the Pentagon as military
budgets tighten.
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that placing
the battleships back into monthballs was under consideration.
   Trost issued an unprecedented order on Tuesday that required a
sharp cutback in Navy training and operations in order to conduct a
wide-ranging safety evaluation into the accidents that have plagued
the service this year.
   He told senators he ordered the safety ``stand down'' in order
to discover whether there are ``some things we can or should do
better.''
   ``We aren't running our people into the ground,'' Trost said,
attempting to assure the lawmakers that neither budget cutbacks nor
a high number of operations have caused the string of accidents
over the past months.
   ``There is no central thread,'' Trost said, and preliminary
investigations have shown that some accidents were due to
mechanical failure, acts of God or problems with the performance of
the personnel involved.
   The admiral argued that the Navy's overall safety record has
steadily improved over the past five years with the number of major
accidents running from 118 in 1984 down to 67 in 1989. A major
accident is considered one in which a death or major loss of
equipment occurs.
   Trost said the Navy's duties to fly thousands of airplanes and
run hundreds of ships means that ``there will be mishaps ... Our
goal is to minimize them.''
   The admiral said he was looking for reports at the end of the
safety stand down in order to analyze whether the service could
improve its performance.
   The Navy admirals were greeted by the statements of several
skeptical senators, as well as some supporters, in the hearing room.
   In particular, Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., criticized the Navy's
Iowa report as one that ``seems based on supposition and guesswork
rather than fact and physical evidence.''
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, although not a member of the
panel, appeared as a representative from Hartwig's home state and
offered a statement sharply criticizing the Navy's findings.
   ``As a lawyer who formerly practiced law I can say unequivocally
that the Navy has no credible case against Clayton Hartwig,''
Metzenbaum said. ``There is not enough evidence to take to a grand
jury, let alone to get a jury to convict. Barring the introduction
of some new evidence, I believe it's clear that the Navy does not
know what caused the explosion.''
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, voiced similar reservations in an
interview earlier, saying: ``It's a mighty leap of faith for me to
take this information and jump to the conclusion Hartwig is it.''
   In the Milligan report, the Navy said it found Hartwig to be a
``loner'' who had few friends and was upset about the breakup of a
friendship with another sailor.
   The Naval Investigative Service garnered criticism for its part
in the investigation, since its agents queried Hartwig's family and
associates about a possible homosexual relationship after it was
discovered that Hartwig had designated Kendall Truitt, one of the
sailors who survived the blast, as the recipient of his life
insurance policy.
   In its report, however, the Navy said it found no evidence that
Hartwig was a homosexual.
   When the report was issued, Navy officials acknowledged that
their evidence was circumstantial in light of the fact that all the
witnesses, including Hartwig, were killed in the fiery blast.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of the House Armed
Services subcommittee on investigations, has said he ``seriously
questioned'' the Navy's report, and cited an FBI report that said
its laboratory investigation on the material found in the gun
barrel was inconclusive.
   ``We didn't find anything that would lead us to conclude that a
device was used to prematurely detonate the charge,'' an FBI
spokesman said last month. ``That's not to say something wasn't
there. Our findings were inconclusive.''
   The Senate inquiry was the first public congressional
questioning of Navy officials since the report was issued on Sept.
7.
   The House Armed Services panel is also looking into the
explosion, while the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, is conducting its own inquiry at the request of
Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio.
</TEXT>
