<FIRST>u a PM-ChildrenKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0543 11-16 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0543,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Children Found Stabbed, Mutilated; Mother Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with woman charged with murder; other detail
and to CORRECT spelling of children's names. No pickup. Note contents of
2nd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISBURG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three children under age 3 were strangled
or stabbed to death and mutilated with a steak knife, and their
mother was charged with murder, officials said today.
   ``Each child had multiple stab wounds, hundreds of stab
wounds,'' said Dr. J.B. Perdue Jr., Franklin County medical
examiner. He said the children's abdomens had been cut open and
their organs were found strewn about the house. ``It was one of the
worst things I've ever seen, if not the worst,'' he said.
   The mother, Katrina McKay, 20, was charged with three counts of
first-degree murder in the deaths Wednesday evening in her home in
rural Franklinton, northwest of here, said sheriff's department
Capt. Ralph Brown.
   Perdue said Ms. McKay left her children's bodies on a neighbor's
doorstep and was taken into custody after she broke into the man's
home. She was committed to John Umstead Hospital at Butner, a
psychiatric hospital, for observation, he said.
   ``I've been in law enforcement for 20 years in Franklin County
... I would say that this is one of the worst that I've
witnessed,'' said Sheriff Arthur Johnson. ``You wonder if you could
have found out something in advance to prevent this from
happening.''
   The victims were identified as Shenika Chantel McKay, 2, Terrell
Quentin McKay, 1, and Quincey Matthew McKay, 2 months, Perdue said.
   Perdue said electrical cords and clothing had been tied around
the children's necks ``in a strangulating fashion,'' but he did not
know whether it was before they were stabbed.
   A neighbor, George Harris Sr., told authorities Ms. McKay broke
into his home, naked and acting irrationally, and it took him 15
minutes to subdue her, Perdue said. The children's bodies were
found on his back doorstep, tied together with cord, Johnson said.
   ``She was very irrational, and he didn't know what was going on
and wrestled her to the floor,'' Perdue said, adding that Harris,
73, was not injured.
   Ms. McKay was treated at Franklin Regional Medical Center for
superficial stab wounds on her legs and neck before being taken to
the psychiatric hospital. After she was charged, officials said
they planned to transfer her to a psychiatric hospital in Raleigh
that has a prison section.
   Perdue said Ms. McKay, who is apparently unmarried, moved to
Franklin County several months ago.
   ``It was a neat little house,'' Perdue said. ``Of course it was
in disarray. TVs were turned over and there was a lot of trash and
things on the floor like hair rollers. On one of the children she
had used an electric hair curler cord to tie up the child and it
was still dangling from the child.''
   Harris told authorities he didn't know his neighbor personally.
His wife said the woman had borrowed their telephone earlier on the
day of the stabbings and got angry when she couldn't get through to
members of her family, Perdue said.
</TEXT>
