<FIRST>u w PM-VaughnWalker 1stLd-Writethru a0609 11-16 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vaughn Walker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee OK's San Francisco Attorney for Judicial Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 7, The committee, to CORRECT committee to club.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee today voted to
recommend confirmation of San Francisco attorney Vaughn Walker as a
federal judge, rejecting claims that he should be disqualified
because he waited too long to resign from a club that refuses to
accept women as members.
   ``I haven't found enough in the record to cause me to vote
against his nomination,'' Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, one of
Walker's critics, said as the panel sent the long-stalled candidacy
to the full Senate by an 11-2 margin.
   The committee also unanimously voted to send to the full Senate
the nomination of President Bush's cousin, District Judge John M.
Walker Jr. of New York, for a U.S. Court of Appeals seat.
   The full Senate is shooting for action on the nominations before
Thanksgiving and a number of others whisked through the committee
without debate.
   The nomination of Vaughn Walker _ no relation to John Walker _
for the District Court in California had been hanging fire for
almost two years and became more deeply embattled in February when
Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who is not on the Judiciary
Committee, came out against it.
   Vaughn Walker, who had strong backing from Sen. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif., resigned from San Francisco's Olympic Club in a letter
dated Feb. 15, almost a year after former President Reagan
nominated him for the judicial post.
   The club expressly barred blacks from membership until 1968 and
did not admit its first black member until last year. It still does
not accept women as full members, although unmarried daughters and
wives of members may play tennis there and take part in limited
other activities.
   Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy was a member of the club
until shortly before he was nominated for that post. Kennedy had
supported easing restrictions against women maintained by the club.
   Voting against Vaughn Walker, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
told the committee the nominee's resignation and contention that he
had worked to reverse the clu'bs discriminatory policy was
``nothing more than a cynical effort to get himself confirmed.''
Also opposing confirmation was Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Presidential cousin John Walker had been opposed for the appeals
bench by Harvard law Professor Alan Dershowitz, who said that the
nomination represented a violation of the nation's anti-nepotism
law.
   Dershowitz scoffed at the notion that his opposition stemmed
from friction between himself and John Walker arising out of an old
lawsuit. When the vote came, none of the committee members opposed
the nomination.
   Also getting favorable recommendations from the committee were
six other District Court nominees, Edwin L. Nelson of Alabama, .
Thomas Van Bebber of Kansas, Susan Webber Wright of Arkansas,
Edward W. Nottingham of Colorado, Arthur D. Spatt of New York and
Edward J. Lodge of Idaho.
   Receiving favorable recommendations from the panel were four
candidates for U.S. attorney. They were: Joyce J. George of Ohio,
Jean Paul Bradshaw of Missouri, Timonth D. Leonard of Oklahoma and
Gene W. Shepard of Iowa.
   The committee voted to recommend Cindy Shinga Daub of Nebraska
as a commissioner of the Copyright Royalty Tribunal. She is the
wife of former Rep. Hal Daub, R-Neb.
</TEXT>
