<DOCNO> AP891116-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Weapons-Radiation     11-16 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons-Radiation,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Orders Better Radiation Protection for Arms Plant Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at the Y-12 nuclear weapons plant in
Oak Ridge, Tenn., are not adequately protected from exposure to
radiation, a special federal inspection team said in a report
released Thursday.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins ordered his under secretary,
John Tuck, to prepare a plan for correcting a variety of safety and
environmental problems at Y-12 identified by the inspectors,
including the radiation protection flaws.
   The plant is owned by the Energy Department, but run by a
private contractor, Martin Marietta Energy Systems Inc.
   Tuck was ordered to complete the plan, with ``special
attention'' to radiation protection issues, by Friday, according to
an Oct. 27 Watkins memo attached to the inspection report.
   The inspection was performed from Sept. 25 to Oct. 20 by a
special group of private and government experts. They and other
similar groups assembled by Watkins last summer have been assessing
health, safety and environmental issues at many of the department's
nuclear weapons production and assembly facilities.
   The Y-12 plant, built in 1943 as part of the Manhattan Project
that developed the atomic bombs used against Japan in World War II,
employs about 7,000 people making components for nuclear weapons.
It is part of the government-owned Oak Ridge Reservation, a massive
complex about 20 miles west of Knoxville.
   Among the major flaws in the radiation protection system are a
failure of the plant's health physics specialists to routinely
check radiation levels in all areas where significant amounts of
radiation are generated, the report said.
   The report also said radiation survey results often are poorly
documented, and that the plant does not routinely check for flaws
in the warning devices and other safety features of equipment that
generates radiation. For example, such checks are not routinely
done on electron-beam welders, which produce radiation fields
comparable to, and sometimes higher than, X-ray machines, the
report said.
   The report said its inspectors noticed that no health physics
specialists were present to monitor radiation levels when workers
removed an air filter from the roof of a building, ``despite the
potential for spreading contamination on the roof and also for an
unmonitored release of airborne radiation.''
   Also, the report said ``safety work permits'' prepared for
employees at Y-12 were ``not an effective means of informing
workers of the radiological conditions that may be encountered at
the job site.''
   The report said Martin Marietta was aware of the shortcomings
and was working to correct them.
   The inspectors praised Martin Marietta managers' commitment to
health and safety goals, and said the plant's operations were
basically sound. However, the team found numerous potential
violations of federal and state environmental regulations,
including discharges of waste into East Fork Poplar Creek.
   The report said that while the environmental problems needed to
be corrected, ``none were of a nature that indicated undue risk to
public health or the environment with continued operation of the
Y-12 plant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ElderlyBypass     11-16 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly Bypass,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: No One is Too Old for Coronary Bypass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coronary bypass can help victims of heart
disease live better and longer even after they reach their 80s, and
no one should be denied the operation simply because of age, says a
study released Thursday.
   However, doctors cautioned that this common form of surgery
should be limited to folks who are healthy and independent except
for serious chest pain.
   ``All 80-year-olds are not created equal,'' said Dr. Gail E.
Darling. ``People with a lot of other illnesses are not considered
good candidates for bypass.''
   But if the patient is otherwise in good shape, she said, ``age
alone should not be a factor in the decision to proceed with
coronary bypass surgery.''
   Darling, a heart surgeon, based her recommendation on a review
of 159 octogenarians who underwent bypass surgery in the past 12
years at the Mayo Clinic. She presented her findings at the annual
scientific meeting of the American Heart Association.
   Before the operations, 97 percent of the patients had severe,
disabling chest pain that occurred while resting or during such
simple activities as cooking or walking. Afterward, most felt
dramatic relief from their symptoms and could lead more active
lives.
   An estimated 284,000 bypass operations were performed in the
United States in 1986. Darling said that while the surgery has
become relatively common for people in their 70s, many doctors are
still reluctant to perform it on older folks.
   The operation typically costs between $20,000 and $30,000. Some
have questioned whether it makes economic sense for the very old.
   ``Considering the skyrocketing cost of medical care, it will
become more and more of a philosophical issue,'' said Dr. Kent W.
Jones of the University of Utah. ``When do people get so old that
we say enough is enough?''
   The main drawback to the surgery was a relatively high death
rate of 11 percent. However, if they survived long enough to be
discharged from the hospital, the patients did relatively well.
   Overall, 84 percent of those undergoing surgery survived at
least one year, and 70 percent were still alive after five years.
   Darling said this was as good as typical survival for people
that age and better than what would be expected for those with
serious heart disease.
   Between 1977 and 1983, less than one-half of 1 percent of all
bypass patients at the Mayo Clinic were over 80. Since then, this
has grown to about 3 percent.
   The patients suffered pain because the arteries that carry blood
to their hearts had become clogged. During the operations, surgeons
used pieces of blood vessel to detour blood around the blockages,
restoring free flow to the heart.
</TEXT>
