<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-PriestsKilled 3rdLd-Writethru   11-16 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Priests Killed, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0598,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Jesuit Priests Tortured And Slain in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL-2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with priests accusing soldiers
of involvement, army denying charge. Pickup 7th, `Tojeira identified...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Jesuits priests were
tortured and killed today at a leading Roman Catholic university,
and a priest said uniformed soldiers were seen entering the
priests' residence before the shooting began.
   The government and armed forces denied that any troops were
involved in the massacre, which occurred during the sixth day of
fierce fighting between leftist guerrillas and soldiers of the
rightist government.
   The dead included the rector and vice-rector of Simeon Canas
Central American University. The cook and her 15-year-old daughter
who worked at the home also were slain.
   ``They were assassinated with lavish babarity. For example, they
took out their brains,'' said the Rev. Jose Maria Tojeira, the
Jesuit Provincial for Central America. He said the victims were
tortured before they were slain.
   The priests were killed, their faces disfigured and their brains
removed from their skulls at the home they shared at the
university, one of Central America's most prestigious insitutions
of higher learning.
   ``If this spiral of violence continues, death and destruction
will sweep away many, especially those who are of most use to our
people,'' San Salvador's Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas said after
leading a prayer over the mutilated bodies.
   A Jesuit priest who spoke on condition of anonymity told
journalists at the site that a witness saw about 30 uniformed
soldiers enter the university grounds and the priests' residence
shortly before the shots rang out.
   ``There have been soldiers posted at the gate since Sunday. The
murders were committed in the middle of a curfew. The same house
where they were killed was raided and searched by soldiers on
Tuesday,'' said the priest.
   The massacre took place during heavy fighting in San Salvador,
where guerrillas of the leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front were trying to hold on to positions they seized on Saturday.
   The armed forces and government rejected the accusation that
troops were involved in the killings. In a communique the National
Information Center, termed the slayings ``savage and irrational.''
   It said the crime ``is intended to destablize the democratic
process and increase even more the climate of anguish created by
the FMLN (Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front).''
   The communique said an investigation into the slayings has begun.
   Eduardo Valdez, Director of Jesuit Studies, said the Jesuits had
received many anonymous threats in past days and that a rightist
death squad was probably responsible for the killings. The extreme
right has for more than a decade accused the Jesuit order and its
university of fostering subversive leftist ideology.
   Tojeira identified the victims as Ignacio Ellacuria, rector of
the Jose Simeon Canas Central American University; Ignacio
Martin-Baro, the vice rector; and educators Segundo Montes, Amando
Lopez, Juan Ramon Moreno and Joaquin Lopez Lopez.
   The home of the Jesuits is located behind the university campus,
on the southwest side of the capital, where there has been fighting
between guerrillas and government troops. The bulk of the fighting,
however, was on the east and north sides and part of the west-side
of the city.
   One priest at the university, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he and other neighbors mistook the shooting at the
Jesuits' home as part of the fighting. Reporters who saw the
victims at the house said their bodies were riddled with bullets,
some of them fired at the heads.
   All but Lopez Lopez, a native Salvadoran, were Spanish by birth
and naturalized Salvadorans.
   The university is one of the most highly regarded institutions
of higher learning in Central America.
   The slain servant was identified as Julia Elba Ramos. He
15-year-old daughter, Celina, was also killed, said Tojeira.
   ``They did not want to leave witnesses,'' said Valdez.
</TEXT>
