<FIRST>r a AM-GayRights     11-16 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Rights,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Opposed to Gay Rights Law Starts Repeal Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of Massachusetts' gay rights law
launched a repeal campaign Thursday one day after Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis signed the measure.
   A coalition filed petitions with the secretary of state's office
seeking a referendum on the law, which bans discrimination against
homosexuals in housing, employment and credit. Massachusetts is the
second state to enact such a law.
   ``We intend to blow this bill to smithereens,'' said the Rev.
Earl W. Jackson. ``We intend to defeat this legislation and bury it
so deep no one will ever find it again.''
   Nancy Sutton, chairman of Citizens for Families First, the group
leading the repeal movement, said, ``When this question has been
taken to the people for a vote anywhere in the nation, people
clearly reject it.''
   ``Protecting and thereby encouraging behavior that is contrary
to traditional family life is harmful to every member of society,''
she said.
   Sutton filed petitions bearing 10 signatures, including those of
former Gov. John Volpe, former Boston Mayor John Collins, state
Sen. Edward Kirby, a Republican, to start the referendum campaign.
To get the repeal question on the 1990 ballot, gay-rights opponents
must collect 25,263 signatures.
   Before Massachusetts, Wisconsin was the only state with a
gay-rights law.
   Kirby, who led the fight in the state Senate against the bill,
said, ``It is giving special privileges to a group who chose to
belong to it. Now this will go to the people. The people have a
right to be heard on this issue.''
   Arline Isaacson, co-chair of the Massachusetts Gay and Lesbian
Political Caucus, said of the repeal effort: ``I'm disappointed and
I'm frustrated, but more than that I am appalled. This bill gives
us equal protection under the law.''
   ``This doesn't mean people have to like gays or approve of our
lifestyle,'' she said.
</TEXT>
