<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JONESBORO, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbye Turner says her biggest surprise
after becoming Miss America was how little it changed her.
   ``I always had this image of Miss America being superhuman,''
she said. ``She was bigger than life and perfect, ... But what I
found is I'm still just Debbye. Being Debbye was enough to win the
title and has been enough to carry the title.''
   Miss Turner, 24, returned to Jonesboro, where she grew up, for a
two-day celebration that ended Thursday.
   The events in Jonesboro marked Miss Turner's second homecoming
since her crowning two months ago. Last month, she was honored in
her adopted town of Mexico, Mo., where she lived while attending
the University of Missouri-Columbia Veterinary School of Medicine.
   Although she entered the Miss America pageant as Miss Missouri,
Miss Turner said Wednesday that Jonesboro is home.
   ``This is going to sound really corny to say, but to this point
the most exciting thing ... is coming home,'' Miss Turner said
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filmmaker Roger Corman, who was quick to
start work on ``The War of the Satellites'' following the 1957
Soviet launch of Sputnik, is ready to dramatize headlines again
with a Berlin-based movie.
   The movie, titled ``The Day The Wall Came Down,'' won't be a
documentary of the recent East German reforms that included opening
the wall separating the two Berlins, Corman said Tuesday.
   ``I didn't want to do a totally political story,'' he said. ``So
I wrote over the weekend an outline of an espionage thriller laid
against the tearing down of the wall.''
   Corman, who started work on the 1957 drama one day after the
Soviet satellite was launched, said he has already shown the script
idea to Bavarian Film Studios and won tentative approval to start
shooting in Germany by springtime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguayan author Augusto Roa Bastos on
Thursday won the Cervantes Prize, popularly known as the Nobel for
literature in the Spanish language.
   The 72-year-old author is best known for his 1974 historical
novel ``I, The Chief,'' about the 19th century Paraguayan dictator
Jose Gaspar Rodriguez de Francia.
   The prize, awarded by the Ministry of Culture for the work of a
lifetime, carries a $86,200 prize. It is named after 16th century
Spanish writer Miguel de Cervantes, author of ``Don Quixote'' and
considered by many to be the father of the novel.
   Spanish sociologist Juan Marichal, a member of the jury, said
Roa Bastos was picked for the high quality of his writing and also
because he wrote most of his works in exile.
   The author makes his home in Toulouse, France, where he taught
at the university before his retirement. During a civil war in
Paraguay in 1947, he was forced into exile to Buenos Aires. He
returned to Paraguay in 1970 but left soon afterward to live in
Europe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nashvile music lovers will help play
Santa Claus for San Francisco earthquake victims at a two-night
benefit auction and show headlined by singer John Hiatt and The
Allman Brothers band.
   At least 39 other acts will join them for the shows Nov. 29 and
Nov. 30 in Nashville, InterNash productions announced Wednesday.
   New toys collected at the door will be sent to the Bay area Toys
for Tots program in time for Christmas.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos, honorary chairman of the event,
says proceeds will go to the Northern California Earthquake Relief
Fund.
