<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Moldavia     11-16 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Moldavia,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moldavian Chief Replaced After Strikes, Protests, Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moldavia's Communist Party chief was removed
Thursday after activists criticized him for slowing reforms in his
republic, wracked by ethnically motivated strikes, clashes and
demonstrations.
   The republic's policy-making Central Committee relieved Semyon
K. Grossu as its first secretary because of a transfer to another
job, Tass said. It did not identify his new post, but the director
of the republic's official news agency said Grossu would work in
Moscow in a yet-to-be determined job.
   Grossu's replacement is Pytor Luchinsky, 49, who has been
serving as the second highest party official in the republic of
Tadzhikistan, Tass reported. Like Grossu, Luchinsky is an ethnic
Moldavian.
   Moldavia is one of the many ethnic trouble spots in the Soviet
Union where the population is clamoring for more control over its
culture, economy and politics, and is running into opposition from
ethnic minorities led by Russians.
   The Tass report did not hint the Moldavian party was unhappy
with Grossu, but activists on Sunday began circulating a petition
demanding removal of conservatives among the republic's top
officials.
   Grossu and three of his deputies were on the list because he was
an ``inactive arch-conservative'' blamed for economic, ecological
and political problems, said Konstantin Bogdanash, a spokesman for
the grassroots group People's Front that organized the petition
drive.
   The People's Front began the campaign after a Nov. 10 brawl
between police and protesters that left almost 200 people injured.
The demonstrators were demanding the release of 20 people arrested
three days earlier while trying to stage another protest.
   Activist Pyotor Shornikov, a leader of a group representing
ethnic minorities in Moldavia, has called the southwestern republic
once ruled by Leonid I. Brezhnev ``one of the epicenters of
stagnation,'' and Grossu has become a target of growing criticism.
   Asked why Grossu was removed, Fyodr A. Angeli, the director of
ATEM, Moldavia's news agency, said by telephone from the Moldavian
capital of Kishinev that the step was ``logical'' after the events
of Nov. 7 and 10. But he added Grossu had been talking for at least
a half-year about stepping down.
   Grossu, 55, headed the Moldavian Communist Party since 1980 and
came under increasing pressure from nationalist activists to
reverse decades of ``Russification'' of the southwestern republic
on the border with Romania. In the past year, Moldavian officials
agreed to measures aimed at preserving the Moldavian language and
ethnic rights of the indigenous population.
   But strikes and demonstrations became common as ethnic
Moldavians and ethnic minorities living in the republic led by
Russians traded charges of discrimination. Of the republic's 4.2
million people, 64 percent are Moldavians, with the rest Russians,
Ukrainians, Bulgarians, Jews and Christian Turks.
   Grossu appeared on the national TV newscast ``Vremya'' on
Wednesday saying a package of economic reforms, including spending
more money on food and consumer goods supplies and the social and
cultural spheres, ``should help ease the tension in our republic.''
   Bogdanash, also speaking by telephone from Kishinev, predicted
Moldavians would welcome Luchinsky's election because he is
respected as ``cultured, politically experienced, energetic and
intelligent.'' Before moving to Tadzhikistan, Luchinsky worked as
the No. 2 party official in Moldavia.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Communist Party chiefs
have been replaced in many of the ethnically troubled republics, in
many cases with more liberal officials. These include Estonia,
Lithuania, Armenia, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan and the
Ukraine.
</TEXT>
