<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Beaujolais     11-16 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beaujolais,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beaujolais Lives Up to 1989 Harvest Expectations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK McDOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wine lovers uncorking the 1989 Beaujolais nouveau
on Thursday nearly unanimously agreed the pricey wine heralds great
promise for other French wine-producing regions.
   Sophisticated and pedestrian palates confirmed predictions by
promoters that the fruity young wine _ the first released since the
autumn grape harvest _ ranks as the best in decades.
   ``You never know how good a wine is going to be until you drink
it,'' lawyer Yves Milon said at a party celebrating the ritual
opening of the first bottles of the new wine on the third Thursday
of November. ``Now that I've tasted it, I know.''
   ``If all the '89 wines are this good, it's going to be a great
year,'' he said.
   Robert Cointepas, owner of the Taverne Henri IV near Notre Dame
Cathedral, detailed his satisfaction with the wine's clarity, color
and bouquet as shouts of ``Vive le nouveau!'' rang out from
indulgent tipplers packed into his celebrated wine bar.
   John Powell, 26, of Palo Alto, Calif., had a somewhat more basic
measure of quality: ``If I'm still standing in five hours, that'll
tell you how good it is.''
   A consumption embargo on the wine was lifted at midnight
Wednesday, but most Parisians held off serious drinking until the
early morning. At lunchtime Thursday, dozens of parties sprang up
throughout the capital.
   Promoters called the 1989 stock the best in a quarter-century.
   ``This is an exceptional year for Beaujolais and all the
vintages in France,'' said Michel Deflache of the Union
Interprofessionnelle des Vins du Beaujolais, the producers
association.
   Wine drinkers around the world await the beverage each November
arriving by plane, train, truck and ship in a massive public
relations campaign.
   Hundreds of Japanese raced to Tokyo's international airport
Wednesday night to get a first taste of the wine at midnight, eight
hours before the wine was allowed to be uncorked in France.
   The marketing by Deflache's organization has boosted the
little-known first-press wine to world fame in two decades while
critics and admirers continue to debate the wine's real merits.
   ``Twenty years ago, this wine was nothing and it's still
nothing,'' declared Jacques Constant at the Bar St. Philippe in the
fashionable Faubourg St. Honore shopping district. ``The real
French wines are the Bordeaux and Bourgogne.''
   Bar owner Rene Bourel vigorously disagreed. ``I prefer the
Beaujolais to the Bordeaux. Why? It's like a blonde woman or a
brunette, a matter of taste.''
   A long dry summer and early rain-free harvest have led to
expectations that this year's French wines could rank among the
best this century.
   As the first wines of the year, the Beaujolais nouveau, normally
considered an inexpensive lightweight, served as a bellwether to
both quality and the price the market will bear.
   Wholesale Beaujolais nouveau rose as much as 30 percent this
year, Deflache said, retailing for an average of $4 per bottle in
Paris and nearly $17 in Tokyo.
   About half of this year's production of 4.4 million cases went
to foreign markets, principally West Germany, Britain, Belgium, the
United States and Japan.
   The Japanese market remains the fastest-growing, Deflache said,
with demand jumping from 300,000 cases in 1988 to 440,000 cases
this year. The U.S. market represents an equivalent number of sales.
</TEXT>
