<DOCNO> AP891116-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade Bjt   11-16 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Falls to Lowest Level in Five Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's merchandise trade deficit in
September tumbled to $7.9 billion, its smallest imbalance in nearly
five years, the government said Thursday in a report that analysts
viewed as evidence of strong overseas economies but weakness at
home.
   The Commerce Department said the September deficit fell 21.4
percent from August, when the trade gap posted a $10.1 billion
difference, the largest of the year.
   The drop resulted from a 3.9 percent decline in imports to $39
billion and a 1.9 percent gain in exports to $31.1 billion. The
deficit is the difference between the two.
   Analysts said that while the improvement is encouraging on the
surface, it is, as chief economist Allen Sinai of the Boston Co.,
said, ``coming about principally from a weak U.S. economy and very
prosperous overseas economies.''
   Reaction also was unenthusiastic on Wall Street, where stock
market observers also interpreted the drop in imports as evidence
of weakening consumer spending.
   But the figures were good news for the Bush adminstration, which
based its predictions of healthy economic growth partly on the
belief that exports would keep expanding.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said that while imports have
fallen back to their monthly average for the year, exports remain
high. Mosbacher noted the figures were in line with administration
expectations of a 1989 deficit ranging between $105 billion and
$110 billion.
   But Treasury Undersecretary David Mulford told a Senate Banking
subcommittee that while Thursday's trade report was ``very
positive,'' the improvement could stall by next year unless the
United States and its major trading partners do a better job of
coordinating their economic policies.
   ``Further improvement ... during 1990 ... we think will be
modest at best and there's soe possibility of a deterioration,'' he
said. ``However, it's interesting to note that the adjustment
process continues.''
   To maintain progress on shrinking the trade gap, the U.S. must
push down its budget deficit and Japan and West Germany must
stimulate their domestic demand for imports, he said.
   The trade gap for the first nine months on an annualized basis
was $107.2 billion, compared with a $118.5 billion imbalance for
all of 1988.
   The September imbalance was the narrowest since a $6.8 billion
deficit in December 1984.
   Leading the exports was a 72.8 percent gain in civilian aircraft
shipments to $1.97 billion. Mosbacher said most of the aircraft
went to Western Europe.
   The United States is running a $1.4 billion trade surplus with
the European Economic Community for the year. Sinai said that was
evidence of prosperous economies since those nations continue to
buy U.S. goods despite a relatively expensive dollar, which make
those goods more costly.
   Michael K. Evns, of Evans Economics Inc. in Washington, said
European growth has doubled from 1988 to 1989 and its economy will
continue to be robust for the next two or three years, enhancing
the export outlook.
   At the same time, Americans spent less on imports in September,
particularly for big-ticket capital goods and other industrial
materials used in manufacturing.
   ``This confirms the manufacturing recession that seems to be in
place,'' Sinai said.
   An exception to the drop in imports was consumer goods, which
rose slightly, not surprising since consumers have continued to
spend dispite weakness in manufacturing.
   The manufacturing sector has been particularly hit by
sluggishness as the Federal Reserve slows the economy by keeping a
tight rein on credit to contain inflation.
   In addition to aircraft, export improvements included office
equipment and machinery, automobiles, telecommunications equipment
and industrial machinery.
   The nation's foreign oil bill fell 7.6 percent to $4 billion in
September. The amount of imported oil dropped to 8.2 million
barrels a day from 8.7 million in August, while the price per
barrel rose to $16.38 from $16.14.
   As usual, the largest trade deficit in September was with Japan,
an imbalance of $4.1 billion, up from $4 billion in August. The
deficit was $1.3 billion with Taiwan, $700 million with Canada,
$500 million with South Korea and $700 million with China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
