<DOCNO> AP891116-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RICO     11-16 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RICO,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>RICO Overhaul Bill Stalls as Senators Rally to DeConcini</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate efforts to overhaul the nation's
racketeering law stalled Thursday while members of both parties
rallied to defend the sponsor, Arizona Democrat Dennis DeConcini,
from consumer advocate Ralph Nader's charge that the bill was
designed to dilute curbs against white-collar crime.
   ``This isn't just some little Mickey Mouse bill that's supported
by business,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, declared after the bill
bogged down in the Judiciary Committee.
   The DeConcini measure would overhaul the 1970 Racketeer
Influenced Corrupt Organizations Act. The law, known as RICO, for
short, was primarily intended as a weapon against criminal mobs.
   Recent years, however, have witnessed a sharp upturn in civil
lawsuits filed under RICO against insurance companies, savings and
loan associations, accounting firms and an array of other
businesses.
   DeConcini's bill would cut back on provisions that enable those
who file such RICO suits to collect triple damages.
   The Judiciary Committee had been expected to draw up its final
version of the bill and send it to the floor on Thursday. But
efforts to do so broke down when the committee ran out of time with
Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, saying he still had substantial
reservations.
   ``I'm willing to reform RICO but not to gut it,'' Metzenbaum
said.
   Judiciary Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., said that he
would try to make time for a full-scale debate on the measure
within the committee before Thanksgiving, when lawmakers hope to
have their work wrapped up for the year.
   But it appeared that final committee action on the measure might
have to wait until next year.
   After the bill stalled, members of the committee rallied to
defend DeConcini against Nader's charges a day earlier. Biden said
he had seen ``nothing but good, solid, reasonable intentions from
the senator from Arizona.''
   ``I think it's shameful to in any way question the motives of
Sen. DeConcini for his involvement in this bill,'' Metzenbaum said.
   ``I think the senator from Arizona has been badly maligned on
this bill just in the last couple of days,'' Hatch said.
   On Wednesday, Nader counted DeConcini among ``a panoply of
purchased politicians'' who aided Phoenix financier Charles
Keating, the central figure in the burgeoning Lincoln Savings and
Loan scandal.
   Nader's charge was rooted in the testimony of Edwin J. Gray,
former chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, who told a
House panel earlier this month that DeConcini, in the presence of
four other senators, once asked him to drop a rule barring risky
investments by Lincoln Savings. DeConcini and the others all
disputed Gray's account of the conversation.
   ``Now the ringleader of the Keating Five, Sen. DeConcini, is
responding to the swirling controversy by pushing a bill that would
weaken the white-collar crime laws,'' Nader told a news conference.
He said DeConcini's bill ``would gut the very law used by
regulators against his friend Charles Keating.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
