<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionClinics     11-16 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Clinics,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Law Has Nationwide Impact, Abortion Rights Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois abortion clinic regulations, if
upheld in a key Supreme Court case, would have a devastating
nationwide impact on women's access to the operation, abortion
rights groups said Thursday.
   The regulations have ``the potential to seriously curtail, if
not eliminate entirely, the ability of most American women to
choose abortion,'' said Barbara Radford, head of the National
Abortion Federation. If the court upholds the Illinois law, she
said, ``it could turn the clock back to an era of virtual
prohibition of abortion.''
   The federation and Planned Parenthood announced the results of a
national survey that said 98 percent of abortion clinics would be
violating at least one of the Illinois rules if they were adopted
by the clinics' home states.
   Three-fourths of the clinics said the regulations would force
them to relocate and could drive them out of business.
   Supporters of the Illinois law have said the impact would be
minimal _ adding $45 to the cost of an abortion.
   The high court plans to hear arguments in the Illinois case Dec.
5. But talks are under way between state officials and an abortion
clinic owner to settle the dispute and eliminate the need for a
ruling by the justices.
   Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan, a Democrat who plans to
run for governor next year, is leading the effort to reach a
settlement.
   Ms. Radford said even if a compromise disposes of the Illinois
case, the issues it raised will remain alive.
   ``We're still going to see efforts by other states to adopt
regulations almost identical'' to the Illinois law, she said.
   The 254 clinics that responded to the survey announced Thursday
perform about one-third of the 1.5 million abortions each year in
the United States. Nearly all said conforming to the regulations
would be extremely costly and perhaps impossible.
   The Illinois regulations were declared unconstitutional by
federal courts that said they would force the clinics to become
``the functional equivalent of small hospitals.''
   For example, the rules require separate facilities such as
lockers and lavatories for male and female employees and eight-foot
wide corridors for patients.
   Dr. Louise Tyrer of Planned Parenthood, in a statement read by
colleague William Hamilton, said the rules are not designed to
protect the health of women.
   ``We have a case of politicians claiming to know more about
medical procedure than the medical profession. These politicians
would have us all believe that abortions are dangerous,'' Dr. Tyrer
said. She said abortions are safer than practically any other
commonly performed surgery.
   The Supreme Court is reviewing two other abortion cases this
term. They test the validity of Minnesota and Ohio laws requiring
notification of parents whose minor daughters want abortions.
   The justices in July gave states new power to regulate
abortions, upholding a Missouri law while stopping short of
overturning their 1973 ruling that said women have a constitutional
right to an abortion.
   The July ruling touched off widespread activity in state
legislatures and state political races.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
