<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearTesting     11-16 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Testing,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evacuees from Atoll Say It's Still Unsafe 4 Decades After N-Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Rongelap, a tiny Pacific atoll,
contended Thursday that their island remains unsafe nearly four
decades after the U.S. government tested a nuclear bomb in the area.
   ``The Rongelap people wish to return home,'' said Jeton Anjain,
who respresents the Rongelapese in the Marshall Islands government.
``However, we will only return home if Rongelap Atoll is determined
to be safe.''
   Such a determination could be made only through a comprehensive
radiological survey of the atoll, which has not been done since the
so-called ``Bravo'' test irradiated the area in 1954, he told a
House interior subcommittee hearing.
   The Reagan and Bush administrations have contended that Rongelap
is safe for habitation. Roughly 350 Rongelapese, concerned about
incidents of leukemia and tyroid cancer, evacuated the island in
1985 to live on Mejato, another island.
   Anjain said the Energy Department believes the Rongelapese
should return to their home island ``despite the fact that the
Rongelap environment today is highly contaminated with radiation.''
   Non-voting Delegate Ron de Lugo, D-V.I. and the chairman of the
insular and international affairs subcommittee, said that although
government officials have used a 1982 study to back up claims
Rongelap is safe, ``the report realy made no such finding.''
   But Bush administration officials said they would spend the next
six months reviewing the literature and studies on Rongelap.
   The six-month review, requested by the Energy Department, will
``conduct an internal review of how the agency reached its present
position on the issue of safety and habitability on Rongelap,''
said Stella Guerra, the assistant secretary of interior.
   ``The Department of Interior shares the desire of the energy
secretary to ensure that all health and environmental impacts, and
the concerns of the Rongelap people, have been properly
addressed,'' she said in prepared remarks.
   Rongelap is part of the Marshall Islands, a former U.S. trust
territory. The islands now have a commonwealth relationship with
the United States under the Compact of Free Association.
   Under the compact, the United States agreed to pay nuclear test
victims $150 million in exchange for the Marshall Islands giving up
the claims of its citizens.
   Some of that money was used for an independent scientific review
of the 1982 Energy Department report. De Lugo said information in
the preliminary review, completed in May 1988, ``appears to be
troubling.''
   Among other things, de Lugo said, the review stated that
Rongelap may be safe for adults but more study is needed to
determine if children are safe.
   The review also said people would have to mostly rely on
imported food for 30 to 50 years.
</TEXT>
