<FIRST>r a AM-Congress-PayReax     11-16 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Pay Reax,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Hosts Vow Won't Be Caught Off-Guard When Senate Debates Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Pay, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED GOLDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The network of radio talk show hosts credited with
defeating an effort to raise congressmen's pay says it was caught
off guard when the House sped toward another salary increase, but
it's mobilizing for the debate in the Senate.
   Sparked by consumer advocate Ralph Nader, radio talk show hosts
around the country began a rush Thursday to urge listeners to
revolt, and fast. The Senate could vote on raises Friday.
   One of the biggest complaints of the talk show hosts was the way
the latest effort took by surprise those who earlier this year were
deemed instrumental in killing a pay raise.
   ``Mostly, the response we've been hearing is about the process,
about getting it done in a couple of days. Nobody really knew about
it and they perceive it as a scheme on the part of leadership, that
`leadership is in the tank,''' said Jerry Williams, the talkmaster
at Boston station WRKO who helped spearhead a campaign against the
last congressional pay raise plan, which included a deluge of
teabags sent to Capitol Hill.
   Williams said Nader notified him of the quick proposal and vote
in the House.
   ``It's just a backroom political deal that they are ramrodding
through in the dark of night,'' said Mike Siegel of KING in
Seattle. ``It flies in the face of everything in the system. They
announced it one day and voted on it the next day without any
chance for public discussion.''
   Siegel said there were a few actions that should have been taken
before any raise was considered.
   ``There should have been no raise of any kind considered until
there is a statute eliminating the honoraria,'' he said. ``And they
should have included a statute that the raises take effect with the
next congressional session.
   But since the House on Thursday approved a plan that would raise
pay from $89,500 to $120,000 within less than 14 months, Williams,
Seigel and their broadcasting cohorts have begun focusing attention
on the Senate, where debate will continue.
   ``It will be a little easier for people to respond because they
don't have to respond to so many lawmakers _ there are only two
senators in their state,'' Williams said, who began Thursday's
program by giving out the Washington phone numbers of Senate
leaders.
   ``All these folks in Congress say they are having trouble
attracting new blood. Well, I don't think they will have any
problem now,'' said Tom Leykis, of KFI in Los Angeles.
   ``Next year, a week before Election Day, I will read out loud
the names of everyone who voted for the pay raise, every day, and
make sure they get new blood in there,'' he said. ``If that's what
they want, the pay raise, then that's what they are going to get.''
   WJNO in West Palm, Fla., held a ``battle of the talk show
hosts'' Thursday with four hosts on the air at once.
   ``Congressmen should not be paid so much that they are making
five times what the average wage earner takes home,'' said Jack
Cole, who said his local listeners were about 80 percent against
the raise.
</TEXT>
