<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AFL-CIO-Abortion     11-16 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO-Abortion,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Ducks Abortion Stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO declined Thursday to take a stand
on abortion, an issue which split labor leaders on the final day of
a convention dedicated to union unity.
   Though pro-choice oratory dominated the final session, the
convention put aside for study a half-dozen resolutions calling
upon the union to embrace, in one way or another, the stance taken
by most of its political allies, including the Democratic Party and
various women's and civil rights groups.
   The four-day gathering was highlighted by the appearance of
Polish Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and a number of rowdy
demonstrations to promote labor unity in several major strikes.
   Labor traditionally has steered clear of the abortion issue, and
had any of the resolutions come up for a vote it was likely that
the federation's older, predominantly male leaders could have
mustered the strength to defeat them.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland himself said two months ago that
he did not believe the federation should take a stand on abortion.
   Kirkland and other leaders struck a deal with the pro-choice
sponsors to allow for the speechmaking and then refer the
resolutions to the federation's Executive Council.
   ``We did not choose this issue,'' said Susan Cowell, vice
president of the International Ladies Garment Workers Union and a
leading member of a small but vocal group of women labor activists.
``The Reagan courts have forced us to take a stand on this issue.
... The labor movement must choose sides and lead as we always
have.''
   Nine delegates, including two men, spoke in favor of adopting
pro-choice positions. Although no one spoke against the proposals,
the socially conservative leaders of the federation's building
trades unions remain opposed and wield considerable power on the
Executive Council.
   Still, several influential council members interviewed this week
predicted the 33-member board would endorse a woman's right to
choose to have an abortion if it could agree on language
acknowledging moral and religious concerns. The sponsors of the
pro-choice resolutions urged the council to act by its February
meeting. A decision then could determine whether labor makes the
issue a factor in its support of 1990 political candidates.
   ``Let us now be in the vanguard regarding the rights of our
women,'' said Arlene Collins of the Oregon AFL-CIO, the first state
federation to adopt a pro-choice platform. ``The elections of the
past few days have proven that pro-choice is not divisive, but a
winner,'' she said, referring to victories by pro-choice candidates
in the New Jersey and Virginia gubernatorial races a week ago.
   ``It is working women, poor women who will pay with their lives
and their futures is we sit by and government interferes,'' said
Mary Butz of the Sacramento (Calif.) Central Labor Council.
   The labor movement has longstanding ties to the Catholic church,
and some opponents of the pro-choice resolutions have said
privately that taking such a stance could hurt union organizing
among blue-collar Catholics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
