<FIRST>r w AM-LivestockExports     11-16 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Livestock Exports,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Value of Sales Abroad Climbs 14 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of U.S. dairy, livestock and poultry
exports in the first half of 1989 was more than $3.6 billion, up 14
percent from the same period last year, the Agriculture Department
said Thursday.
   Beef, pork, animal hair, live animals, leather and poultry meats
contributed to the increase, the department's Foreign Agricultural
Service said in a report.
   Animal fats, hides and skins were down slightly, the report
said. Both quantity and value of variety meats were down slightly
from a year earlier, due mostly to a sharp drop in shipments of
pork variety meats.
   In the category of dairy products, cheese and non-fat dry milk
declined 40 percent to 50 percent both in volume and value, the
report said. Butter exports nearly doubled in volume from a year
earlier, however, and were up more than 80 percent in value.
</TEXT>
