<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Bridge 1stLd-Writethru a0483 11-16 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bridge, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bay Bridge Ceremony Today; Bridge Opens to Traffic Saturday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with ceremony under way; UPDATES
expected re-opening to late Friday, sted Saturday morning. Picks up 5th
graf pvs, `In the...'. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of festive people strutted on the
San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge today, commemorating the quick
repair job that will enable commuters to return to the span this
week for the first time since the earthquake.
   Celebrators paid $5 _ proceeds to quake relief _ to walk over
the bridge to within 100 yards of the 50-foot break on the upper
deck that had severed the vital link between San Francisco and the
East Bay on Oct. 17. One motorist died.
   They couldn't walk all the way across because some of the
concrete was still in the final stages of hardening, officials said.
   ``I was on a bus when the bridge broke, about 150 yards from
where it broke,'' recalled Susan Palumbo, 42, of San Francisco, as
she stood on the bridge today. ``We had to get off the bus and walk
to Treasure Island and then to San Francisco.''
   ``It was scary. I didn't feel the quake, but I waited for the
aftershock to take the bridge down. I feel safe now,'' she said.
   The 53-year-old bridge, one of the world's most heavily
traveled, is scheduled to reopen at 11:59 p.m. Friday, said Bob
Halligan of the California Department of Transportation.
   Gov. George Deukmejian and Mayors Art Agnos and Lionel Wilson of
San Francisco and Oakland, respectively, were among the dignitaries
on the program for today's ceremony near the site of the collapse.
   In the early stages of the repair, state Department of
Transportation officials said they hoped to have the bridge
reopened by Thanksgiving. Denny McLeod, a contractor, said planning
alone for such a job usually would take a month.
   Samuel Skinner, the U.S. Secretary of Transportation,
congratulated Caltrans after observing the final stages of repair
work on Tuesday and said, ``We've beaten the bureaucracy on this
one.''
   Some local officials grumbled about today's ceremony, saying the
bridge could have been opened to cars today insteady of Saturday.
   Officials expect the usual traffic backups come Monday morning
when motorists pay their $1 tolls to cross.
   In recent weeks damage has been detected in many of the approach
ramps on either side of the bridge, so delays aren't likely to end.
   ``There are going to be tremendous traffic problems for at least
a year because of earthquake damage,'' said state Assemblyman Tom
Bates of Oakland. ``It seems like an excellent time to get
reliable, timely public transportation in place.''
   Bates plans to call for a toll increase, to at least $2, when
the legislature reconvenes in January.
   The bridge was carrying an average of more than 260,000 vehicles
every working day before the quake. It opened on Nov. 12, 1936.
   In the past month, commuters who normally drove the bridge to
work had to use alternate routes, longer and much slower because of
increased traffic.
   The Bay Area Rapid Transit system, which has an underground tube
below the Bay, has set records during the bridge closure, with as
many as 345,000 passengers riding BART trains some days.
   For the bridge repair, the first step was to make sure the
damaged decks didn't fall through to the bay. Working around the
clock, crews cut the damaged upper deck into two pieces, then used
a crane to lower them to a barge below.
   Other steps involved installing new girders, placing 20 new
I-beams, lowering 42 precast deck sections and pouring concrete
between them.
   Skinner said he hoped people who used mass transit during the
closure would stick with it.
   ``The nation can't afford the single occupant vehicle,'' he said.
</TEXT>
