<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchCouncil     11-16 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Council,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Minister Assumes Second-Highest Post Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-born Presbyterian minister condemned
by some conservatives for calling for the reunification of his
homeland was chosen Thursday as president-elect of the National
Council of Churches.
   ``By faith, I have been able to overcome the past, hatred,
hostility, and begin to see the new reality of reconciliation, in
particular the situation in Korea,'' the Rev. Syngman Rhee said
after being named to the No. 2 post in America's biggest ecumenical
organization.
   The council's 273-member governing board, gathered here for its
twice-yearly meeting, unanimously elected Rhee, the sole nominee
for the post.
   Rhee will assume office Jan. 1 and become president in 1992,
succeeding the Very Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky, an archpriest of the
Orthodox Church in America in Syosset, N.Y.
   Thirty-two Protestant, Orthodox and Anglican denominations
constitute the council, with a combined membership of 42 million
Christians.
   Rhee, 58, associate director of the global mission unit for the
Presbyterian Church (USA) in Louisville, fled to South Korea in
1950 after his father was slain by the communists.
   He served for five years in the South Korean military before
coming to the United States in 1956.
   There was no sign at Thursday's meeting of Rhee's primary
critic, the Presbyterian Lay Committee. The conservative
organization, which seeks to de-emphasize political involvement by
the Presbyterian Church (USA), has questioned Rhee's motive in
calling for the reunification of North and South Korea.
   The Presbyterian Lay Committee's president was out of town
Thursday and unavailable for comment, said the Rev. George Booker,
a consultant at the group's office in Springfield, Pa.
</TEXT>
