<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pasionaria     11-16 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pasionaria,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>100,000 Bid Farewell to Fiery Communist Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD LORANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Spaniards and
Communists from 78 countries bade farewell Thursday to Dolores
Ibarruri, ``La Pasionaria,'' whose fiery oratory rallied Republican
forces during the Spanish civil war.
   An estimated 100,000 people crowded around the downtown Plaza
Colon for the 20-minute ceremony, with many waving red flags and
raising clenched fists in honor of Mrs. Ibarruri, who died Sunday
at the age of 93.
   Mourners shouted ``No pasaran!'' _ ``They shall not pass!'' _ a
phrase she made famous as a deputy in Parliament when nationalists
under Gen. Francisco Franco rose up against the Second Republic to
set off the 1936-39 conflict.
   The crowd followed the hearse bearing Mrs. Ibarruri's coffin
from Communist Party headquarters to the plaza.
   ``Times change, then and now, and you knew how to match your
Communist militancy to new moments and situations,'' said Spanish
Communist Party General Secretary Julio Anguita in his eulogy.
``But you never went back on your principles _ nor did the Spanish
Communist Party.''
   Both Mrs. Ibarruri and the party she headed for several decades
embraced the Eurocommunist movement.
   The cortege left the plaza and headed for a municipal cemetery
for burial next to Pablo Iglesias, founder of the ruling Socialist
Party.
   More than 50,000 people paid their last respects to the
legendary leader during the three days she lay in state in party
headquarters, officials said.
   Officials from Communist parties in the Soviet Union, Cuba,
France, Italy, Nicaragua and Czechoslovakia, among others, took
turns in five-minute vigils around the casket as people filed by.
   Many of the mourners raised their fists in salute, others tossed
flowers at the foot of the bier, still others knelt and cried.
   At least 600 buses brought mourners into Madrid for the funeral,
according to the party officials.
   Visitors included U.S. and Canadian veterans of the
International Brigades that fought alongside Republican troops in
the 1936-39 war, the officials said.
   Mrs. Ibarruri, who began her career as a labor organizer and
strike leader, wrote articles signed ``La Pasionaria.'' She chose
the name in 1916 when her first article appeared during Holy Week,
the time of the Christ's passion.
   She went into exile in the Soviet Union when the Second Republic
fell to Franco's forces and only returned to Spain in 1977, two
years after his death.
   She was one of the first women elected to Parliament in Spain
and served as deputy during the Second Republic as well as in that
of the constitutional monarchy established after Franco's death.
   Political leaders said her death signaled the end of the
divisive era in Spanish history symbolized by the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
