<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Kohl     11-16 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Kohl,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Says East Germans Must Decide on Reunification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-East Germany, Bjt ^By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Describing socialism as a ``total
failure,'' Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Thursday the East Germans
must decide for themselves whether to unite with West Germany.
   The Soviet Union is firmly opposed to German reunification, and
some Western countries are nervous about the idea.
   But Kohl told a raucous parliamentary session that the East
Germans should be allowed to make up their own minds.
   ``They don't need any lectures from one side or another. They
know best what they want. That pertains also to German unity, to
the question of reunification,'' he said.
   Parliament erupted into a verbal free-for-all as lawmakers and
officials from Kohl's governing coalition exchanged barbs with the
opposition about Kohl's responses to events in East Germany
following the opening of the Communist country's borders and a
series of other reforms.
   The chancellor said West Germany would ``respect every decision
made by the people of the German Democratic Republic (East Germany)
in free self-determination.''
   Kohl added: ``He who does not want to make decisions for our
people should not try to persuade them the best thing is a division
of our fatherland.''
   He said West Germany's call for sweeping economic reform in East
Germany was not an example of meddling, but a recognition of
disastrous results from communist rule.
   ``We don't want to impose our ideas on anyone,'' he said. ``But
no one can seriously dispute that socialism has proven itself to be
a total failure. Everywhere in the world, not just in the GDR (East
Germany), it has failed.''
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev insists that sweeping changes in the
Communist world are not an admission that socialism was a mistake.
The Soviet president also has warned the West not to gloat over
what would seem like its victory in the Cold War.
   Gorbachev on Wednesday said talk about reunification ``would
mean interference in the affairs'' of East Germany and West Germany.
   On Thursday, Soviet Central Committee adviser Nikolai Portugalov
said reunification won't happen even in the long-term future.
   ``Reunification in the form in which certain rightists and
nationalists in the Federal Republic (West Germany) envision it
doesn't fit in the concept of the German states, neither East or
West,'' Portugalov told the Soviet news agency Novosti.
   ``Therefore I think that for the forseeable future and also in
the long term two German states will exist with one another, not
against one another, as sovereign and equal.''
   West Berlin Mayor Walter Momper accused Kohl of dragging his
feet in offers of help for East Germany and demanded that financial
aid not be linked to a complete overhaul of the Communist nation's
economy.
   Rudolf Seiters, Kohl's chief of staff, interrupted Momper and
said to him angrily: ``Do you really think that in this hour of
history your attack is really appropriate?''
   In his speech, Momper also said East Germans want ``no meddling
in the formation of their society'' and contended most aren't
interested in the question of German reunification.
   Renewed interest in possible German reunification has followed
East Germany's decision a week ago to open its borders, including
the Berlin Wall. Built in 1961 to prevent citizens from fleeing,
the wall was a symbol of East-West division.
   Kohl offered to make desperately needed doctors and medical
assistance available to East Germany but said fundamental changes
in its political and economic system remains crucial to Bonn's
plans for ``a fully new dimension of help and cooperation.''
</TEXT>
