<DOCNO> AP891116-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     11-16 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Rejects Attempt in Congress to Pardon Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco's government
opposes an attempt in Colombia's congress to pardon drug
traffickers, newspapers reported Thursday.
   During debate in congress Wednesday, Justice Minister Roberto
Salazar said Barco is steadfastly opposed to giving amnesty to the
Medellin Cartel members and other cocaine traffickers, reported the
dailies El Espectador and El Tiempo.
   Barco has no veto power over legislation and if the congress
should decide to approve the amnesty bill, it would become law.
   However, there is little doubt the Supreme Court would declare
such a law unconstitutional. The constitution clearly reserves
pardons for political crimes while forbidding amnesty for common
criminals.
   Rep. Cesar Perez is proposing that amnesty for traffickers be
made part of a bill that would offer amnesty to leftist guerrillas
who signed a truce with the government.
   Perez said in a speech to the congress Wednesday that the
minister of justice was ignorant because of his opposition to
amnesty for drug traffickers.
   Colombia's congress has not been enthusiastic over the
government's war on drug traffickers declared by Barco Aug. 19
after traffickers killed a popular presidential hopeful, Sen. Luis
Carlos Galan.
   Barco issued decrees allowing the extradition of traffickers to
the United States and the confiscation of their property in
Colombia.
   Attacks blamed on drug thugs since the government offensive
began have left at least 39 people dead and 226 injured.
   Several members of congress have been accused in the last 10
years of accepting money from drug traffickers, but the accusations
have never been proven. The suspected head of the Medellin Cartel,
Pablo Escobar, was a member of congress from 1982 to 1986.
   Several congressmen have expressed support for amnesty for drug
traffickers, but because most are keeping their opinions to
themselves there is no way to tell if amnesty for traffickers might
be approved.
   Debate on the bill is expected to end within the next two weeks.
   The proposed amnesty for guerrillas came in a peace treaty with
the April 19 Movement, known as the M-19. Few in congress have
spoken out against the government's attempt to reach a peace with
the guerrillas.
   In exchange for pardons and the right to form a political party,
the M-19 has agreed to give up its weapons and disband.
   Four other guerrilla groups have expressed interest in opening
talks with the government, but so far no other talks have taken
place. A sixth guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, has
said it will never negotiate with the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Iowa-Questions     11-16 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa-Questions,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Hearing Prompts Heated Questioning</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iowa Hearing Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for item slugged AM-Iowa-Unanswered Questions on
Digest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the questions posed by the
members of the Senate Armed Services Committee on Thursday to Navy
officials who conducted the investigation into the April 19
explosion aboard the battleship Iowa, and some of the replies they
received:
   _Does the Navy have proof the explosion was caused by gunner's
mate Clayton Hartwig?
   Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, author of the Navy's report, said
the Navy has ``forensic evidence'' that Hartwig was the gun captain
on the day of the explosion, and that he was the one who
``controlled the loading'' of the 16-inch gun, which was rammed 21
inches further up the barrel than it should have been. Hartwig had
the ability to construct an explosive device and the opportunity to
put it in the gun, the admiral said.
   Milligan cited as other evidence an FBI psychological profile of
Hartwig that he said suggested the sailor ``took his own life in
hopes it would look like an accident.''
   _But Hartwig didn't know he was to be in the turret until
several hours before the blast.
   Milligan said the sailor was upset over the breakup of a
friendship with another sailor, had discussed suicide and did have
those hours of notice. He noted that superiors who assigned Hartwig
to replace another sailor in the turret also died in the blast.
   _Aren't there other possible causes for such an explosion?
   The admiral said his investigation and the Navy's 20,000
technical tests of the gunpowder and charge ruled out numerous
other possibilties, such as a spark from a burning ember or the
ship's electrical system, friction during the loading of the gun
barrel, or contamination of the gunpowder during its years of
storage.
   _Could the ``foreign matter'' found on the projectile, a key to
the Navy's conclusion that someone probably used a detonator, have
gotten there at some other time?
   Milligan said the material was embedded in the copper ring of
the projectile by the fierce power of the explosion, and could not
have gotten there when the shell was forcibly removed from the gun
barrel following the explosion.
   _Given the safety and training problems aboard the Iowa,
couldn't they have played a part in the explosion?
   Milligan admitted that there were ``major problems'' in the
administration of the ship and that the sailors in the gun turret
had not completed the proper procedures to prove that they were
competent to work in those positions, but the admiral said those
problems didn't cause the blast.
   _Doesn't a recent series of deadly accidents give rise to doubts
about the Navy's training and the leadership of its commanders?
   The Navy's top admiral, Carlisle A.H. Trost, told the committee
that steps have been taken to make sure that the lapses in
procedure aboard the Iowa have been corrected throughout the fleet,
and that he ordered a Navywide safety inspection to make sure that
proper procedures are being followed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
