<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-ArtFight     11-16 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Art Fight,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Sale of Van Gogh Masterpiece was Invalid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court ruled Thursday that the Italian government
has ownership rights to Van Gogh's masterpiece ``The Gardener,''
thus preventing its sale to the Peggy Guggenheim Collection in
Venice.
   Under the ruling by the administrative court of the province of
Lazio, the 1889 oil painting valued at $8.5 million will remain at
the National Gallery of Modern Art in Rome.
   The ownership dispute dates to 1977 when Ernst Beyeler, an art
collector from Basel, Switzerland, bought the painting for 600
million lire _ about $1 million then _ from an Italian nobleman.
   The painting remained in Italian museums and Beyeler tried to
sell it last year to the Guggenheim Collection, one of the most
renowned modern art galleries in Europe. The sale price was $8.5
million.
   The Italian Culture Ministry, however, blocked the sale. It
charged Beyeler's 1977 purchase of the painting was illegal, saying
it was bought in another person's name. The ministry said Beyeler
was not the legal owner and that the government had rights to the
painting.
   Beyeler took the case to court, which ruled against him
Thursday. The court will announce the reasons for its ruling later.
   Guggenheim officials were not involved in the court case.
   The court ruling means the state can buy the painting at the
1977 price, now equivalent to $444,000. However, an official
familiar with the case said another court could adjust the price
for inflation, putting the sales tag at about $1.5 million.
   The painting has been in Italy since 1910 and is considered by
the government part of the country's artistic patrimony.
   In 1977, an attempt was made to illegally export the painting
from Italy.
   The painting, a half-length portrait of a peasant in a sun hat,
has been kept in the basement of the Rome museum since 1987 pending
clarification of its ownership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Kidnap-US     11-16 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnap-US,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Want to Question Non-Kidnapped Californian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER V. CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department official said Thursday that
U.S. consular officials want to question the California woman who
for a time was thought kidnapped by terrorists in Lebanon.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said West German authorities had
conveyed word that Deborah Fahrend and two West German citizens
were ``free and safe.''
   ``We don't know for sure'' whether they were kidnapped, Miss
Tutwiler said. ``They have told the Germans that they were robbed,
not kidnapped.''
   Reports from Lebanon said the trio had gone by ferry to Larnaca,
Cyprus.
   ``Our consular officer, wherever she surfaces, will definitely
want to have a little _ meet her,'' said Miss Tutwiler, ending her
sentence on a different note.
   She said that a privacy law prevented her from discussing Mrs.
Fahrend's passport, but she emphasized it is against the law to use
a U.S. passport to travel to Lebanon without a special validation.
   She said no American citizen to date has been prosecuted for
such passport violations, ``but there are a number of cases under
consideration for prosecution right now.''
   After outlining what the State Department knew of the Fahrend
case, Miss Tutwiler added:
   ``The Lebanon travel advisory states that the situation in
Lebanon is so dangerous for Americans that no U.S. citizen can be
considered safe from terrorist acts.''
   She noted that U.S. embassy personnel were evacuated last Sept.
6 and said, ``without a special validation, U.S. passports remain
invalid for travel to, in, or through Lebanon.''
   Lebanon and Libya are the only two countries on which the United
States has placed such stringent travel restrictions.
   So far this year, Miss Tutwiler said, U.S. officials have
granted only 15 such passport validations for travel to war-torn
Lebanon. It validates passports for journalists, for Red Cross or
humanitarian purposes, or for trips ``in the U.S. national
interest,'' she said.
   Mrs. Fahrend, 54, had no connection with the U.S. government,
she added.
   Mrs. Fahrend, a registered nurse formerl of San Francisco, had
been living in West Berlin in recent years. She reportedly
described herself as a ``publisher-journalist'' and gone to Lebanon
to write a book on what she called ``a chance in a lifetime.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater announced to
reporters flying with President Bush to Houston earlier Thursday
that Mrs. Fahrend and her two companions had turned up.
   Eighteen foreigners are held in Lebanon, including eight
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity-Wages     11-16 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security-Wages,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guidelines Designed to Improve Wage-Reporting System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday proposed voluntary
record-keeping standards for employers so workers get credit for
all their wages when Social Security benefits are calculated.
   ``It is simply unacceptable for anyone to receive less than
their entitled Social Security benefits because their wages were,
at some point in their career, improperly recorded,'' Social
Security Commissioner Gwendolyn King said.
   The Social Security Administration believes the new voluntary
computer software standards could help employers more accurately
report wage and tax information to SSA and the Internal Revenue
Service.
   If an employee does not get proper credit for his or her wages,
it could result in lower Social Security benefits. Under the
current system, an estimated 10 percent of employer wage reports
contain inaccuracies or discrepancies that government workers must
try to resolve.
   The General Accounting Office last year reported that between
1978 and 1983, employers reported $58.8 billion less earnings to
Social Security than to IRS, and that little was being done to
reduce a growing backlog of unresolved cases.
   Social Security spokesman Phil Gambino said all those cases have
since been closed, with differences successfully resolved in
two-thirds of them. For 1984-87, about three-fourths of problem
cases have been resolved, and all should be completed by next year,
he said.
   The work has resulted in the crediting of $84 billion in wages
for 1979-87, Gambino said.
   ``In recent years, SSA has struggled mightily to attempt to
reconcile these errors after the reporting fact,'' Mrs. King said.
``Now, we want to correct the problem at the employer level ...
before differences occur.''
   Employers are being asked to comment on the draft guidelines
before a final version of the voluntary standards is issued.
   Workers themselves can help verify the accuracy of their
earnings record by obtaining a Personalized Earnings and Benefit
Estimate Statement from Social Security which contains a
year-by-year display of their earnings from 1951 through the most
recent year. Applications for the statements can be obtained by
contacting local Social Security offices or by calling
1-800-234-5772.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
