<FIRST>r w AM-SeabrookLicense     11-16 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook License,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Makes Move That Could Speed Up Seabrook Licensing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said
Thursday it would immediately move toward a decision on licensing
the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant.
   In a three-page ruling, the commission said it would take the
case away from two lower-level boards who were disputing the
adequacy of emergency evacuation plans for New Hampshire residents
living near the plant. No timetable for action was announced.
   Rick Bornemann, spokesman for Connecticut's United Illuminating
Corp., owner of the second-largest share of the Seabrook plant,
said, ``Anything that speeds up this outcome is good news.''
   Opponents of Seabrook, meanwhile, reacted angrily.
   ``I am absolutely outraged,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. ``I
will ask for a speed-up of the congressional investigation of NRC
procedures that we called for this week.''
   The plant, planned since the early 1970s, was finished in 1986.
Licensing and operation has been held up by disputes over the
adequacy of emergency evaucation plans, particularly for
Massachusetts communities near the plant.
   The commission would have had to consider the action by the
boards in any case and it is under no obligation to wait for the
boards to complete their work.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board earlier this week
dismissed a ruling by the Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeal Board
that questioned the effectiveness of the evacuation plans. The
licensing board's argument was that the concerns raised by the
appeal board should not stand in the way of Seabrook receiving a
license.
   Until Thursday's ruling, the appeal board was preparing to open
a two-week process during which arguments on the evacuation plans
would be heard.
   ``In the interests of efficiency and effectiveness in resolving
matters relating to the licensing board's authorization of the
issuance of a full-power license, the commission has decided that
it rather than the appeal board will consider all applications for
a stay of the licensing board's authorization of full-power
operation,'' the four commissioners said.
