<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Complaints     11-16 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Complaints,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEMA Denies Charges By Quake-Hit Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pressm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency is denying charges by a
group of earthquake victims who contend they aren't getting the
benefits they deserve.
   Outside a crumbling and boarded residential hotel, the group
Wednesday presented a petition of grievances against the Federal
Emergency Management Agency, demanding parity for poorer victims of
the Oct. 17 earthquake.
   ``We're outraged against this discriminatory action of FEMA,''
said attorney Kenneth Zimmerman of the Legal Aid Society of Alameda
County.
   The group accused FEMA of violating its legal obligations to
ease the burdens of quake victims.
   Zimmerman accused FEMA of granting low-income tenants of
residential hotels and seasonal workers a half to a third of the
payments other renters are getting. He charged also that the agency
has labeled some people as ``pre-earthquake homeless'' when they
had addresses before the quake.
   Lorri L. Jean, FEMA's deputy federal coordinating officer,
categorically denied the allegations. She said the authors of the
petition ``do not understand FEMA's program and have not made an
attempt to try and understand FEMA's program.''
   She said long-term renters and homeowners get more money because
it takes them more time to relocate them than residential hotel
tenants.
   ``Those who need and qualify for help from FEMA and other
organizations receive it now and will continue to receive it,'' she
said.
   Jean said that as of Monday her agency paid out almost $6.3
million in temporary housing aid, and that the figure would soon
double.
