<FIRST>r w AM-ShiftingBorder     11-16 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shifting Border,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Endorses Bill to Move 1,800 Acres from Nebraska to South Dakota</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Dakota would grow by 1,800 acres under a
bill rushed through a House committee Thursday to move back a
12-mile stretch of the Nebraska border that lies along the shifting
course of the Missouri River.
   The strip of land on the north side of the river just west of
Sioux City, Iowa, technically lies in Nebraska because the river's
course has moved since the boundary was set in 1905, Rep. Tim
Johnson, D-S.D., told the House Judiciary subcommittee on
administrative law.
   An interstate compact that must be approved by Congress would
fix the boundary along the river's main channel. Legislatures of
both states have approved the change.
   The House could vote on the bill as early as Monday, Johnson
said.
   Johnson said the river is relatively stable now because the
Corps of Engineers has brought the river under control with dams
and channels.
   However, the Corps of Engineers said in a letter to the
committee that it is ``technically correct'' that the river is
stable now but that the channel could shift at some time as dikes
erode.
   Johnson said Congress should act quickly on the compact so that
construction can begin on a planned community and business park
along the river in Union County, S.D.
   The Dakota Dunes development, which would occupy 400 acres of
the disputed area, is eventually expected to house 3,000 people, he
said.
</TEXT>
