<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Shelter     11-16 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Shelter,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Army Refurbishes Former Jail to House Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABNER KATZMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Berlin's newest shelter for homeless
East German refugees will have 400 small rooms, walls three feet
thick and all the comfort of a jail _ which is what it was.
   U.S. Army Engineer units armed with steel-cutting rescue saws
and acetylene torches stormed the former Youth Detention Center
Wednesday morning and began cutting out the inch-thick bars on the
windows and removing the reinforced cell doors. The Army has
offered to help with the refugees.
   The engineers have just three days to make the house of
detention into a home. The 19th-century prison building, still in
use as a jail until five years ago, will be used as a transit
center for the refugees, most of whom are now sleeping in schools
and other public buildings.
   Since the Berlin Wall and the other fortifications dividing East
from West Germany were opened Friday, millions of East Germans have
flooded into the West. Although most have gone back across to their
homes, the West Berlin government said that about 7,500 East German
refugees had come to stay.
   ``My job is to get all the bars out of the window, to get away
from the jail cell appearance,'' said Sgt. Robert J. Hart, as the
gasoline-powered disc saws of his men roared and spewed exhaust
fumes along the cell blocks.
   His unit is also tearing out the iron bed frames and the
antiquated cell toilets to make the 7-by-12 foot cells more
liveable. The jailhouse graffiti will have to stay, because there's
no time for painting.
   ``They're going to move in more suitable furniture,'' Hart said.
``It's better than sleeping on the streets. At least they're out of
the weather.
   ``It's kind of ironic that now they're trying to get out to
freedom, they're moving into a jail. I just hope they appreciate
it.''
   Known to local wags as the ``Cafe Schoenstedstrasse'' because of
its location at the intersection of Karl Marx Strasse and
Schoenstedstrasse in the borough of Neukoln, the four tiers of
cells surround an exercise courtyard where occupants will be able
to stretch their legs.
   The West Berlin government will provide food for the refugees
until more permanent lodging can be found.
   Because of their size, each cell can only accomodate one person,
but Hart said they'd be as comfortable as the Army can make them.
   ``I believe everybody should have a chance for freedom. Now
they're having it,'' said Hart, from California, Mo.
   But one of his men, Spec. 4 Daniel Bross of Newton, Ill., was
concerned that a prison might be too much a reminder of repression.
   ``How would you feel if just got out of a country where you
couldn't do nothing and they stuck you in a 6-by-6 room?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Summit     11-16 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Summit,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush May Leave Early for Seagoing Summit With Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may leave a day early for his
seagoing summit with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev so he
can visit a U.S. aircraft carrier and perhaps address sailors of
the Mediterranean fleet, officials said Thursday.
   Bush originally had been scheduled to leave Washington early
Dec. 1 and fly to Malta for two days of talks with Gorbachevon U.S.
and Soviet warships anchored about 1,000 feet offshore.
   However, officials said Thursday that Bush may leave the evening
of Nov. 30 and fly through the night, arriving in Malta early the
next morning. Under that plan, the president would then fly out to
the carrier Forrestal, meet with servicemen and perhaps deliver a
speech to sailors gathered from other ships in the region.
   Bush would spend the remainder of the day preparing for the Dec.
2-3 summit talks. His headquarters will be the USS Belknap, a
guided missile cruiser.
   The first day of talks are to be held on Gorbachev's ship, the
Slava, followed by meetings the next day on Bush's ship. Bush will
give a dinner for Gorbachev on the Belknap on Dec. 2.
   The two leaders are expected to close their summit with a joint
statement on the afternoon of Dec. 3 and then hold separate news
conferences.
   Bush is to spend the night of Dec. 3 on the Belknap and fly to
Brussels, Belgium, the next day to report to NATO allies on the
talks. He returns to Washington on Dec. 4.
   Bush was expected to make remarks both on his departure from
Washington and on his arrival home.
</TEXT>
