<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ExportSubsidies     11-16 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Export Subsidies,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Foreign Agriculture Programs Wasting Millions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of dollars have been wasted because
of mismanagement in federal programs that subsidize agriculture
exports, a farm state congressman said Thursday.
   ``This is one of the biggest cases of mismanagment ever in the
history of the Agriculture Department,'' said Rep. Dan Glickman,
D-Kan., after receiving two investigative reports on three export
programs.
   Glickman said the investigations by the Agriculture Department's
inspector general and the congressional General Accounting Office
did not reveal fraud but showed ``lack of controls.''
   ``There has been an enormous waste of government funds,'' he
said of the export enhancement program, the targeted export
assistance program and the export credit guarantee programs.
   ``These audits were done prior to this administration,'' said
Sally Michael, spokeswoman for Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter.
   She said the department appreciates the review of the programs
and is working with both the inspector general and GAO.
   ``We want to respond to their criticisms,'' she said.
   The first two programs were established in 1985 to help U.S.
exporters compete with countries that heavily subsidize their
commodities on the world market. The third guarantees that
exporters will be repaid for credit sales made to foreign buyers,
even if the buyer defaults.
   When it comes to targeted export assistance and export
enhancment, foreign agriculture service officials have not been
sufficiently documenting their decisions and say they don't have
time to do so, said the GAO.
   ``We believe that such documentation is essential to ensure
accountablity and fairness,'' the agency said.
   Furthermore, the inspector general said the foreign agriculture
service didn't have written policies to determine how it calculates
the subsidies it gives.
   ``Although FAS officials prepare price sheets which list each of
the figures used in price and bonus calculations, they do not
provide either narrative or statistical support to explain how they
arrived at these figures,'' said the GAO.
   The reviews indicated ``control weaknesses in the bonus payment
process which allowed overpayments to occur,'' said the GAO.
   The GAO also said better controls were needed in the credit
guarantee program.
   ``Our review also indicates that controls are not in place to
ensure that exporters are complying with applicable regulations,''
said the GAO.
   Glickman said the inspector general's report ``estimates that
USDA may have misspent as much as $114.8 million solely in
miscalculating bonuses awarded to exporters by understanding the
world price and overstating incidental costs incurred by
participating exporters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
