<FIRST>u w AM-TransportationNominee     11-16 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transportation Nominee,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Nominee Following Committee Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President's Bush's nominee to head the Urban
Mass Transportation Administration was approved by the Senate after
a two-month delay while a committee investigated work done by his
auditing firm.
   Brian W. Clymer was confirmed by unanimous consent Wednesday
night once a ``hold'' on his nomination was lifted by the Senate
Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee.
   The committee had unanimously backed Clymer's nomination on
Sept. 8. But the panel delayed sending the nomination to the Senate
floor while it examined work done by Clymer's suburban Philadelphia
accounting firm on behalf of an economic development organization
nearby, according to a Senate aide who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   According to the aide, the committee asked a certified public
accountant from the General Accounting Office of Congress to
determine whether Clymer's firm should have uncovered questionable
expenditures by the Delaware County Economic Development
Partnership. The aide said it was determined the firm had done its
job properly.
   A committee spokeswoman said Thursday she could not discuss the
results of the investigation. ``All Senate confirmation procedures
had been completed and it was now time to release the hold,''
committee aide Deborah DeYoung said.
   The partnership was founded in 1983 by Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa.
The congressman asked consultant Anthony J. Dunleavy to investigate
the partnership earlier this year following press reports about the
awarding of no-bid contracts.
   Of particular interest to the Senate panel were no-bid contracts
awarded Clymer's firm by the partnership to audit its books.
Dunleavy said in an interview Thursday that he was asked about the
contracts recently by the committee staff.
   Dunleavy said that this year's contract was properly bid. But he
said that the contracts for 1986, 1987 and 1988 were not awarded
through competitive procurement policies required by the federal
government, and that federal money was used.
   Dunleavy also said Thursday that the partnership misspent
$121,000 in federal funds on ineligible items such as a promotional
film between July 1988 and July 1989.
   But Dunleavy said that Clymer's firm was just now auditing that
period. Dunleavy said there had also been improper expenditures in
previous years, but that there was no reason Clymer's firm should
have discovered them.
   ``In layman's terms, he's been criticized for not doing
something he was never asked to do,'' Dunleavy said. He also said
Clymer should not have been expected to know that the 1986, 1987
and 1988 contracts were not properly bid.
   Clymer already has a desk at UMTA, where he has been acting as a
consultant. UMTA assists state and local governments in improving
mass transportation systems.
   Clymer was on a business trip in California Thursday, and could
not be reached for comment, according to UMTA spokesman Richard
Centner. Clymer is the former vice chairman of the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, which runs Philadelphia's
mass transit system.
</TEXT>
