<FIRST>u a AM-NavyStand-down 1stLd-Writethru a0707 11-16 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Stand-down, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailors Spend Time on Safety, Navy Boat Swamped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to UPDATE with Navy boat swamped in York
River. Picks up 4th graf, `Again and...'. SUBS 15th graf, `The order..'
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy boat with 10 sailors aboard was
swamped as it returned to base Thursday to take part in an
unprecedented, two-day ``stand-down'' that had sailors around the
world brushing up on safety.
   In Navy wardrooms and engine compartments, flight decks and
hangars, crews were busy in lectures and training. The Navy ordered
the halt to normal operations Tuesday after a rash of 10 accidents
over the last three weeks killed 10 people and injured at least 71.
   The 36-foot Navy Seafox was swamped in stormy weather on the
nearby York River as it headed to Cheatham Annex near Williamsburg.
The 10 sailors aboard the Seafox were picked up by a Virginia
Institute of Marine Science vessel that was in the area, said Lt.
Cmdr. Steve Burnett, an Atlantic Fleet spokesman in Norfolk. None
were injured.
   A Seafox is a twin-engine boat designed for special warfare
operations.
   A second Seafox towed the swamped boat, which is designed to
float even when flooded, said Burnett. They were returning from
training in Maryland.
   ``At no time was it a life threatening situation,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, aboard the guided missile cruiser USS Josephus
Daniels docked at the Norfolk Naval Station, Petty Officer Mike
Ballard instructed seamen in damage control.
   Again and again, Ballard walked sailors through the proper way
to wear firefighting equipment and the necessary checks for each
safety device.
   Every sailor is trained in damage control, according to Lt. j.g.
Paul Ward, the ship's assistant damage control officer. He said the
ships runs a daily fire or rescue drill. Ward saw the stand-down as
a good way to stress safety to all hands.
   ``Our job is to carry out our mission while sustaining damage.
Everyone here has to be a capable firefighter. When there is a fire
on board, you can't just run away. ... There is nowhere to run,''
Ward said.
   Throughout the ship, sailors gathered in compartments for talks
about electrical safety, fire aid and weapons handling.
   While sailors were going to school aboard the Daniels, 30 miles
away at the Oceana Naval Air Station the pilots of Squardon VF-41
were in their ready room going over data on the flight performance
of the F-14 Tomcat.
   The squadron already had been scheduled for a safety inspection
Friday by the Naval Safety Center, so the stand-down did not affect
the flight schedule. One pilot characterized the exercise as a
``two-day stand-around.''
   But aboard the San Diego-based carrier Independence, ``we're
taking this very seriously,'' said ship spokesman Lt. Greg Smith.
   A stand-down ``doesn't mean everything is at a standstill,''
said Lt. Mike Andrews, a spokesman for the U.S. 7th Fleet, based in
Japan. ``Ships at sea will obviously maintain normal watch
stations'' while conducting safety reviews.
   At the Miramar Naval Air Station in San Diego, Rear Adm. Phil
Anselmo joined about 1,000 sailors in a walk around runways,
taxiways and aprons looking for potentially hazardous litter. They
found about 50 pounds, including industrial bolts and chunks of
epoxy.
   Out on the hangar floor at Oceana, Lt. Cmdr. Ken Heimgartner
watched young crewmen go over his F-14.
   ``After a while, you start equating safety with combat
readiness,'' said Heimgartner, the squadron commander. ``When you
start seeing something unsafe, that's an indicator you may not be
combat ready.''
   The order Tuesday gave all Navy units 72 hours to complete 48
hours of safety stand-down. Most Atlantic Fleet units began the
stand-down Thursday morning, according to Burnett.
   Stand-downs are not unusual, though this is the first in memory
that involved the entire service, said Capt. Ferguson Norton, the
Navy's top safety officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
