<DOCNO> AP891116-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bolivia     11-16 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Defy State of Siege, Call 24-hour Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest labor group defied a
state of siege Thursday and called a 24-hour strike to pressure the
government to free hundreds of people rounded up by police.
   Schools, government-owned mines and some factories were
affected, but businesses, banks and offices were open and public
transport operated normally.
   Labor Minister Oscar Zamora claimed only ``2 percent of the work
force'' took part in the strike.
   Officials declared the strike illegal and said police would
arrest labor leaders who disobeyed the state of siege, which
imposes a curfew from 1 a.m. to 5 a.m., restricts public gatherings
and allows arrests without warrant.
   Guillermo Capobianco, the interior minister, said the purpose of
the state of siege was ``to preserve economic stability and the
foreign assistance needed to reactivate the economy, re-establish
peace and guarantee municipal elections.''
   The Bolivian Workers Central, which includes most of Bolivia's
labor force, called the strike to demand freedom for 858 teachers,
students and workers police detained Wednesday. The government
released several hundred, but sent 146 to detention camps in the
Bolivian tropics.
   President Jaime Paz Zamora's government declared the state of
siege Wednesday in response to protest marches and a hunger strike
by hundreds of teachers and other workers. Police have used tear
gas and rubber bullets to disperse crowds of rock throwing students
and teachers.
   When the siege was declared, three leaders of the teachers'
union were in critical condition from the effects of a 24-day
hunger strike, but doctors said Thursday they were out of danger.
   Teachers demand the equivalent of $103 each in a year-end bonus
to compensate for the increasing cost of living, but the government
says that would upset the economy and contribute to inflation.
   Schoolteachers earn an average salary equivalent to $75 a month
and 18 percent of the government budget goes to education.
   Opposition parties said they would defy the state of siege and
candidates in the Dec. 3 municipal elections would hold rallies
despite restrictions on public gatherings.
   ``No governmental decree will prohibit us from conducting
political activity on the streets,'' said Antonio Aranibar of the
United Leftist Party.
   ``Holding elections under a state of siege constitutes a
tremendous aberration without precedent in Latin America,'' said a
statement from the Nationalist Revolutionary Movement, the main
opposition party.
   The opposition group, which controlled the government during the
four years before Paz Zamora took office three months ago, declared
states of siege on two occasions to quell social unrest and
opposition to its austerity measures.
   Paz Zamora's administration has said there will be no pay
increases or bonuses until next year.
   ``Our No. 1 priority is to preserve economic stability and
attract foreign investors, said Raul Loayza, undersecretary of the
interior.
</TEXT>
