<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Germany     11-16 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Germany,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says German Reunification Not Realistic Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said again Thursday
that the two Germanys may be reunited someday, but not now.
   In a television broadcast of his answers to questions at a
conference of students, Gorbachev repeated earlier statements that
the existence of two German states is reality and trying to change
it ``would be meddling into the affairs of the Federal Republic of
Germany and the German Democratic Republic.''
   ``You have to proceed from this reality,'' he said. ``As to how
history will turn out in the future, we will live and see.
   ``I think all European society and the international community
are interested in stability. Both the world and Europe could
develop and come to new forms of coexistence, and life will show
what will happen. Let's not read tea leaves.''
   ``The whole world is changing, and these changes are positive.''
   Little was said of reunification except in West Germany until
tens of thousands of people began fleeing East Germany last summer
and huge protests for democracy began inside the country.
   Last week's opening of the Berlin Wall and the border between
East and West Germany suddenly made the idea conceivable and the
debate began.
   Gorbachev gave a formal speech to the students Wednesday, then
answered written questions. The speech was broadcast Wednesday and
his responses to the questions were shown Thursday night.
