<FIRST>u i AM-Bulgaria 2ndLd-Writethru a0720 11-16 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0720,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Holds 1st Meeting Since Zhivkov</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to give details on proposed changes, add
quote; picks up 6th pvs `Removed from...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party overhauled its ruling
Politburo on Thursday, sweeping out three members of the old guard
and installing four more liberal men likely to support Petar
Mladenov, the new leader.
   The one-day session of the party's policy-setting Central
Committee was called less than a week after the removal of Todor
Zhivkov, 78, who led the nation with rigid orthodoxy for 35 years.
   BTA, the official news agency, said speakers at the Central
Committee meeting described the remaking of the Politburo as a step
``without which onward progress is hardly possible.''
   They expressed the party's resolve to ``pursue the watershed
policy of renewal of socialism ...on the basis of democratization,
openness and responsibility of everyone,'' the agency said.
   Zhivkov resigned Nov. 10 and was replaced by Mladenov, 53, who
was foreign minister and is considered more open to reform.
   The Central Committee ousted three members of the 10-member
Politburo with close ties to Zhivkov and named four new members.
One of the seats filled was Zhivkov's.
   The committee also accepted a proposal that Mladenov be
nominated to replace Zhivkov as president and approved suggestions
for unspecified government changes proposed by Premier Georgi
Atanassov, BTA reported.
   Mladenov is expected to be replaced as foreign minister but the
agency gave no indication of what other changes might be made.
   Removed from office was Politburo member Milko Balev, 69, a
close associate of Zhivkov who for many years was his private
secretary. Also ousted was Dimitar Stoyanov, 61, a former interior
minister.
   Western analysts speaking on condition of anonymity said
Stoyanov was associated with the widely condemned forced
assimiliation of the 1.5 million-member Turkish minority.
   Also removed was Grisha Filipov, 70, a former premier who was
responsible for economic policy.
   Balev, Stoyanov and Filipov were also expelled from the Central
Committee.
   Petko Danchev, a non-voting member of the Politburo who was
reportedly a Zhivkov protoge was also ousted, BTA reported.
   The new Politburo members are the current foreign trade
minister, Andrei Lukanov, 51, who is considered a liberal. The
others promoted to the ruling body were Nacho Papazov, Pantelei
Pachov and Mincho Yovchev. Papazov had been in charge of a
commission for reform in the party.
   There were several shakeups in the Central Committee as well.
According to a resolution carried by the state BTA news agency,
Zhivkov's son, Vladimir, was expelled from committee.
   The Central Committee also reinstated former members Stoyan
Mihailov and Svetlin Roussev, who were removed in 1988.
   Roussev, an artist, was active in establishing an unofficial
committee to protect the environment, while Mihailov had been
stripped of his ideology portfolio after being criticized for what
appeared to be deemed a too liberal interpretation of Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Mladenov has moved quickly to assert reforms since his
appointment Nov. 10, when he pledged greater openness and called
for the establishment of a ``contemporary democratic and
law-abiding country.''
   His appointment was greeted by intellectuals and the official
media. According to an opinion poll published in the trade union
daily Troud on Thursday, Bulgarian citizens also welcomed the new
leader as providing hope for change.
   Thursday's personnel changes followed a decision by the
Politburo on Monday to restore the party membership of 11 activists
and on Tuesday, Mladenov met with a group of intellectuals, many of
them members of opposition groups.
   The leadership shakeup in Bulgaria comes as reform is sweeping
the Soviet bloc. This Balkan country has traditionally been one of
the Kremlin's most loyal allies, but while Zhivkov's leadership
paid lip-service to reform, little was done to implement change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
