<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-DeathSquad     11-16 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Death Squad,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Police Officer Tells of Death Squad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police captain has
admitted participating in the murders of government opponents as
part of a special police unit, a newspaper reported Friday.
   Dirk Coetzee, identified in the article as a white captain who
left the police force in 1982, was interviewed on the Indian Ocean
island of Mauritius after leaving South Africa last week, said the
Afrikaans-language newspaper, Free Weekly.
   The paper quoted Coetzee as saying he had been actively involved
with a police hit squad until August 1982 when he left the force,
but had kept in contact with the unit's members and knew of further
misdeeds committed since his departure.
   Coetzee is the second former policeman recently to admit being
part of a death squad. Last month, a black former security
policeman on Death Row was reprieved the day before his set
execution when he contacted attorneys and said that when he was
part of the squad in 1981 he had killed black anti-apartheid
attorney Griffiths Mxenge in Durban.
   The black policeman was about to hang for a murder committed
during a robbery after he left the police force, and he said he
spoke out because his former colleagues failed to keep promises to
save him.
   According to Free Weekly, Coetzee also listed the Mxenge murder
among the acts committed by the squad to which he belonged. The
paper said Coetzee admitted planning and taking part in murders.
   The newspaper quoted Coetzee as saying the police death squad
sent the letter bomb to Maputo, Mozambique, in 1982 that killed
Ruth First, wife of South African Communist Party leader Joe Slovo.
   The paper said Coetzee also said his squad was responsible for:
   _the killing of African National Congress member Patrick Makau
and his child at Manzini, Swaziland, in 1980;
   _a bomb explosion at the ANC's London office in 1982;
   _the murder of two ANC members near Komatipoort on the
Mozambican border in 1980,
   _the attempted murder of ANC military wing leader Chris Hani in
Lesotho.
   In the article, Coetzee alleged that police stole cars, killed
guard dogs and people with poison, and used former members of
outlawed guerrilla organizations to carry out some deeds.
   The Free Weekly article was made available just after midnight
to the independent South African Press Association, and there was
no immediate comment from police officials. But high-ranking
officials already have been appointed to investigate the charges
made by the reprieved black security policeman.
   There have been about 20 unsolved killings and bombings of
anti-apartheid activists and organizations the past 10 years.
Anti-apartheid leaders have often said they believe security force
members are involved, but have no proof.
   The Free Weekly said Coetzee had left the country with his wife
and children to start a new life, and gave the interview to ``put
the past right.''
</TEXT>
