<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany-Media     11-16 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Media,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Newspaper Replaces Top Editor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main Communist Party daily, until now the
most reluctant to embrace the new spirit of change, jumped on the
reform bandwagon Thursday with a new editor and a more lively tone.
   In a front-page notice to readers, Neues Deutschland said the
moves were needed to promote renewal. Previously the newspaper had
been critical of opposition groups and of calls for an end to the
Communist monopoly on power.
   Long-time chief editor Herbert Naumann was replaced by Wolfgang
Spickermann, who signed the announcement of the top-level shakeup.
   ``As in all of the fundamental organizations within our party,
the comrades in editing and publishing in these weeks have exposed
their work to a confrontation with the past,'' the newspaper said.
   ``The result of these discussions is not just a new editorial
board, but above all the concept for a rejuvenated newspaper,''
Neues Deutschland said.
   It promised ``new content, more information, political views and
timely journalistic forums.''
   While state-run East German television and other publications
have given relatively balanced coverage of the rise of opposition
groups and independent actions by parties allied with the
Communists, Neues Deutschland had been more defensive of the
party's leading role and control of state affairs.
   The newspaper's front page on Thursday conveyed a more
reform-oriented image, with more than a dozen articles addressing
problems and benefits resulting from the newly opened borders and
other changes introduced the past month.
   It also published a call for more public involvement in
government affairs, providing telephone numbers for readers to call
in with advice, proposals and criticism.
   The format of the newspaper was little revised, with numerous
small articles but no pictures to break up the gray monotony.
   But the changed approach to reporting was clear in articles from
foreign countries discussing what can or should be done to help
East Germany develop in the right political and economic directions.
</TEXT>
