<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Travel     11-16 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Travel,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovaks Still Must Go To Police for Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens still must have police
approval to travel to the West after the first of the year even
though exit visas will not be necessary, the government said
Thursday.
   Premier Ladislav Adamec announced Tuesday that exit visas no
longer would be required.
   Government spokesman Miroslav Pavel told reporters Thursday the
visa would be replaced by a ``statistical sheet'' issued by police
and valid for one trip abroad.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Jiri Belohlavek told the official
news agency CTK the statistical sheets were being introduced
because ``a record of Czechoslovak citizens' travels abroad is
necessary.'' He did not elaborate.
   Anyone wishing to travel to the West now must apply for exit
visas with Interior Ministry authorities after receiving a
passport. Stamps of approval are required from the local Communist
party branch, the person's employer and the army, so the process
can take up to 30 days.
   Even under the new regulations, Czechoslovaks would have to
maintain foreign currency deposits in banks or present invitations
to visit from relatives or friends abroad, Pavel said.
   Government officials have given no indication that people
previously denied passports will be given permission to travel
under the new regulations.
   The government said Thursday it would cancel weekend trips to
Czechoslovakia organized by state travel agencies for people from
Poland, Hungary, the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia, due to
``excessive purchases'' of consumer goods.
   Rising prices in those countries and shortages of certain goods
make food, clothing and shoes relatively cheap in Czechoslovakia.
   Last month, authorities restricted exports of a long list of
consumer goods ranging from meat to personal computers.
</TEXT>
