<FIRST>u a AM-BoysKilled     11-16 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boys Killed,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Boys Killed by Police Officer Who Mistook Screwdriver For Gun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran police officer killed two
13-year-old boys with a single shotgun blast to their backs after
one of the youths pointed a screwdriver at him and he mistook it
for a gun, authorities said Thursday.
   Thia Yang and Basee Lor, who were suspected of auto theft, were
shot Wednesday with a 12-gauge shotgun fired by Inver Grove Heights
officer Kenneth Murphy, according to Mark Shields, superintendent
of the state Bureau of Criminal Apprehension.
   ``Officer Murphy, fearing his life was in danger, discharged his
weapon,'' Shields said at a news conference.
   However, the killings angered members of Minnesota's Southeast
Asian community, who said Murphy had used unneccessary force. The
boys' parents, who live in St. Paul, are Hmong immigrants.
   Murphy was placed on paid administrative leave pending a grand
jury investigation, which is expected to open in about three weeks,
said Dakota County Attorney James Backstrom. A special prosecutor
from the state attorney general's office will present the evidence,
he said.
   ``The decision on whether that was justifiable use of deadly
force is up to the grand jury,'' Backstrom said.
   Authorities at the press conference declined to answer questions
about why the boys were shot in the back.
   Yang Vang, director of the Lao Family Community of Minnesota,
charged that the police officer had acted recklessly. Vang said his
center had been receiving telephone calls from outraged Laotian
neighbors.
   ``Members are very, very upset,'' Vang said.
   Ge Yang, coordinator of the Laotian center's delinquency
prevention program, complained that Murphy ``should have known how
to deal with those kids (without) firing a gun.''
   The brief chase involving police from Inver Grove Heights,
Rosemount and Dakota County began at 12:31 p.m. Wednesday when a
Rosemount police squad responded to a report of an auto theft,
according to Shields.
   The pursuit continued after the car went into a ditch in Inver
Grove Heights and three boys fled on foot, he said.
   Murphy, a 20-year veteran, pursued the boys on foot through a
field. He took cover behind a hay wagon, identified himself as a
police officer and shouted at the boys, who fled into five-foot
high raspberry bushes, Shields said. The officer saw Yang raise his
hand with what Murphy thought was a gun, he said.
   Murphy was about 30 yards away from Yang when he shot, and Lor
was about 15 feet behind and to the side of Yang, Shields said.
   ``We don't think the officer even realized that (Lor) was in
such close vicinity,'' he added.
   Yang was shot in the back and upper left shoulder by one of the
nine pellets in the shell, severing his aorta, according to the
Ramsey County coroner.
   Lor was hit by three pellets, one in the arm, one in the spinal
column and another in the stomach, causing severe abdominal
bleeding.
   The third boy, a 14-year-old, was arrested after the shooting,
authorities said.
   Le Yang, Thia Yang's 14-year-old sister, said her brother was an
eighth-grader at Washington Junior High School in St. Paul.
   ``It was their fault _ the police's fault,'' she told the St.
Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch. ``They don't have the right to take
out their gun and shoot him. To me, my brother is a nice guy. He
doesn't fool around; he doesn't do bad things.''
   Inver Grove Heights Mayor William Saed described Murphy as ``a
very stable officer over the years.''
   ``It's very unfortunate for the boys, a real tragedy,'' Saed
said. ``But it's a tragedy for the officer, too. Something must
have happened to cause him to do that.''
</TEXT>
