<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     11-16 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUNXSUTAWNEY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Bartlebaugh always wanted to
walk down the aisle with the man of her dreams, but she never
imagined she would do it in a supermarket _ in the generic section.
   Ms. Bartlebaugh, 38, and Russell Marshall, 46, were married
Thursday night in Aisle 3 at the County Market store, where they
met in July 1988.
   ``It's romantic,'' she said. ``We fell in love with each other
on first sight in the generic section.''
   Ms. Bartlebaugh said she was looking for bargains, not love,
when she met Marshall in the supermarket in this small town 70
miles northeast of Pittsburgh.
   ``I was comparing the prices, and he turned around and started
talking to me,'' she said. ``He said, `Don't I know you from
somewhere?' and I said, `Not really.' I was going to buy some soap
powder and then he started talking to me.''
   The bride and groom wore black pants and white shirts, and the
aisle was decorated with black and white streamers and balloons.
The wedding cake featured a universal pricing code symbol painted
in black and white icing.
   ``Last night we stopped at the County Market and a lady said, `I
can't ever find anything in this store,' '' Ms. Bartlebaugh said.
``I said, `What are you talking about? I found my husband here.' ''
</TEXT>
