<DOCNO> AP891116-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nigeria     11-16 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nigeria,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military to Draw Up Platforms for Parties, Register Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling military will dictate the
platforms and register members of the two parties it will permit to
contest elections returning Africa's most populous nation to
democracy, it announced Thursday.
   The moves were the latest by the military to take more control
over the transition to civilian rule. Last month, Maj. Gen. Ibrahim
Babangida, the head of state, rejected each of the 13 parties the
civilian National Election Board had nominated to compete in local
and parliamentary elections.
   Babangida, who seized power from civilian President Shehu
Shagari in 1983 and banned political parties until May, says the
military needs to be involved in even the smallest details of the
transition to civilian rule to avoid tribalism and corruption. The
change-over is set to be completed by Oct. 1, 1992.
   The announcement means the government rejects the platforms
proposed by the civilian election board, which the military had
originally entrusted with registering parties and defining their
platforms. Earlier this week, the board gave Babangida platforms
for a left-center and a right-center party.
   The policy-making Armed Forces Ruling Council said late Thursday
that the party platforms would be written by a council committee
and published within two months. Registration of party members
would begin immediately after the platforms were published.
   In rejecting the 13 parties on Oct. 7, Babangida said none ``had
passed the test as imposed by our vision of a new political order.''
   He said the parties, which had each raised at least $3 million
and gathered petitions of support from the 435 local government
districts, had close ties to past parties that had failed Nigeria.
   Babangida had said the civilian election board would monitor the
election process and polling.
   Babangida said limiting the country to two political parties was
the only way to avoid regional, ethnic or religious divisions. His
government blames factionalism for the failure of previous civilian
governments.
   The general already had banned all former politicians from
taking part, and had extended the ban to officials now in the
government or military.
   Nigeria, an oil-producing nation with a population of 95
million, has seen its economy near collapse from mismanagement,
corruption and falling oil prices. It has been ruled by the
military for 20 of the 29 years it has been independent from
Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
