<FIRST>r i AM-India-Miners     11-16 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Miners,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>66 Miners Rescued After 3 Days in Flooded Coal Pit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers hauled 66 trapped miners to the
surface through a narrow hole Thursday, three days after an
underground flood stranded them in an eastern India coal pit, news
agencies said.
   The search continued for five other miners thought to have been
trapped when water from a subterranean reservoir burst into the pit
100 yards beneath the surface Monday.
   Press Trust of India said the 66 rescued miners were in good
health and had been taken to a hospital for medical checks.
   United News of India said the miners were lifted to the surface
through a rescue hatch drilled to their underground prison in the
government-owned mine near Raniganj. The bore hole was only 24
inches in diameter, and the miners were rescued one at a time in a
specially built capsule lowered down the hole.
   Rescuers had been in voice contact with the miners since shortly
after the disaster and had managed to pass food and water to them
during most of their ordeal.
   The news agencies said at least 1.5 million gallons of water
poured into the pit Monday, blocking the exit shaft of the Mahavir
Colliery 465 miles southeast of New Delhi.
</TEXT>
