<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Strike     11-16 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Strike,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0700 to fix story name</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gov't Company Fires Hundreds More Strikers, Clashes Injure Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed with striking
black workers Thursday and the government-run transport company
fired hundreds more employees demanding nearly 2{ times their
current pay.
   Police said six officers were hurt in two clashes.
   The South African Transport Services said it fired 800 strikers
after dropping 626 from the payroll earlier this week. The company
said the walkout is illegal because rail, trucking and harbor
operations are designated as essential.
   Police headquarters said violence broke out at a railway station
in Germiston, near Johannesburg, when about 50 strikers arrived by
train for a union meeting without having paid their rail fares.
   Officers moved in to arrest the men and were attacked with
sticks, whips and stones, police said. Strikers scattered after
officers fired two pistol shots, according to police, who said
three officers were injured.
   An hour later, three more officers were hurt trying to disperse
about 150 strikers outside a union office in Germiston, according
to police headquarters. No arrests were reported in either incident.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, with which the
transport union is affiliated, said police ``indiscriminately
attacked'' the workers when they got off the train without paying.
   The statement by the congress, the country's largest and most
militantly anti-apartheid trade federation, said police ``brutally
assaulted'' the strikers when they fled to the union offices. The
union said the workers were unable to pay for their train tickets
because they were on strike.
   The dispute centers on a demand by the South African Railways
and Harbor Workers for the minimum wage to be increased to $570 a
month from $230. Other issues in dispute are the union's objection
to possible privatization and the company's refusal to officially
recognize the union.
   The union claims a membership of 40,000 of the total 180,000
black workers employed by the transport company.
   The strike, which has hit mainly the Johannesburg-Pretoria area
and the port city of Durban, is one of two bitter labor disputes
that show no signs of resolution.
   About 6,000 black employees of South African Breweries, the
country's privately owned beer monopoly, have been on strike for
five weeks.
   On Wednesday, the brewery workers' union lowered its wage demand
for the first time, saying it would accept a 32 percent increase
instead of a 38 percent increase. But management maintained its
refusal to change its ``final'' offer of a 16 percent raise.
   Seven deaths have been linked to that strike.
   Police officials also said Thursday that 15 black activists were
arrested for participating in an illegal meeting in Alexandra, a
township adjoining Johannesburg. The meeting followed the
announcement that a magistrate had refused to grant permission for
a protest march in Alexandra on Saturday.
   Organizers hoped 30,000 would join the march to demand new
housing, an end to evictions and the writing off of arrears accrued
during a three-year rent boycott.
</TEXT>
