<DOCNO> AP891116-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil 3rdLd-Writethru a0810 11-16 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0810,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative, Leftist Headed for Runoff in Presidential Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with new results. Picks up 14th
pvs, `The impending...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Fernando Collor de Mello on
Thursday was virtually guaranteed a berth in a runoff election for
president, and two leftist rivals battled for the second spot.
   Official and TV network tallies gave Collor de Mello about 26
percent of the vote and an ample lead in Wednesday's election, the
first free presidential balloting in 29 years.
   With his elegant suits and good looks, the 40-year-old former
governor of the tiny northeastern state of Alagoas campaigned on a
clean-government program that captured the imagination of many poor
Brazilians, most of whom earn less than $25 a week.
   None of the candidates was expected to obtain a majority, and a
runoff between the top two finishers was scheduled for Dec. 17.
   In Washington, the State Department said it was ``a truly
significant day'' for Brazil. Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler likened
the elections to the developments sweeping Eastern Europe.
   ``In considering the spread of democracy into other regions such
as Eastern Europe, we should also take note of what occurred in
Brazil yesterday,'' she said in a statement.
   ``We congratulate the people of Brazil on what has been a truly
significant day in their history,'' she said. ``We look forward to
working with whomever they choose in the upcoming runoff election
to be their next president.''
   Official and TV network counts gave Collor de Mello a wide lead
over radical-leftist Luis Inacio Lula da Silva and rival populist
Leonel Brizola in Wednesday's balloting.
   An unofficial tally by Brazil's largest TV network, Globo TV _
which said it independently counted 57.3 percent of the returns
from the country's 82 million registered voters _ gave Collor de
Mello 12.5 million votes, or 26.5 percent of the total.
   Brizola, of the center-left Democratic Labor Party, was
comfortably in second place with 8.6 million votes, or 18.3
percent, the network said.
   Da Silva, a former union president of the Marxist-oriented
Workers Party, was trailing in third with 7.5 million votes, about
16 percent.
   The government's official vote-counting center, far behind
unofficial tallies because of apparent computer problems, issued
partial results showing da Silva in second.
   It said that with only 20.68 percent of the votes counted,
Collor de Mello was leading with 26.91 percent, da Silva was second
with 17.27 percent, and Brizola was third with 15.91 percent.
   Those were the last official results to be issued Thursday.
   The impending runoff raised the possibility of an alliance
between the leftist candidates to defeat Collor de Mello. The two
insulted each other during the campaign and dismissed the idea of
joining forces.
   Brizola overtook da Silva on Thursday in the Globo TV count.
Network analysts said Brizola's surge was due to a predicted strong
showing in the heavily populated states of Rio de Janeiro and Rio
Grande do Sul, where he was governor.
   However, Globo TV analysts said da Silva, a charismatic labor
leader backed by the progressive wing of Brazil's powerful Roman
Catholic Church, could close the gap when votes from remote
interior precincts came in.
   Sen. Mario Covas, of the left-of-center Brazilian Social
Democracy Party, was fourth with 5.2 million votes in the network
count but was not expected to overtake Brizola or da Silva.
   The Supreme Electoral Court released an official partial result
Thursday night based on only 12 percent of the votes counted. It
showed Collor de Mello leading with 2.4 million votes, da Silva
second with around 1.6 million, and Brizola third with some 1.5
million votes.
   Mauricio Mello, head of the Electoral Court's computer systems,
said the final tally would be announced in five days.
   Collor de Mello, who had led in polls since April, has sharply
criticized President Jose Sarney, calling the 59-year-old leader
corrupt and incompetent, and blaming him for Brazil's 1,300 percent
inflation. Sarney, who by law cannot run for re-election, said he
will sue the candidate for slander.
   The new president takes office March 15 for a five-year term.
   Brazil's last direct presidential election was in 1960, when
Janio Quadros was elected. Quadros quit after seven months in
office, and three years later the Armed Forces took power in a
right-wing coup.
   The generals banned direct voting for presidential election,
although limited regional elections were allowed. Sarney, a
civilian, took office in 1985 in an electoral college controlled by
the generals.
</TEXT>
