<FIRST>u i AM-Kidnap 2ndLd-Writethru a0694 11-16 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnap, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0694,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>American, Two West Germans Safe; Kidnapping Report a Hoax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th pvs, `We are...' to UPDATE with State
Department comment. Pickup 6th pvs, `A statement...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American woman and two West German
friends were reported safe Thursday, the day after a previously
unknown group claimed to have kidnapped them. Police said they had
not been abducted.
   The three sailed from the Christian port of Jounieh north of
Beirut aboard a ferry for the Cypriot port of Larnaca, police and
port officials said. They arrived at the Lebanese harbor and
refused to talk to reporters as they boarded.
   Police said Deborah Fahrend, 54, of San Francisco; Lebanese-born
naturalized West German Mounir Shamseddin Sami, 39; and his
7-year-old son Danjel, born in Berlin, were not kidnapped.
   A police spokesman, whose name cannot be revealed because of
regulations, said the case ``involved a robbery report.''
   ``We are investigating to find out what whether they were robbed
or their passports were just stolen,'' he said, and refused to
elaborate.
   In Washington, the State Department said Thursday that U.S.
consular officials want to question Ms. Fahrend. Spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler said West German officials had told Washington
the three were ``free and safe.''
   ``Our consular officer, wherever she surfaces, will definitely
want to have a little _ meet her,'' said Miss Tutwiler.
   A statement Wednesday claimed a group called The Organization of
Just Revenge kidnapped the three ``because of their activities in
Lebanon.'' The 30-word typewritten statement in Arabic was put in
the mailbox of a Western news agency along with photocopies of
their passports and visas.
   Both the police spokesman and Wolfgang Gottelmann, the West
German ambassador, said Ms. Fahrend and the Samis were in good
health and planned to leave by sea for Larnaca, Cyprus, when
weather permitted. They would not say where the three were staying
in Jounieh.
   The U.S. Embassy in Beirut has been closed since Sept. 22.
   Gottelmann said by telephone: ``They are free. They presented
themselves this morning at the consular section of the embassy
after they had read the reports.
   ``They had not been robbed. They were already back in east
Beirut to return to Cyprus when the claim was issued. They had come
to Lebanon to see the man's family.''
   ``The American lady was a friend of the family,'' the ambassador
said. ``They cannot explain how this happened. I doubted this thing
from the beginning.''
   A Sami family source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the three telephoned from the West German Embassy in east Beirut to
say they were fine.
   According to the relative, Mounir Sami said they were ``robbed
by gunmen'' but ``he didn't say where they were robbed. It seems
those who robbed them also took their passports, photocopied them
and issued the claim hoping to make some money.''
   The photocopies showed they arrived in Jounieh by sea from
Larnaca on Nov. 3.
   Ms. Fahrend's mother, Margaret Brooks, said in the United States
her daughter had planned to write a book about Lebanon and said in
a letter last week: ``It seems to me to be a chance in a lifetime.''
   She said her daughter chose the name Fahrend, which means
``travel'' in German, about three years ago. Her name previously
was Corra, from the husband she divorced about 20 years ago.
   Neighbors said Sami, his son and Ms. Fahrend spent 10 days at
the apartment of his parents in the Bourj Abu Haidar district of
Moslem west Beirut and left on Tuesday.
   ``They told me they were heading for Jounieh to leave Lebanon
and I was under the impression that they did,'' said Ibtisam Malak,
a 40-year-old housewife and neighbor of the Samis. ``I was amazed
when I heard radios this morning saying they were kidnapped.''
   Eighteen Western hostages, including eight Americans, are held
in Lebanon, most by radical Shiite Moslem factions loyal to Iran.
   Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
