<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru a0690 11-16 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says He Will Blame West If Poland Fails</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `At the...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Walesa's
visit to New York. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ```I will...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa declared
Thursday ``the Iron Curtain is no more'' but also said the West
will be to blame if Poland's experiment in democracy fails for lack
of economic support.
   ``If we do not succeed in evolution, a revolution may come,''
Walesa told a packed luncheon at the National Press Club before
leaving for New York on the next leg of his weeklong visit to the
United States.
   Lionized during four days in the nation's capital, Walesa met
with President Bush, addressed a joint session of Congress and
received the cheers of U.S. labor leaders. The president hailed him
as ``America's special guest'' and Congress gave him repeated
standing ovations.
   He also found time to tape a 30-second commercial for the
AFL-CIO's ``Union Yes'' advertising campaign. In the ad he speaks
in Polish, through a translator, until the end when he grins,
switches to English and gives the ``Union Yes'' slogan.
   The taping took about 90 minutes, partly because Walesa had such
trouble pronouncing ``union.''
   In Manhattan on Thursday night, the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize
winner received a Freedom Award from the International Rescue
Committee, a nonsectarian, voluntary agency that runs relief,
medical and resettlement for refugees fleeing political, religious
or racial persecution.
   Past Freedom Award recipients included Winston Churchill, George
Meany, Hubert Humphrey and Elie Wiesel.
   Walesa told an estimated 700 government officials, diplomats,
industrial leaders and private citizens at the award dinner:
``Please care for this country, because this country is a beacon of
hope for people elsewhere.''
   At the press club earlier, Walesa repeated his call for
Americans to invest in Poland to protect the fragile beginnings of
democracy. Walesa said he would not be to blame if the peaceful
evolution degenerates into chaos.
   ``I will defend myself and ... my defense will be as follows:
   ``We have done everything. We have fulfilled all your conditions
and we have stretched out our hands. But there was no other hand to
take it.''
   Animated despite his hectic schedule, the Solidarity leader
bantered with his press club audience and said Polish reforms so
far represent ``a beautiful house of cards'' that will not survive
without ``economic concrete.''
   ``The Iron Curtain is no more,'' declared Walesa, an emissary
for the East bloc's first non-communist led government.
   ``We have fought and we have won. But the victory is mostly a
theoretical victory. I call it a beautiful house of cards.
   ``Any wind could destroy this house of cards. If we want a real
victory we need to build a strong foundation under it by pouring
economic concrete.''
   ``We want to make business deals,'' said Walesa, who met earlier
in the day with Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter and representatives of a dozen American
corporations.
   At their meeting earlier, Mosbacher declared Walesa an honorary
Texan and presented him a white Stetson hat.
   ``All heroes, all good guys wear white hats,'' said Mosbacher, a
former Houston businessman.
   Asked at the luncheon if he had achieved everything he wanted
during the visit, Walesa referred to his one passion outside of
Solidarity _ fishing.
   ``Obviously ladies and gentlemen, you have to remember that I am
like a fisherman. I caught a fish this big,'' he said, first
stretching out his arm, then gesturing with his hand a catch only
the size of his forearm.
   The crowd guffawed.
   ``I talk a lot, I ask for a lot, and of course I already know
that I cannot accomplish everything, that the results will be
limited.''
   But he added a few minutes later:
   ``It seems to me that I am being received with great sympathy
and with understanding. ... So there is a chance that we will
succeed. I hope that the fish will be a larger one than the one I
have shown.''
   Congress was taking steps this week to help finance the Polish
reforms, as the Senate voted Tuesday to authorize $657 million in
economic aid to Poland over three years and $81 million for nearby
Hungary, which also is dismantling its centrally controlled economy.
   The House went further, approving an initial one-year
installment of $533 million for the two Soviet bloc nations.
</TEXT>
