<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-PartyAnimals Adv19   11-16 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Party Animals, Adv 19,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Animal Cracker Maker, Giant Brewer in Dog-Eat-Dog Legal Jungle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owen Ryan envisioned ``Party Animals'' as a fun
way to market wheat and sesame-seed party crackers shaped like
ducks, deer, pigs and rabbits.
   What he got was a dogged legal scrap with beer giant
Anheuser-Busch Inc., which sued Ryan, contending that people would
confuse the crackers with its beer-promoting mascot, Spuds
MacKenzie, ``The Original Party Animal.''
   ``This is financial bullying and harassment, plain and simple.
It's like a bully who goes to a playground and wants to take your
ball because he's bigger,'' said Ryan, founder of Owen Ryan and
Associates, a marketing and consulting company in New York.
   ``Can you believe that pooch can bite so hard?'' he said. ``But
every dog has its day.''
   Anheuser-Busch, which makes 78.5 million barrels of Budweiser
and other beer a year and controls 40 percent of the U.S. beer
market, declined comment through its attorneys and Peter Fowler of
Fleischman Hillard, a public relations company.
   Ryan said the dogfight pits a pipsqueak businessman with five
employees and no mascot against a company with $9.7 billion in
annual sales, 41,000 employees and Spuds, an English bull terrier
who has promoted beer, stuffed animals, beach towels, T-shirts and
hats since April 1985.
   Ryan says he has been unable to market his party crackers
because leery manufacturers want all the legal questions resolved
first, and a protracted battle could last years.
   ``They're using the courts to restrict competition,'' Ryan said.
``This is a free country. My product should have the opportunity to
succeed or fail in the marketplace. We want the ability to market
without this cloud hanging over our head.''
   Anheuser-Busch sued in February 1988 to stop use of the ``Party
Animals'' trademark, arguing that the snack food could be confused
with the products of one of its subsidiaries, Eagle Snacks Inc. In
court papers, the brewer said it ``believes that it will be
damaged.''
   But the courts already have ruled the trademarks and products
are distinguishable.
   ``There is no likelihood of confusion,'' according to a
three-member panel of the U.S. Trademark Trial and Appeal Board,
which dismissed part of the brewer's claim in a summary judgment
given May 30.
   However, the board said a trial would be needed to decide one
remaining question under interstate commerce law _ whether Ryan
ever actually marketed his crackers to consumers. Ryan claims the
issue is a technicality, but Anheuser-Busch has filed stacks of
legal motions against Ryan in an attempt to keep him from using the
name.
   Ryan said he first used his trademark on Aug. 15, 1987. He
argued that the term ``party animal'' was generically defined in
1983 by the Dictionary of American Slang and has been used by Walt
Disney Studios, Tiffany &amp; Co. jewelers and greeting card makers and
by others to describe politicians such as John Tower.
   His lawyer thinks it's a case of a little guy getting into a
corporate giant's doghouse.
   ``Spuds is a pit bull who won't loosen his grip,'' said Jay
Begler, Ryan's attorney. ``The court has already said that people
who see an animal cracker shaped like a duck aren't going to think
of Spuds MacKenzie. But they don't want to let go.
   ``I think this is something the American public can sink its
teeth into, if you'll pardon the expression,'' Begler said.
   Trademarks are jealously guarded by companies that spend
millions of dollars to cultivate symbols so the public can identify
with a product, whether it's beer, cars, fast food or clothes.
   Anheuser-Busch lost a 1984 case after suing the Florist
Association of Greater Cleveland for trademark infringement and
unfair competition because it sold stems with the slogan ``This
Bud's For You.''
   The court sided with the florists, saying consumers would not
confuse beer with flowers. It also said the promotion of rosebuds
did not disparage the beer producer or its product.
   Ryan has promised to keep fighting. He formed a ``Party Animals
Defense Fund'' to help pay his legal costs.
   ``Psychologically, there are times I've just felt blown away,''
he said. ``But this is my livelihood, and I'm just not a quitter.
   ``If that dog wants another black eye, he's come to the right
guy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv19   11-16 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 19,0947</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>No Surprise in US Response to German Surprises</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Berlin Wall went up, the initial
response from John F. Kennedy's White House was as cautious as
President Bush was when it began coming down 28 years later.
   Kennedy was silent, Bush subdued. Kennedy faced a crisis that
threatened Cold War explosion; he had to worry about war. Bush
seemed bent on playing down any celebration of victory for the
West, lest the United States seem to be crowing.
   In both cases, the administrations clearly were taken by
surprise by abrupt moves on the Communist side, one adverse, one
welcomed.
   Democrats have criticized Bush for what they say is too timid a
response now; some Republicans complained in 1961 that Kennedy was
not responding forcefully enough to a Soviet threat that seemed to
imperil western access to West Berlin.
   That access and the freedom of West Berlin _ not the wall _ was
the issue that threatened major East-West confrontation.
   Aug. 13, 1961, was a brilliant midsummer Sunday at Hyannis Port,
on Cape Cod, and Kennedy was headed for an afternoon cruise when
word came that the Communists had sealed the border of East Berlin
and started building a barbed-wire barricade.
   He was briefed by his military and security aides, then resumed
his weekend holiday and spent five hours cruising Nantucket Sound
with his family. His spokesman said there would be no comment on
Berlin.
   Back at the White House the following week, Kennedy put U.S.
forces on alert, ordered a partial callup of military reservists,
and sent 1,500 soldiers to reinforce the U.S. garrison in West
Berlin. He said later that the troops were hostage to America's
intent to maintain access to West Berlin.
   While the United States denounced the border closing and the
barricades that halted a flood of refugees and locked East Germans
into their Communist state, the crisis centered on Soviet demands
and statements that seemed to threaten western highway and air
routes to West Berlin, across 110 miles of East German territory.
   Kennedy sent Vice President Lyndon B. Johnson to West Berlin to
declare that the United States would fight if necessary to defend
freedom there, and to greet the troops, convoyed across East German
territory without incident on Aug. 20, 1961.
   There were to be more Soviet threats to impede western access to
Berlin, but it was not blocked.
   The wall became a symbol of oppression, Western protests a
litany. It went up in 1961 because East Germans were fleeing their
communist country, about 3,000 of them a day. It was reopened this
month by an East German government seeking to stem a new wave of
refugees, and hoping that free travel would persuade many of them
not to flee.
   From Kennedy's day to this, every American president has
challenged the Communists to tear down their wall. Bush did so in
Mainz, West Germany, last spring.
   But when the border was opened, Bush's response was bland and
bureaucratic. It was as though he had decided to play it safe by
playing it down, and overdid the role. He called the reopening a
dramatic happening for freedom and said he was elated, although he
didn't look it. ``I'm just not an emotional kind of a guy,'' he
explained.
   In televised contrast came the indelible image of John F.
Kennedy in West Berlin, calling the divided city a symbol of
freedom everywhere, declaring in a Boston accent that he took pride
in proclaiming ``Ich bin ein Berliner.'' That Kennedy speech was
replayed again and again as the Berlin Wall came open. It was not
an early response to the wall. Kennedy delivered it on June 26,
1963, nearly two years after the Communists walled in East Berlin.
   In the days after the border was sealed in 1961, the
administration accused the Soviet Union of cynically and
irresponsibly sealing the eastern sector of Berlin in violation of
the agreement among the World War II allies.
   ``I don't feel the situation in East Berlin is satisfactory in
any way,'' Kennedy said at a news conference on Aug. 30. ``And we
have made clear that we have _ do not consider it satisfactory.''
   Eloquence came later.
   Bush has said that he will be imaginative yet prudent in dealing
with the new situation in the East. So far the emphasis has been on
prudence.
   The administration has offered to help West Germany house and
care for refugees. There have been no major policy moves.
   Senate Democratic Leader George Mitchell urged Bush to go to
West Berlin to express American exhilaration. The White House said
Bush has no such plans. Sen. Robert J. Dole of Kansas, the
Republican leader, complained about an ``increasing level of
Democratic carping'' at Bush's actions and words on Eastern Europe.
   ``We have no apologies or concern with anything that we've done
at this point,'' said White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
``I would simply say that all the actions that we have taken thus
far ... we believe have been appropriate, have not been offensive,
and have had the desired effect of offering our support without
inciting revolution or other actions that would take the process
backwards.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, was covering President John F. Kennedy in
Hyannis Port, Mass., when the Berlin wall was started.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
