<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0842</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growth of business inventories outpaced
business sales in September, the government said in a report
analysts said contained a warning of growing backlogs due to the
slowing economy.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that inventories held
on shelves and back lots climbed 0.2 percent to a seasonally
adjusted $791.8 billion after advancing 0.4 percent in August.
   Business sales, on the other hand, fell 0.3 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $524.6 billion following a 3 percent gain the
previous month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission will
ask stock exchanges to voluntarily test the capabilities and
security of their computer systems.
   The five-member commission voted unanimously Wednesday to
approve a policy statement calling on self-regulatory organizations
in the securities industry to review their computer systems
periodically.
   The SEC wants the industry to conduct studies assess their
systems' capacity to handle heavy volume and their vulnerability to
natural catastrophes and human tampering.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange is
investigating reports of program-trading abuses to determine
whether rules were violated during days of hectic trading, exchange
officials said.
   The world's largest options marketplace is looking at trading in
Standard &amp; Poor's 100 stock-index options during the Oct. 13 market
plunge as well as on other volatile trading days, CBOE President
Charles Henry said Wednesday.
   The CBOE is the fourth major exchange to search for
program-trading abuses. The New York Stock Exchange, the Chicago
Board of Trade and Chicago Mercantile Exchange are conducting
separate probes of computer-assisted program trading in stocks and
stock-index futures.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury indicted two more Chicago
Mercantile Exchange traders on charges of wire fraud, mail fraud
and violating exchange rules.
   The charges Wednesday bring to 49 the number of people indicted
since Aug. 2 in a broad government probe of corruption at the
Chicago Merc and the Chicago Board of Trade, the world's two
largest futures exchanges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has proposed a broad
overhaul of U.S. liability law, including creation of a federal
product liability statute it said would reduce insurance costs and
help make U.S. companies more competitive with foreign
manufacturers.
   Wendell Willkie II, chief counsel for the Commerce Department,
at an insurance industry seminar Wednesday gave the first public
statement of the Bush administration's plans to seek an overhaul of
product liability laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has removed the ``for
sale'' sign from the world's tallest building, saying it decided
not to sell Sears Tower but to use it as collateral for an $850
million loan.
   Sears said Wednesday it expected to sign by mid-summer a 15-year
convertible mortgage agreement with AEW Partners, a limited
partnership formed by Aldrich, Eastman &amp; Waltch Inc., a pension
fund real-estate investment manager based in Boston.
   The deal will provide Sears with $815 million after expenses and
give AEW an option to buy the 110-story downtown Chicago landmark
at the end of the loan period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling cigarettes ``a form of death,'' Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy has proposed legislation that would give the
government control over tobacco products and finance an
anti-smoking campaign.
   The legislation, announced Wednesday, would call for a total of
$185 million in federal spending next year on an anti-smoking
advertising campaign, grants to states, schools and businesses that
promote anti-smoking programs and money to establish a new Center
for Tobacco Products.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican efforts to cut capital-gains taxes
this year ended when the Senate refused for a second time to choke
off a Democratic filibuster against the proposal.
   A 51-47 vote Wednesday in favor of limiting debate was nine
votes short of the 60 required to end the filibuster. The vote was
the same as on Tuesday, with the same six Democrats joining all 45
Republicans in supporting the limitation on debate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivan Boesky, the focus of Wall Street's
insider trading scandals, reportedly is staying in the Stamford
area with friends during a three-week release from a
minimum-security federal prison camp in Lompoc, Calif.
   The owner of a local convenience store said Wednesday that a man
identified as Boesky in a front-page photo in the tabloid New York
Post ``looked like a homeless person'' and asked about the sugar
and salt content of foods during a weekend shopping visit.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market snapped out of a brief sinking spell with a
rally Wednesday encouraged by declining interest rates. The Dow
Jones industrial average, down 16.18 on Tuesday, rebounded 22.33
points to 2,632.58.
   The dollar ended higher after declining overseas.
   Bond prices rose.
   Silver futures prices soared to six-month highs; pork futures
prices rose sharply; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; and
energy futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
