<FIRST>r f PM-Tungsram-GeneralElectric Bjt   11-16 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tungsram-General Electric, Bjt,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE in Largest Postwar Business Investment Deal in Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a $150 million deal that would
represent the largest postwar business investment in Hungary by a
Western company, General Electric Co. has agreed to buy controlling
interest in Tungsram, a Budapest-based lightbulb maker.
   The deal, announced Wednesday, is made possible by the recent
liberalization of economic and political systems in Eastern Europe.
Hungary has been in the forefront of this trend, throwing out
restrictions on foreign ownership and signaling it is eager for
investment from the West.
   ``This is both an excellent global move for GE and a historic
moment in the reform of Hungary's economic system,'' said John T.
Welch, chairman of Fairfield-based General Electric. ``This joint
venture was made possible by the Hungarian government's policy of
encouraging foreign investment and looking to world markets.''
   Tungsram is one of Hungary's largest industrial companies, with
12 manufacturing plants. Annual sales amount to about $300 million
and 85 percent of its products are marketed abroad.
   Under the terms of a joint venture agreement negotiated with the
Hungarian Credit Bank, GE's Cleveland-based General Electric
Lighting unit will purchase just over 50 percent of Tungsram and
will assume management of the venture.
   The majority of these shares are owned by the Austrian
Girocentrale bank, GE said.
   In addition, General Electric has the option to purchase up to
20 percent more of the shares on condition it accepts the
obligation of doubling the partnership's West European sales within
a five-year period.
   Andras Gabor, president of Tungsram, said Hungary was on its way
to becoming a democracy and developing a free enterprise system,
and that there was no going back.
   ``GE's participation in Tungsram gives us the opportunity both
to grow our lighting business and to embrace this process of
change,'' Gabor said, according to a GE statement.
   The two partners plan to combine their European lighting
distribution organizations into one unit to market both General
Electric and Tungsram products, GE said.
   The joint venture will manufacture and sell products ranging
from household lamps and energy-saving fluorescent products and
high-technology discharge lamps.
   In addition, it will manufacture a full range of vehicle lamps
and a number of special lamps, ranging from miniature halogen lamps
to infrared quartz lamps. GE Lighting said it will assist Tungsram
in expanding its product lines.
   GE also will invest technological resources in the joint
venture, modernize Tungsram's plant and equipment and introduce
Western management techniques.
   GE will provide training for Tungsram management and workers
both in Hungary and the United States.
   The transaction is expected to be completed by the end of this
year, GE said, following negotiation of definitive agreements and
government reviews.
   ``The combination of Tungsram's extensive product line and
manufacturing base with GE's advanced technology and manufacturing
expertise will give us a better competitive position in the
worldwide lighting market,'' said John D. Opie, a senior vice
president of GE Lighting.
</TEXT>
