<FIRST>r f PM-CableTV     11-16 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cable TV,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Propose Controls On Cable TV Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local governments should have the power to
regulate basic cable television fees in certain cases, says a
bipartisan group of senators who have proposed controls on the
cable TV industry.
   Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, the senior Republican on the
Commerce Committee, which handles communications issues, said
Wednesday the legislation was ``to place some check on what is now
an unregulated monopoly.''
   The bill's sponsors, seven Democrats and seven Republicans, said
the legislation was to address complaints about rising cable
television rates in the wake of deregulation and a lack of local
government control over services provided to the more than 50
million cable TV subscribers nationwide.
   The legislation is strongly opposed by the industry.
   ``This bill offers a series of extreme solutions to problems
that are either modest or non-existent,'' James P. Mooney,
president of the National Cable Television Association, said in a
statement.
   As introduced, the bill would:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Empower cities and other local governments to regulate rates
for basic cable TV service in areas where there is no competition
from another cable provider.
   _Make it easier for local governments to revoke a cable
operator's franchise or deny a renewal.
   _Prohibit any individual cable operator from serving more than
15 percent of the nation's subscribers.
   _Require cable companies to carry local TV station signals from
their area, known in the industry as a ``must carry'' rule, and
give local broadcasters some guarantees on their channel placement
by the cable operator. In general, the bill would require cable
systems to carry local stations on the same channel as their
over-the-air position or at the channel location they had on the
cable-TV system as of 1985.
   A 1984 law largely deregulated the cable industry, with rate
deregulation taking effect in 1987.
</TEXT>
