<HEAD>Georgia Pacific May Up Offer for Great Northern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. Chairman T. Marshall Hahn
Jr. said a ``friendly merger'' with Great Northern Nekoosa Corp.
could still take place despite Great Northern's opposition to the
proposal, and that the offering price could be raised.
   Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig earlier this week
rejected the company's $58-a-share offer in a letter to its
shareholders and to Hahn.
   Georgia-Pacific announced Wednesday that it had lined up
commitments for $4.5 billion from 19 domestic and international
banks to fund the takeover of the paper company. The company said
Bank of America, its primary bank since the 1950s, agreed to
provide $1.25 billion of that amount.
   Georgia-Pacific added that banks offered more than $8.4 billion
more than is needed for the takeover. Georgia-Pacific needs $3.3
billion to buy the Norwalk, Conn.-based Great Northern.
   In written answers to submitted questions, Hahn said
Georgia-Pacific's offer was ``50 percent above Great Northern's
market price''' when it was made, ``but we've made it clear that
all terms of our offer, including price, are negotiable,'' he said.
   Hahn added, ``We are disappointed with Great Northern's
misdirected response.''
   If successful, the takeover of Great Northern would be one of
the largest acquisitions ever for Georgia-Pacific, which has used
buyouts to grow over 62 years from a lumberyard to one of the
world's top forest products companies.
   Meanwhile, Georgia-Pacific announced Wednesday it has received a
request by the Federal Trade Commission for additional information
on the company's tender offer for Great Northern. Georgia-Pacific
officials said the company will begin assembling the additional
information immediately.
   Great Northern announced Tuesday it was challenging a ruling by
the Interstate Commerce Commission that cleared Georgia-Pacific to
include Great Northern's four railroads in the proposed takeover.
   Great Northern charged that Georgia-Pacific ``cut corners'' and
engaged in ``questionable tactics'' to get the ruling.
