<FIRST>r f BC-CargillFine     11-16 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cargill Fine,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cargill Fined $754,000 for Allegedly Exposing Employees to Injury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Labor has fined a Missouri
turkey processing plant owned by Cargill Inc. $754,000 for
``knowingly and willfully'' exposing its employees to injury caused
by repetitive motions.
   The fine, one of the largest penalties ever imposed by the
department on a poultry processing company, is the second for
Cargill in a month. The food processor was fined $242,000 on Oct.
23 for 113 alleged violations at a plant in Buena Vista, Ga.
   Secretary of Labor Elizabeth Dole on Monday said the company was
aware of the safety problems at the California, Mo., plant, as it
was at the Georgia plant.
   ``The company fully recognized that employees were exposed to
hazards causing serious physical harm and took little action to
eliminate or reduce the possibility of injury,'' she said.
``Employers must protect their workers from these illnesses and
injuries.''
   The company is contesting the fines, issued after the Labor
Department's Occupational Safety and Health Administration
investigated the plants.
   ``Cargill is committed to protecting the safety and health of
its employees,'' said Greg Lauser, a company spokesman.
   The department contends that workers have been exposed to
``trauma disorders'' in the hands, arms, shoulders and neck. The
injuries are caused by rapid and repetitive motion.
   At the plants, workers cut up as many as 5,000 birds a day.
   Cargill, which has its headquarters in Minneapolis, was cited
for 101 alleged violations at the Missouri plant, which employs
about 520 people.
</TEXT>
