<FIRST>r f BC-L.A.GearProbe     11-16 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-L.A. Gear Probe,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoe Company Reveals Federal Investigation of Import Duties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.A. Gear Inc., the designer and marketer of
popular shoes and apparel, said it has learned it is a target of a
federal investigation of alleged underpayment of duties on imports
from Taiwan.
   The investigation is being conducted by the U.S. Attorney's
office in Massachusetts and involves several shipments of shoes
from Taiwan several years ago, the company said Wednesday in a
statement.
   The company referred queries for details of the investigation to
its New York attorney, John Quinn.
   ``We decline to comment other than to say we're cooperating with
the investigation. We've produced the documents requested,'' Quinn
said.
   L.A. Gear's statement said the shipments were made through an
independent agent before the company opened its own office in
Taiwan.
   ``The company believes it has fully complied with its
obligations to pay customs duties. The company's counsel has
conducted an internal investigation and, based on advice of
counsel, company management believes it has meritorious defenses to
any foreseeable charges or claims,'' L.A. Gear said.
   The statement said the federal investigation could lead to an
indictment, a civil case for underpayment of duties or no action at
all.
   If the company is indicted and prosecuted, legal opinions hold
that ``the company's maximum exposure would not have a materially
adverse effect on the company's financial statements or its
continuing operations,'' L.A. Gear said.
   Founded as a retail store in Los Angeles in 1983, L.A. Gear now
markets athletic and athletic-style shoes, apparel and accessories
in more than 90 countries. It describes itself as the third-largest
athletic footwear company in the United States.
   Sales in 1983 totaled $4.5 million. Since then, annual sales
have grown rapidly, reaching $235.6 million in the first six months
of 1989.
   Pop music superstar Michael Jackson recently announced an
agreement with L.A. Gear to design and market a signature line of
fashion sneakers.
</TEXT>
