<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FederalInsurance-Credit     11-16 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Federal Insurance-Credit,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Loans, Guarantees Increase Tenfold</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Lead not planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government loans or insures
$20,000 for every man, woman and child in the country _ a total of
$5 trillion _ congressional auditors say in reporting a 10-fold
expansion of such programs in the past 13 years.
   ``While the government will undoubtedly not be required to
provide financial assistance for its total exposure associated with
these programs, its continuing and growing exposure to losses
cannot be ignored,'' the General Accounting Office says.
   Nonetheless, the congressional watchdog agency said in a report
prepared for a hearing today before a House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee, it ``is apparent that federal financial assistance
beyond that already provided will be needed to pay for growing
losses.''
   Future taxpayers already have been tapped through a farm credit
rescue and two savings and loan bailouts in the past three years to
absorb tens of billions of dollars in federal loan and insurance
losses.
   Additional billions of dollars in losses _ many of them not even
discovered yet _ exist in other government credit and insurance
programs, the GAO said.
   ``Not every program is in trouble,'' said Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., who requested the study as the subcommittee's chairman.
``But some are in a serious enough state to be cause for concern.''
   Dingell said the potential liabilities make the $14 billion to
$16 billion in fiscal 1990 budget cuts being sought by Congress
``look like pocket change.''
   ``In effect, every single American has co-signed a note for
$20,000,'' he said.
   From 1985 to 1988 losses on direct loans written off by the
government increased 1,700 percent _ from $1.2 billion to $21.2
billion _ and delinquent loans rose by 33 percent, from $14.6
billion to $19.5 billion last year.
   An even bigger potential for losses exists in the loan guarantee
programs that deficit-conscious Congresses and presidents found
attractive this decade for keeping the potential liabilities off
the government's balance sheet, the GAO said.
   ``Many newer guarantee programs such as those for education and
energy conservation involve loans with little or no marketable
property as security,'' the auditors said.
   Others, such as those for small businesses that cannot otherwise
get credit in the private market, can quickly turn sour upon
industry downturns and other changes in the economy, they added.
   As an example, the GAO cited the Department of Education's
student loan guarantee program, which has grown from $26.5 billion
in 1983 to $47.6 billion last year. Reported defaults on student
loans have almost tripled during the same time, from $486 million
in 1983 to $1.4 billion in 1988.
   Altogether, a wide variety of loan guarantee programs have
increased by 51 percent over the past five years to $550 billion.
Annual defaults on those federally guaranteed loans have jumped by
138 percent, from $4.7 billion in 1983 to $11.2 billion last year,
the GAO said.
   The real situation could be even worse, the agency said. Just
two months ago GAO auditors found $4.2 billion in Federal Housing
Administration loan defaults in 1988 _ five times what the agency
reported.
   ``The full magnitude of the government's losses under its credit
assistance and insurance programs is not known,'' the GAO said.
``Because of long-standing deficiencies in financial managements
and inconsistencies in the application of accounting principles by
federal agencies, losses are not always being recorded or reported
when they occur.''
   In addition to the $550 billion in loan guarantees and another
$222 billion in outstanding direct loans, the government also is
liable for $3.6 trillion in insurance commitments, most of it
covering deposits in banks, S&amp;Ls and credit unions.
   Loans by government-sponsored enterprises, such as the Federal
National Mortgage Association, or Fannie Mae, and the Federal Home
Loan Mortgage Corp., Freddie Mac, total $656 billion, up from $15
billion in 1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Heileman     11-16 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heileman,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heileman Chief Says Loan Waiver Gives Brewer to June to Reorganize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The G. Heileman Brewing Co. has reached
agreements with creditors that will give it until next June to
rebound from a declining market share and sales, the company said.
   Heileman was given a waiver on its loans from U.S. and Canadian
banks, company President Murray Cutbush said Wednesday. The
agreements will allow the brewer to realize benefits from spending
on capital improvements and marketing in 1989, he said.
   In an interview published Wednesday in The Milwaukee Journal,
Cutbush responded to a report in Australia that Heileman may not be
able to continue as a going concern.
   An auditor for Heileman's owner, Bond Corp. Holdings Ltd. of
Australia, said in Bond's annual report that cash flow from
Heileman's operations was not projected to be enough to make
principal payments on Heileman's long-term debt in fiscal 1990.
   ``These factors raise substantial doubt about (Heileman's)
ability to continue as a going concern,'' the report said.
   Cutbush said that while the company's 1989 performance was less
than satisfactory, price increases and marketing and capital
expenditures during the year were made for the long term, not just
for one year.
   Heileman could have spent nothing during 1989 and ended the year
with a better record, he said, ``but that was not the view we
took.''
   Heileman spent money on capital improvements and new advertising
and marketing efforts, including the development of new
commercials, all of which ultimately will benefit the brewing
operation, said Cutbush.
   The expenditures were painful, he said, but ``done with the
long-term future of Heileman in mind.''
   In addition, Heileman closed three breweries, including a large
one in Perry, Ga., and those moves will reduce significantly the
brewery's overhead, Cutbush said. The other two breweries closed
are in Evansville, Ind., and Belleville, Ill.
   ``We will realize those benefits in the following years,'' he
said.
   Since May, Heileman has been trading profitably, in part because
of price increases for its premium beers for the first time in
years, Cutbush said.
   ``We have seen a significant benefit from the large expenditure
for marketing,'' he said.
   Bond bought Heileman in 1987, just weeks before the stock market
crashed, for about $1.3 billion, and reportedly still owes about
$850 million after selling the profitable Heileman Baking Co. and
other Heileman subsidiaries.
   Analysts have said Bond paid too much for Heileman and cannot
service the debt with Heileman earnings.
   The audit of Bond Corp., which is controlled by Australian
financier Alan Bond, was done in Perth, Australia, by Terry
Underwood, a partner in investment firm Arthur Andersen &amp; Co.
   The audit also cast doubt on the value of some of the Australian
concerns assets, including real estate and media properties around
the world.
   Last month, Bond reported losses of $773.9 million in the fiscal
year ending in June, and the auditors report said those losses are
continuing.
   Underwood said the Bond groups liabilities exceeded assets by
$1.36 billion in Australian dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
