<FIRST>r f PM-JournalistsFellowship     11-16 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Journalists Fellowship,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Times Offers Fellowship at Columbia Law School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times will sponsor a one-year,
$25,000 fellowship beginning in 1990 for journalists to study law
at Columbia University.
   The program will be open to working reporters or editors at any
U.S. newspaper or magazine, The New York Times Company said in a
statement Wednesday.
   The $25,000 fellowship will cover the costs of tuition and
university housing. The journalist's employer will be asked to
offer support through a salaried leave of absence, the statement
said.
   The program's first fellow will be selected in the spring of
1990 and will start the fall semester of that year.
   The grant for mid-career print journalists was created to
commemorate the 25th anniversary of the Supreme Court's decision in
``New York Times vs. Sullivan.'' The landmark First Amendment case
established ``actual malice'' as the legal basis for public
officials to recover damages for libel.
</TEXT>
