<FIRST>r f PM-Obit-Deramus     11-16 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Deramus,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman of Kansas City Southern Dies At Age 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William N. Deramus III, chairman of
Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. and once the youngest man to
head a railroad company has died. He was 73.
   Deramus, who took over as head of Kansas City Southern in 1961,
died Wednesday at Truman Medical Center after being rushed there
from his office in downtown Kansas City.
   ``He was one of our finest,'' said Donald J. Hall, chairman of
Hallmark Cards Inc. Hall said he worked with Deramus on civic
activities thoughout the years. ``He was a very generous soul and
an important Kansas Citian.''
   Deramus, who headed Kansas City Southern _ a diversified holding
company with major businesses in railroads and trucking _ during
its era of expansion and diversification, also was active in Kansas
City civic affairs.
   He was named Kansas Citian of the Year in 1985 by the Chamber of
Commerce of Greater Kansas City.
   Deramus was prononunced dead at Truman Medical Center on
Wednesday afternoon, but a cause of death was not released.
   ``He died suddenly at his desk, doing business,'' said Landon H.
Rowland, Kansas City Southern's president and chief executive
officer.
   Information regarding services had not been released late
Wednesday.
   Deramus, whose father joined Kansas City Southern in 1909 as
telegrapher in Pittsburg, Kan., began his railroad career in 1939
on the Wabash Railroad after receiving a law degree from Harvard
University. In 1949 at age 33, he became the youngest railroad
chief when he was named president of the old Chicago, Great Western
Railway.
   Deramus was credited with building up the struggling railroad,
and Chicago, Great Western reported a record profit of $3.4 million
in 1956. The next year, Deramus took over another line with
financial troubles, the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad. The
railroad, better known as the Katy, rebounded during Deramus' four
years of leadership.
   In 1961, Deramus was elected president of the Kansas City
Southern Railway Co. and its subsidiary, Louisiana &amp; Arkansas
Railway Co. Deramus succeeded his father, William N. Deramus.
   Deramus established Kansas City Southern Industries as a holding
company in the early 1960s. It was one of the first of its kind in
the railroad industry, and it expanded into fields such as life
insurance, real estate, broadcasting and data processing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
