<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MerrillLynch-SouthAfrica     11-16 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Merrill Lynch-South Africa,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merrill Lynch Severs All Ties to South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. is banning all business
related to South Africa, including trading or researching South
African securities, according to a published report today.
   The move by the country's biggest brokerage goes further than
similar policies of other securities firms and could encourage
others to take a tougher stance to protest South Africa's practices
of racial separation, The Wall Street Journal reported.
   The story appeared on a day when the South African government
announced the repeal of a major segregation law, called the
Separate Amenities Act.
   President F.W. de Klerk said the government will open all
whites-only beaches to blacks and repeal the law allowing local
authorities to segregate public facilities.
   Merrill Lynch's move, announced in an internal memorandum to
employees, reflects growing public outcry that Wall Street firms
continue to maintain ties to South Africa, the Journal said.
   Other financial firms, such as Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
already don't do business with South Africa, its corporations and
individuals.
   The sweeping new policies reportedly mean Merrill Lynch will no
longer do securities research on South African companies and won't
offer investment recommendations on their stocks.
   Also, Merrill Lynch will no longer handle the buying or selling
of South African shares for customers. This extends to American
depositary receipts for South African stocks plus warrants and
other instruments. An ADR is a vehicle for U.S. investors to trade
in foreign securities.
   Researchers at Merrill Lynch will keep track of certain South
African industries, such as gold mining, but won't comment on
individual companies, the newspaper said.
   A spokesman for Merrill Lynch did not immediately return a
telephone call seeking comment on the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
