<SECOND>PM-Coke-Pepsi,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Dig at Coke's Hometown; Offends Some in Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cola wars have entered a new dimension, with
rivals Coca-Cola and Pepsi Cola now in a fizz over the merits of
each other's hometown.
   Pepsi, based in Purchase, N.Y., recently took a swipe at Coke's
home base, Atlanta, in a handout to business students on an
employment recruiting trip to Northwestern University.
   The handout compared the relative merits of New York and Atlanta.
   The ``Pepsi Raffle'' challenge asked the students to match
statements with the correct city.
   On food, for example, it asked which city offers ``any food in
the world'' and which one has ``fat backs and grits?'' For
recreation, which one offers ``yachting'' or ``cow tipping?'' On
culture, which has the ``Metropolitan Museum of Art'' vs. the
``Stone Mountain Civil War Museum?''
   Coca-Cola issued a relatively restrained response this week:
``We're proud to call Atlanta home. What is cow tipping anyway?''
   But Gerald Bartels, president of Atlanta's Chamber of Commerce,
was a little more offended. ``I always thought of New Yorkers as
sophisticates and erudites. I'm surprised they would display their
naivete and ignorance so publicly.''
