<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Unemployment     11-16 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Unemployment,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unemployment Below 6 percent for First Time Since 1980</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate
fell below 6 percent for the first time since October 1980, the
government announced Thursday.
   It stood at 1.674 million, or 5.9 percent, in October, its 39th
consecutive monthly decline and down 1.7 percentage points from a
year ago, Employment Secretary Norman Fowler said.
   The opposition Labor Party, which claims the government is
massaging the figures by removing various categories from the
definition of unemployed, said the underlying trend gave cause for
``deep concern.''
   The party's employment spokesman, Tony Blair, said: ``Britain
will now end the 1980s with over 1.6 million unemployed, even on
the government's statistics, leaving many people facing the
prospect of yet another Christmas without a job, and thousands more
fearful of their job prospects at a time of high interest rates.''
   Fowler said Britain had the third lowest unemployment rate in
the 12-nation European Economic Community, and added that the rate
in Britain had fallen faster than in other Western industrialized
nations.
   But he warned that pay increases were averaging 9.1 percent,
well above the EEC mean of 6 percent. ``These kind of pay
settlements can only make us less competitive and therefore harm
future job prospects,'' he said.
   The highest regional level of joblessness was in Northern
Ireland, at 14.4 percent, followed by northern England at 8.9
percent, according to the government figures. The lowest level was
3.2 percent in eastern England.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
