<FIRST>u f PM-CommoditiesProbe 1stLd-Writethru f0047 11-16 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0047,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Merc Traders Indicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Newly indicted...'' to CORRECT to 45, sted
46; picks up 4th graf, `Both are....'' Also SUBS 11th graf, ``In all...''
to CORRECT total of those indicted to 48 sted 49; picks up 12th graf: ``Of
the''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Swiss-franc traders at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange have been indicted as part of a sweeping
federal probe of corruption at the world's two largest futures
exchanges.
   The indictments, on charges of wire and mail fraud, and
violating commodity exchange laws, were announced Wednesday by U.S.
Attorney Anton Valukas as part of a long-range investigation by
federal authorities of the Mercantile Exchange and the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Newly indicted were David Zatz of Chicago and Danny Scheck of
Skokie. They are the first traders to be indicted in connection
with the investigation since Aug. 2, when federal prosecutors
announced charges against 45 traders and one clerk.
   Both are charged with multiple counts of mail and wire fraud,
and violating the Commodity Exchange Act.
   Scheck's lawyer, Harvey Silets, said his client would fight the
accusations.
   ``We believe he will be fully vindicated and that the charges
will not result in any conviction because he's innocent,'' Silets
said.
   Zatz' attorney, Alan Blumenthal, said that although he had not
yet examined the indictment, ``we intend to go to trial.''
   Also named in the indictment was Robert Mosky, 33, of Chicago,
who had been charged previously in the probe. However, Wednesday's
indictment supercedes the previous one.
   The indictment increased to 80 from 63 the number of counts
against Mosky, who is charged with racketeering conspiracy, wire
fraud and mail fraud, and violations of the Commodity Exchange Act.
   Mosky's attorney, Jerry Samuels, said his client ``emphatically
denies any wrongdoing.''
   In all, 48 people have been charged in the investigation.
   Of the 46 others previously indicted, 13 have pleaded guilty, 30
have pleaded innocent and three have yet to be arraigned.
   The new indictment came just two days after Valukas, who
directed the investigation, announced he plans to resign next month
as federal prosecutor for northern Illinois to return to private
practice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
