<DOCNO> AP891116-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-World-Steel     11-16 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-World-Steel,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Steel Output Fell In October From Year-Earlier Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude steel output in the non-Communist
world fell 4.6 percent in October from the corresponding
year-earlier month, the International Iron and Steel Institute said
Thursday.
   It dropped from 41.6 million tons in October last year to 39.7
million tons last month, Brussels-based IISI said.
   The decline was led by Japan where production fell 10 percent to
8.4 million tons. In the European Community, it fell 4.3 percent to
11.8 million tons and in the U.S., it dropped 4.1 percent to 7.25
million tons.
   In the first 10 months of 1989, steel output of non-Communist
countries rose 1.9 percent to 401.8 million tons from the
corresponding year-earlier period, IISI said.
   Its report covers 62 percent of world steel production.
</TEXT>
