<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern     11-16 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carrier Struggling to Rebuild Keeps Low Winter Fares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A move by money-losing Eastern Airlines to woo more
passengers by keeping cut-rate fares to Florida this winter has
been matched by Pan American World Airways, Eastern's closest
competitor in its Miami home market.
   After Eastern announced plans to continue its cheaper fares,
Midway Airlines also announced it will retain similar discount
fares on some seats. American Airlines and Delta Air Lines, the top
carrier out of Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood Airport, are studying the
lower rates.
   ``The existing fare structure...is a fare structure that is
doing nothing to stimulate travel into Florida,'' George Brennan,
Eastern's vice president for marketing, said Wednesday. ``Our
objective obviously is to make money.''
   ``We know a lot about Florida and how to stimulate travel,''
Brennan said. ``We have an awful lot of seats coming into Florida
this winter.''
   With relatively few restrictions, the fares go into effect
immediately for travel between nine Florida cities and 45 other
U.S. cities.
   While the airline industry normally boosts winter season fares
to vacation points such as Florida, Brennan said most of those
flying to the Sunshine State are discretionary, or leisure,
travelers and Eastern must offer incentives.
   ``It is used more as a marketing tool to attract attention,''
said Robert Joedicke, an airline analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton. ``It's calculated to create a loss, but it's calculated to
regain critical mass, or market share. (Eastern must) be
particularly active to win people back.''
   A Miami-to-New York fare, based on roundtrip purchase, would be
$99 each way midweek, compared with a current price of $139.
   Eastern in many cases is maintaining discount fares aimed at
regaining market share lost since the airline was hit March 4 by a
strike and entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization five days
later.
   Passengers must make reservations before Dec. 15, and purchase
their tickets _ if space is available _ seven days in advance.
Tickets are fully refundable, Brennan said. Reservations can be
made through 1990, and will be honored with seven-day advance
purchase.
   A two-night stay is required for the fares, but the discounts
are not limited to the weekend, according to Brennan. Normal fares
apply during the blackout dates Dec. 21-26 southbound (into
Florida) and Jan. 1-3 northbound (out of Florida).
   A slightly higher fare structure is to become effective Jan. 6,
offering discounts still below industry norms, but about $20 higher
each way than the bargain fares.
   Miami-based Eastern currently flies 335 flights in and out of
nine Florida cities: Miami, Fort Lauderdale, West Palm Beach,
Tampa, Orlando, Daytona Beach, Sarasota, Fort Myers, and Melbourne.
   The Eastern announcement came after last week's third-quarter
report showed losses of $185.2 million, with indications creditors
have been told of the carrier's cash shortfall.
   Eastern officials are trying to rebuild without the unions. They
have said the airline will emerge from bankruptcy in early 1990 at
nearly 90 percent its pre-strike size.
   The airline has 775 daily flights. It had nearly 1,100 before
the strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
