<FIRST>u f PM-AFL-CIOConvention 1stLd-Writethru f0027 11-16 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Debate Undermines Labor's Week of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 9 grafs new to include quotes from Cowell; picks up 7th
graf pvs, If pro-choice ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO was urged today to adopt a
pro-choice stance in the national debate over abortion, an issue
that has sharply divided labor leaders gathered to celebrate their
unity.
   The sponsors of six resolutions calling on the federation to
take a pro-choice position agreed to put the issue to further study
in exchange for a debate on the subject today, the final day of a
gathering highlighted by speeches by Polish Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa and President Bush.
   Nine speakers, including two men, spoke in favor of adopting a
pro-choice stance before the issue was referred to the Executive
Council for study. No one spoke against the resolutions, although
pro-life forces within the labor movement are expeated to lobby the
council heavily for their position.
   ``The labor movement must choose sides and lead as we always
have,'' Susan Cowell, vice president of the International Ladies
Garment Workers Union, said in urging the federation's Executive
Council to study the issue quickly and endorse a pro-choice stance.
   ``We did not choose this issue,'' she said. ``The Reagan court
has forced us to take on this issue. Labor cannot stand on the
sidelines.''
   The abortion issue has proved a divisive one for a number of
reasons, pitting traditional labor factions that long have
advocated staying neutral against a vocal coalition of women labor
activists demanding that the federation take a stand.
   Those women say going on the record against last year's Supreme
Court decision expanding state's rights to limit abortions and
Bush's recent vetoes of legislation providing federal funding for
some abortions would put labor in line with its traditional allies,
including the Democratic Party, and help it recruit women.
   Others, however, argue that a pro-choice stance would hurt
labor's standing among Hispanics, most of whom are Catholic, many
religious organizations and in conservative states.
   Cowell said advocates of the pro-choice resolutions would push
for the federation's Executive Council to decide the issue by its
February meeting and suggest language that would allow it to take a
pro-choice stance while recognizing moral and religious concerns.
   If pro-choice resolutions did come up for a vote, it is widely
believed they would be defeated, leaving labor in an awkward
position at a time most of its political allies are helping
mobilize pro-choice forces.
   ``That's certainly not a bastion of liberalism in there,''
William Lucy, vice president of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees, said of the 800 delegates.
   Susan Bianchi-Sand, president of the Association of Flight
Attendants and a newly elected member of the council, is being
pressed by sponsors of the pro-choice resolutions to lobby the
council.
   In an interview Wednesday, she would say only that the issue
``deserves to be looked at seriously.''
   Her union is on the record in favor of choice, but Bianchi-Sand
said she had not decided whether the federation should take a
position.
   Bush's Wednesday address to the delegates was criticized by
labor leaders because he avoided discussing his numerous
differences with labor. He praised AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland
and the role of the federation in helping Solidarity and other
union movements around the world.
   ``Through the labor movement, democracy is finding its voice,''
Bush said.
   But he steered clear of his differences with labor over issues
ranging from child care to the Eastern Airlines strike except to
say, ``I know we have differences.''
   At the end of the speech, some delegates began chanting, ``Sign
the bill,'' a reference to legislation that would create a special
congressional panel to investigate the 8-month-old Eastern strike.
   Administration officials have said Bush likely will veto the
measure.
   ``He very skillfully avoided dealing with several of the very
difficult issues that affect American workers,'' Lucy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
