<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishTelecom     11-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Telecom,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Telecom Reports 8.5 Percent Increase in After-Tax Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Telecommunications PLC reported Thursday
an 8.5 percent increase in after-tax profit for the first half of
the year.
   British Telecom Chairman Iain Vallance said that despite the
slowdown in the British economy, the company should ``make
continuing progress in the second half.''
   Vallance said the company's domestic investment program ``is
paying off,'' with improved services helping to ``ensure profitable
growth in the future.''
   Profit after taxes rose to 867 million pounds, or $1.37 billion,
in the first half from 799 million pounds a year earlier, while
earnings per share rose to 14.2 pence, or 22.4 cents, from 13.2
pence.
   A 10 percent rise in sales helped offset high interest payments
to finance the company's $1.5 billion purchase of a 22-percent
stake in McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the biggest U.S.
cellular telephone company.
   Overall sales rose to 5.95 billion pounds, or $9.40 billion, in
the six months ended Sept. 30 from 5.41 billion pounds the previous
year.
   Its operating profit increased 9.4 percent to 1.53 billion
pounds, or $2.42 billion, from 1.40 billion pounds a year earlier.
   Pretax profit rose to 1.313 billion pounds, or $2.08 billion,
from 1.239 billion pounds in the first half of 1988.
   Net profit attributable to shareholders, or after-tax profit
minus minority interests, rose 7.9 percent to 857 million pounds,
or $1.35 billion, from 794 million pounds the previous year.
   Interest costs rose 36 percent to 220 million pounds, or $347.6
million, from 162 million pounds due to the cost of financing
British Telecom's investment in McCaw.
   British Telecom bought into McCaw, based in Kirkland, Wash.,
last January as part of its plans to compete globally in mobile
telephone communications.
   The company also owns 60 percent of Cellnet, a British cellular
phone concern. Cellnet is growing rapidly, the company said, and
increased capital spending in that area is planned.
</TEXT>
