<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishSteel     11-16 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Steel,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>After-Tax Profit Up 31 Percent At British Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Steel PLC, Europe's largest publicly-owned
steel maker, said Thursday its after-tax profit rose 31 percent in
the latest six-month period due to strong profit margins and a
lower than expected exceptional charge.
   The company reported profit after tax and minority interests of
332 million pounds, or $524.6 million, in the six months ended
Sept. 30. That compared with a net of 253 million pounds in the
same period last year.
   Earnings per share rose to 16.6 pence, the equivalent of 26.2
cents, from 12.6 pence a year earlier.
   Group sales rose to 2.55 billion pounds, or $4.03 billion, from
2.33 billion pounds a year earlier.
   British steel had an extraordinary loss of 45 million pounds
stemming from future reorganization costs.
   Operating profit rose 35 percent to 388 million pounds, or $613
million, from 287 million last year.
   Pretax profit rose to 423 million pounds, or $668 million, from
270 million pounds during the same period last year.
   British Steel said the six-month period was distinguished by
``buoyant trading conditions and good plant performance.'' But the
company warned that high British inflation and weakening steel
demand might affect operating profit in the second half of the year
and said it would continue its cost-cutting efforts.
   In the past two years, demand for steel products, particularly
in Britain, has soared, enabling British Steel to post strong rises
in profits.
   But Robert Scholey, Chairman of British Steel, said: ``Overall
steel demand is slightly fading after running well over the average
trend.''
   In Britain, Scholey said, ``the company wasn't doing too badly
but that demand will probably go down.'' He said he hopes the
company's prices ``can hold up,'' and forecast that full-year
1989-90 pretax profits would surpass last year's.
   ``It is likely that the weaker market conditions in Britain will
carry over into next year's trading profit, although market
conditions in mainland Europe are expected to remain relatively
strong,'' he said.
</TEXT>
