<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     11-16 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $200.8 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 478 money market mutual
funds fell $200.8 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $363.61 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $3.92 billion increase in the funds' assets
the previous week to a record high $363.81 billion, according to
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 235 general purpose funds fell $354.3 million to $118.79
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds decreased $13.1 million
to $157.39 billion, and assets of 146 institutional funds rose
$166.6 million to $87.43 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.01 percent from 8.07 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.09 percent from 8.14 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
43 days, up from 42 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan associations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to
6.38 percent as of Wednesday from 6.40 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was 5.08 percent, unchanged from a week earlier.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.11
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.16
percent the previous week. Yields were 8.16 percent on 1-year CDs,
down from 8.21 percent; 8.09 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.14
percent; and 8.09 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.14 percent.
</TEXT>
