<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-16 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heating Oil Carries Energy Market Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices advanced Thursday, led by
a surge in demand for home heating oil.
   The December contract for heating oil soared 1.66 cents to 58.79
cents a gallon in New York Mercantile Exchange trading as colder
weather was predicted for many parts of the country. Subsequent
contract months also posted strong gains.
   Heating oil prices are sensitive to changes in the weather. On
Wednesday, warmer weather in the East sent the December contract
0.32 cent lower.
   Crude oil futures also moved higher. The December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, picked
up 19 cents to close at $19.86 a 42-gallon barrel, following a 17
cent gain Wednesday.
   And wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery rose 0.70
cent to settle at 51.31 cents a gallon, compounding a 0.30 cent
rise the previous session.
   Andrew Lebow, an energy market analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc., said a rally in European markets set
the stage for Thursday's domestic gains.
   Speculation that heating oil would be in short supply in the
Soviet Union sent prices higher overseas, and the momentum carried
over to U.S. trading, where seasonal factors also came into play,
Lebow said.
</TEXT>
