<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-16 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warm-Up of Soviet Relations Boosts Grain Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid hopes that the warming of U.S.-Soviet relations
would lead to greater grain sales to the Russians.
   But analysts were skeptical, saying the Soviets already seem
able to buy as much grain as they want.
   On other commodity markets Thursday, coffee prices fell sharply;
heating oil surged, leading the energy complex higher; precious
metals were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   In Chicago, wheat futures settled 2{ cents to 4 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.07{ a bushel; corn
was { cent to 2 cents higher with December at $2.40\ a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with December at $1.47\ a bushel;
soybeans were 3{ cents to 5{ cents higher with November at $5.84\ a
bushel.
   Most of the buying stemmed from comments made Thursday by
Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, who said the expected easing
of Soviet emigration laws would open up the Soviet Union for
most-favored-trade status with the United States.
   Most-favored nations have full access to U.S. markets at the
lowest possible tariff rates.
   The Soviet Union's restrictive emigration policies have
prohibited it from being considered for most-favored-nation trading
status, but the United States has allowed the Soviets to buy
millions of tons of U.S. grain and even subsidized Soviet purchases
of wheat.
   ``The Soviets already buy large amounts of grain around the
world and they probably already buy at their maximum level,'' said
Walter Spilka, a grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   He said the effective ceiling on Soviet grain purchases is set
by their own limited port capacity, not by restrictions on how much
they can buy.
   Analyst William Biedermann agreed that lowering trade
restrictions would not likely increase Soviet purchases of U.S.
grain immediately, but it might in the long term if it means the
Soviets can buy grain more cheaply.
   Coffee futures fell sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange amid nervousness about Thursday's voting in the Brazilian
presidential election. Brazil is the world's largest coffee
producer.
   News of significant rainfall in Brazilian coffee-growing regions
also prompted selling of futures.
   Coffee settled 2.4 cents to 4.12 cents lower with December at
72.89 cents a pound.
   Heating-oil futures surged on on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as frigid temperatures moved into the Midwest and headed
for the Northeast.
   Analysts said crude-oil futures also got a boost from
speculative buying ahead of an OPEC meeting that begins this
weekend in Vienna.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 24 cents
higher with December at $19.86 a barrel; heating oil was .95 cent
to 1.66 cents higher with December at 58.79 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .60 cent to .80 cent higher with December at
51.31 cents a gallon.
   Silver futures climbed higher in a technically inspired rally on
New York's Commodity Exchange, extending the sharp gains registered
on Wednesday. Gold was little changed.
   Gold settled 10 cents lower across the board with December at
$392.70 a troy ounce; silver was 5.4 cents to 6.1 cents higher with
December at $5.595 a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures slipped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
reflecting ideas that Wednesday's gains were overdone. Pork futures
were mixed amid disappointment over the government's rejection of
initial offers from dealers for pork bellies that the government
plans to buy and send to Poland.
   Cattle futures settled .25 cent to .48 cent lower with December
at 74.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent
lower with November at 83.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with December at 49.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .35 cent lower to .75 cent higher with
February at 63.52 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
