<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Pepsi-Atlanta     11-16 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepsi-Atlanta,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Calls Recruitment Quiz It Distributed `Insulting' To Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A job recruitment quiz distributed by a Pepsi
Cola employee was denounced Thursday by Pepsi officials, who called
it ``insulting'' for its digs at Atlanta _ the hometown of the soft
drink maker's chief rival Coca-Cola.
   The quiz poked fun at the eating habits, leisure activities and
sophistication of Atlanta, home of The Coca-Cola Co., comparing the
city unfavorably with New York. Pepsi Cola Co. is based in
Purchase, N.Y., a suburb of New York City.
   The handout, distributed recently to business students during a
Pepsi employment recruiting trip to Northwestern University in
Chicago, asked the students to match statements with the correct
city.
   For example, it asked which city offers ``any food in the
world'' and which one has ``fat backs and grits.'' For recreation
it asked which had ``yachting'' or ``cow tipping.'' On culture, the
choices were ``Metropolitan Museum of Art'' or the ``Stone Mountain
Civil War Museum.''
   Word of the handout surfaced in Atlanta when The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution published a story about the quiz on Thursday.
   Coca-Cola's relatively restrained response stated: ``We're proud
to call Atlanta home. What is cow tipping anyway?''
   Cow tipping refers to a prank in which people attempt to knock
over a sleeping cow. The reference to ``fat backs'' apparently
meant fatback, an ingredient in some Southern dishes.
   Gerald Bartels, president of Atlanta's Chamber of Commerce, was
a little more offended. ``I always thought of New Yorkers as
sophisticates and erudites. I'm surprised they would display their
naivete and ignorance so publicly,'' he said.
   Spokesman Tod MacKenzie at company headquarters said Pepsi
officials still were trying to determine the origin of the quiz,
but they were sure it was the work of a Pepsi employee.
   ``The quiz was a terrible prank and done in extremely poor
taste,'' MacKenzie said. ``It was insulting. We don't condone it
and it is not part of our recruitment strategy.''
   MacKenzie said Pepsi has about 8,800 employees in the Atlanta
area.
   Ron Tidmore, president of Dallas-based Pepsi South, the parent
company's Southern operation, said he received a few calls Thursday
from consumers who had heard of the quiz and were ``upset and
concerned.''
   ``We tried to explain the whole thing was done in poor taste,''
Tidmore said.
   ``I was upset when I heard about it myself,'' said Tidmore, a
native of Columbiana, Ala., and a graduate of the University of
Georgia. ``Whoever did it obviously has never spent any time in the
South.''
   He said the person responsible would be ``dealt with,'' but he
would not say if the person would be fired. ``It was just bad
judgement. It probably was a very junior level person who did
something they thought was cute and didn't understand the
ramifications,'' Tidmore said.
   Tidmore said the company did not plan to run advertisements
apologizing for the incident because that would only attract more
attention to it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891116-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   11-16 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carrier Reports Good Response, Competitors Matching</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS new grafs 5-6 to UPDATE with Texas Air announcing jet order
for Continental; picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, Matell said ...; SUBS 10th
graf pvs to ADD name of Pan Am spokeswoman; picks up 11th graf pvs bg'ng,
``We certainly ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Continental Jets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines reported quick and heavy response
Thursday to its cut-rate winter air fares to Florida, and two
competitors matched the rebuilding carrier's new fares.
   Pan American World Airways, a major competitor in Florida and
second to Eastern in Miami service, immediately matched Eastern's
fares, as did Midway Airlines. Officials at two other key
competitors in Florida, Delta Air Lines and American Airlines, said
they were still considering responses.
   Eastern, losing some $2 million a day as it struggles to
overcome an 8-month-old strike and emerge from Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization, on Wednesday moved to build up its
passenger base by offering fares as low as $79 one way in Florida
during the peak winter travel season.
   ``Our agents are experiencing very, very heavy call volume,''
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said. ``It started last night and is
continuing today.''
   In a separate development Thursday, Texas Air Corp. announced
that Eastern's sister carrier Continental Airlines has agreed to
buy 40 foreign-made Airbus jets in a deal valued at about $4.5
billion.
   The move is the latest example of parent company Texas Air
building up Continental to the detriment of money-losing Eastern,
pilots union spokesman Skip Orr charged.
   Matell said Eastern officials knew they could be triggering a
winter fare war.
   ``Let's face it, anytime you file a fare that offers a
competitive advantage you always run the risk of the other carriers
matching,'' Matell said.
   Some independent analysts say such lowball fare promotions do
little to help airlines improve a crucial passenger base _ business
travelers who aren't as responsive to lower fares as discretionary
fliers who fly infrequently.
   But Matell said Eastern is trying to get any and all passengers.
   ``Our approach on something like this is to stimulate traffic
and to generate passengers who might otherwise not have traveled,
given the existing fare structure,'' Matell said. ``We're in the
process of rebuilding our market share because of the strike and
the long-term effects it's had.''
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon in New York said the carrier
felt compelled to match Eastern.
   ``We certainly want to remain competitive in that market,'' she
said, adding that although Pan Am didn't welcome a fare war, ``The
decision was easily made ... We'll match all of them.''
   With relatively few restrictions, Eastern's fares went into
effect immediately for travel between nine Florida cities and 45
other U.S. cities.
   A Miami-to-New York fare, based on roundtrip purchase, would be
$99 each way midweek, compared with a current price of $139.
   Passengers must make reservations before Dec. 15, and purchase
their tickets _ if space is available _ seven days in advance.
Tickets are fully refundable, and reservations can be made through
1990.
   A two-night stay is required for the fares, but the discounts
are not limited to the weekend. Normal fares apply during the
blackout dates Dec. 21-26 southbound (into Florida) and Jan. 1-3
northbound (out of Florida).
   A slightly higher fare structure is to become effective Jan. 6,
offering discounts still below industry norms, but about $20 higher
each way than the bargain fares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
