<SECOND>AM-Warner-Sony, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0289,P012</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner, Sony Settle Dispute Over Guber-Peters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Guber and Peters,
comment from Sony vice chairman. Picks up 8th graf, `Morita said ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. got leading Hollywood producers
Peter Guber and Jon Peters for its newly-aquired Columbia Pictures
on Thursday by settling a dispute with Warner Bros. Inc. in a pact
that includes joint business arrangements.
   The settlement ends all litigation stemming from Guber's and
Peters' acceptance of Sony's employment offer, according to an
announcement from New York by Warner, Sony USA and The Guber-Peters
Entertainment Co.
   Guber and Peters were producers of the highly acclaimed and
box-office hit movies ``Batman'' and ``Rain Man.''
   ``We're excited about the opportunity,'' Guber said in an
interview. ``It's something we dreamed and planned for all our
lives.''
   ``Over the next 120 days our agenda is to meet everybody ... and
to develop our relationship,'' Peters said, calling the deal a
``win-win'' situation for both sides with no animosity. ``We've
left as friends.''
   Warner has committed or invested $13 million in 50 projects
under development by the pair. The settlement included Warner
retaining rights to all unreleased Guber-Peters projects, including
sequels to ``Batman.''
   The settlement, which had been tentatively reported two weeks
ago, was signed in New York by Steven J. Ross, co-chairman of Time
Warner Inc., and Akio Morita, chairman of Sony Corp.
   Asked if there had been a significant hitch that kept the
settlement from being finalized for two weeks, Guber said it was
simply ``the process.''
   ``This transaction held a lot of importance to us and we wanted
to go about it carefully,'' he said.
   Sony Vice Chairman Michael T. Schulhof, who flew to Los Angeles
after the settlement was announced, said, ``We've gotten things
that we think are important to us. On balance, both companies have
done very well.''
   Schulhof would not put a value on the deal.
   In a statement, Ross said, ``The joint arrangements we have
worked out add significantly to Time Warner's worldwide position in
the media industry and help us achieve longstanding strategic
objectives on a global basis.''
   Morita said that Sony believes ``our agreements represent
excellent opportunities for all of us.''
   ``I think out of this you might get a win-win situation for both
parties,'' said Paul Marsh, an analyst with Bateman Eichler Hill
Richards Inc. in Los Angeles.
   Warner avoided getting bogged down in an expensive lawsuit and,
through the joint business agreements, will see profits flowing
back to them.
   ``They were smart enough to say `let's settle and get on with
things,''' Marsh said.
   Sony agreed in September to buy Columbia for $3.4 billion. The
dispute with Warner arose when Sony said it wanted to hire away
Guber and Peters.
   The settlement announcement said that some details would remain
confidential but it did confirm some points.
   Columbia Pictures will sell Warner its 35 percent interest in
The Burbank Studios and ranch, making Warner again the sole owner
of the 144-acre Southern California property. Warner previously
owned the entire facility during its heyday.
   Columbia Pictures will purchase Lorimar Studios in Culver City,
Calif. _ the former MGM lot _ from Warner Bros., which will give
Columbia ownership of its own studio facility.
   Warner and Columbia also agreed to a basic cable distribution
agreement for Columbia theatrical movie releases,
made-for-television movies and mini-series in the United States.
   Warner will also purchase a 50 percent interest in the Sony CBS
Records' subsidiary Columbia House, which is the largest
direct-marketer of records, tapes and videocassettes in the United
States. The announcement said Warner will continue its nonexclusive
distribution agreement with Columbia House and other clubs.
</TEXT>
